The KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven, also known as Communication Tower, is a self-supporting telecommunications tower located in Rotterdam in the Netherlands that was built in 1962. It is the tallest structure in Rotterdam and one of the tallest structures in the Netherlands. The tower is made of reinforced concrete with a metal transmitter at the top and at least one observation deck about halfway up. <S> [["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "instance of", "Telecommunications tower"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "located in", "Rotterdam"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "country", "Netherlands"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "built in", "1962"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "material", "Reinforced concrete"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "height", "Tallest in Rotterdam"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "height", "One of the tallest in Netherlands"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "features", "Metal transmitter at the top"], ["KPN-Zendmast Waalhaven", "features", "At least one observation deck halfway up"]]
The 2011 South Florida Bulls football team represented the University of South Florida (USF) in the 2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season. The Bulls played their home games at Raymond James Stadium in Tampa, Florida. The 2011 college football season was the 15th season overall for the Bulls, and their seventh season as a member of the Big East Conference. This was the second season with Skip Holtz as the head coach. They finished the season 5–7, 1–6 in Big East play to finish in a tie for seventh place. USF failed to qualify for a post-season bowl ending its streak of six consecutive bowl trips dating back to 2005. <S> [["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "represented", "University of South Florida"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "played home games at", "Raymond James Stadium"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "season", "15th overall season"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "conference member", "Big East Conference"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "head coach", "Skip Holtz"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "finished season", "5-7"], ["2011 South Florida Bulls football team", "finished in", "seventh place"], ["University of South Florida", "location", "Tampa, Florida"], ["University of South Florida", "failed to qualify for", "post-season bowl"], ["University of South Florida", "bowl trips streak", "six consecutive trips dating back to 2005"]]
The Times of Indonesia was a daily English-language newspaper in Indonesia, published from Jakarta. Founded in 1952, it was the first English-language daily in independent Indonesia. The founding editor was Mochtar Lubis, who was also the editor of "Indonesia Raya" at the time. Mochtar Lubis had close links to the army leadership. In 1953, Lubis stepped down from his position due to the stresses of his simultaneous editorship of "Indonesia Raya". Charles Tambu, from Ceylon, took over as managing editor of the newspaper.In the aftermath of the Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia revolt, the publishing license of "The Times of Indonesia" was revoked on October 31, 1960. The publication of the newspaper was thus discontinued. <S> [["The Times of Indonesia", "instance of", "Newspaper"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "language", "English"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "location", "Indonesia"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "published from", "Jakarta"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "founded in", "1952"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "first English-language daily in independent Indonesia", "true"], ["Mochtar Lubis", "editor of", "The Times of Indonesia"], ["Mochtar Lubis", "editor of", "Indonesia Raya"], ["Mochtar Lubis", "links to", "army leadership"], ["Mochtar Lubis", "stepped down from position", "1953"], ["Charles Tambu", "managing editor of", "The Times of Indonesia"], ["Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia", "revolt", "true"], ["Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia", "revoked publishing license of", "The Times of Indonesia"], ["Revolutionary Government of the Republic of Indonesia", "date of revocation", "October 31, 1960"], ["The Times of Indonesia", "discontinued publication", "true"]]
Acrocercops orthostacta is a moth of the family Gracillariidae, known from Bihar, India. It was described by Edward Meyrick in 1918. The hostplant for the species is "Sida cordifolia". <S> [["Acrocercops orthostacta", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Acrocercops orthostacta", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Acrocercops orthostacta", "location", "Bihar, India"], ["Acrocercops orthostacta", "described by", "Edward Meyrick"], ["Acrocercops orthostacta", "hostplant", "Sida cordifolia"]]
"Driving Wheel", also called "Drivin' Wheel" or "Driving Wheel Blues", is blues song first recorded by Roosevelt Sykes (listed as "The Honey Dripper") in 1936. It was an influential early blues composition and has been recorded by numerous artists, including Junior Parker and Al Green, whose renditions were hits on the record charts. <S> [    ["Driving Wheel", "also called", "Drivin' Wheel"],    ["Driving Wheel", "also called", "Driving Wheel Blues"],    ["Driving Wheel", "genre", "Blues"],    ["Driving Wheel", "first recorded by", "Roosevelt Sykes"],    ["Roosevelt Sykes", "listed as", "The Honey Dripper"],    ["Driving Wheel", "recorded by", "numerous artists"],    ["Numerous artists", "include", "Junior Parker"],    ["Numerous artists", "include", "Al Green"],    ["Junior Parker", "hit on record charts"],    ["Al Green", "hit on record charts"]]
Gannutz Glacier () is a smooth glacier which flows north from the Bowers Mountains of Victoria Land, Antarctica and enters the eastern part of Rennick Bay between Weeder Rock and Stuhlinger Ice Piedmont. It was first mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960–65, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Theodore P. Gannutz, a biologist at Hallett Station in the 1966–67 season, and station scientific leader at Palmer Station in 1968. The glacier lies situated on the Pennell Coast, a portion of Antarctica lying between Cape Williams and Cape Adare. <S> [["Gannutz Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "location", "Victoria Land, Antarctica"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "flows", "north"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "enters", "Rennick Bay"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "named after", "Theodore P. Gannutz"], ["Theodore P. Gannutz", "profession", "Biologist"], ["Theodore P. Gannutz", "workplace", "Hallett Station"], ["Theodore P. Gannutz", "workplace", "Palmer Station"], ["Gannutz Glacier", "located on", "Pennell Coast"], ["Pennell Coast", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Pennell Coast", "lies between", "Cape Williams and Cape Adare"]]
Gargoyle Ridge () is a high rock ridge forming the south end of the Cobham Range in the Churchill Mountains of Antarctica. It was so named by the Holyoake, Cobham, and Queen Elizabeth Ranges party of the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (1964–65) because of the curiously wind-carved rock buttresses on top of the ridge. <S> [["Gargoyle Ridge", "instance of", "Rock ridge"], ["Gargoyle Ridge", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Gargoyle Ridge", "part of", "Cobham Range"], ["Gargoyle Ridge", "named by", "Holyoake, Cobham, and Queen Elizabeth Ranges party"], ["Gargoyle Ridge", "reason for name", "Curiously wind-carved rock buttresses"]]
Garrard Glacier () is a glacier in the Queen Alexandra Range of Antarctica, draining eastward from the névé between Mount Lockwood and Mount Kirkpatrick and entering Beardmore Glacier south of Bell Bluff. It appears that the British Antarctic Expedition, 1910–13, applied the name "Garrard Glacier" to the feature which had been named Bingley Glacier by Ernest Shackleton in 1908. The area was surveyed by the New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (1961–62), who retained Bingley Glacier on the basis of priority and reapplied the name Garrard Glacier to this previously unnamed feature. The name is for Apsley Cherry-Garrard, a zoologist with the British Antarctic Expedition. <S> [["Garrard Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Garrard Glacier", "location", "Queen Alexandra Range, Antarctica"], ["Garrard Glacier", "drains", "eastward from the névé between Mount Lockwood and Mount Kirkpatrick"], ["Garrard Glacier", "enters", "Beardmore Glacier south of Bell Bluff"], ["Garrard Glacier", "named by", "British Antarctic Expedition, 1910–13"], ["Garrard Glacier", "previously named", "Bingley Glacier by Ernest Shackleton in 1908"], ["Garrard Glacier", "surveyed by", "New Zealand Geological Survey Antarctic Expedition (1961–62)"], ["Garrard Glacier", "retained name", "Bingley Glacier on the basis of priority"], ["Garrard Glacier", "reapplied name", "Garrard Glacier to this previously unnamed feature"], ["Garrard Glacier", "named after", "Apsley Cherry-Garrard, a zoologist with the British Antarctic Expedition"]]
Gatson Ridge () is a jagged ridge, long, that runs east from the southern part of Bowling Green Plateau in the Brown Hills of the Cook Mountains, Antarctica. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names after Karl W. Gatson of the United States Geological Survey (USGS), a topographic engineer on the joint 1975–76 USGS – British Antarctic Survey project to establish control points for Landsat mosaics of Palmer Land, and to establish geodetically tied independent survey nets in the Ellsworth Mountains and Antarctic Peninsula into a worldwide reference system using Doppler satellite control. <S> [["Gatson Ridge", "instance of", "Ridge"], ["Gatson Ridge", "length", "long"], ["Gatson Ridge", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Gatson Ridge", "named after", "Karl W. Gatson"], ["Gatson Ridge", "named by", "Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names"], ["Karl W. Gatson", "affiliation", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Karl W. Gatson", "occupation", "Topographic engineer"], ["United States Geological Survey", "project", "USGS – British Antarctic Survey project"], ["USGS – British Antarctic Survey project", "purpose", "establish control points for Landsat mosaics of Palmer Land"], ["USGS – British Antarctic Survey project", "purpose", "establish geodetically tied independent survey nets in the Ellsworth Mountains and Antarctic Peninsula"], ["USGS – British Antarctic Survey project", "purpose", "establish worldwide reference system using Doppler satellite control"]]
Gdynia Point () is the eastern point of Dufayel Island, lying in Ezcurra Inlet, Admiralty Bay, King George Island, in the South Shetland Islands. It was named in 1979 by the Polish Antarctic Expedition after Gdynia, Poland, a port city on the Baltic Sea. <S> [["Gdynia Point", "located on", "Dufayel Island"], ["Gdynia Point", "located in", "Ezcurra Inlet"], ["Gdynia Point", "located in", "Admiralty Bay"], ["Gdynia Point", "located in", "King George Island"], ["Gdynia Point", "located in", "South Shetland Islands"], ["Gdynia Point", "named after", "Gdynia, Poland"], ["Gdynia Point", "named by", "Polish Antarctic Expedition"], ["Gdynia, Poland", "located in", "Baltic Sea"]]
Chuck Compton (born January 13, 1965 in Atwater, California.) was an American professional football player in the National Football League. <S> [["Chuck Compton", "birth date", "January 13, 1965"], ["Chuck Compton", "birth place", "Atwater, California"], ["Chuck Compton", "nationality", "American"], ["Chuck Compton", "occupation", "professional football player"], ["Chuck Compton", "league", "National Football League"]]
Cape Geology is a low, gravel-covered point marking the western limit of Botany Bay, in the southern part of Granite Harbour, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It was charted and named by the Western Geological Party of the Terra Nova Expedition (1910–13) who established their base there. <S> [["Cape Geology", "located in", "Botany Bay"], ["Cape Geology", "located in", "Granite Harbour"], ["Cape Geology", "located in", "Victoria Land"], ["Cape Geology", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Cape Geology", "geological feature", "low point"], ["Cape Geology", "geological feature", "gravel-covered"], ["Cape Geology", "named by", "Western Geological Party"], ["Western Geological Party", "part of", "Terra Nova Expedition"], ["Terra Nova Expedition", "date", "1910-13"], ["Western Geological Party", "established base at", "Cape Geology"]]
Geodetic Glacier () is a glacier flowing east from Bettle Peak along the north side of the Thomas Heights into Bowers Piedmont Glacier, on the Scott Coast of Victoria Land, Antarctica. The name is one of a group in the area associated with surveying applied in 1993 by the New Zealand Geographic Board, and comes from geodesy, the branch of applied mathematics concerned with measuring, or determining the shape of the earth, and the precise location of points on its surface. <S> [["Geodetic Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "flow direction", "east"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "associated with", "surveying"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "named by", "New Zealand Geographic Board"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "meaning of name", "geodesy"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "branch of mathematics", "applied mathematics"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "concerned with", "measuring"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "concerned with", "determining shape of the earth"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "concerned with", "precise location of points on earth's surface"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "flows from", "Bettle Peak"], ["Geodetic Glacier", "flows into", "Bowers Piedmont Glacier"], ["Bettle Peak", "location", "north side of Thomas Heights"], ["Thomas Heights", "location", "Scott Coast of Victoria Land"]]
Isohypsibius is a genus of water bear or moss piglet, a tardigrade in the class Eutardigrada. <S> [["Isohypsibius", "instance of", "Genus"], ["Isohypsibius", "species", "Water bear"], ["Isohypsibius", "species", "Moss piglet"], ["Isohypsibius", "class", "Eutardigrada"]]
James Higginbotham FBA (17 August 1941 – 25 April 2014) was a distinguished professor of Linguistics and Philosophy at the University of Southern California. He taught previously at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Columbia University, and at the University of Oxford as a Fellow of Somerville College, Oxford. <S> [["James Higginbotham FBA", "instance of", "Professor"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "field of study", "Linguistics"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "field of study", "Philosophy"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "affiliation", "University of Southern California"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "previous affiliation", "Massachusetts Institute of Technology"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "previous affiliation", "Columbia University"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "previous affiliation", "University of Oxford"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "Fellow of", "Somerville College, Oxford"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "born on", "17 August 1941"], ["James Higginbotham FBA", "died on", "25 April 2014"]]
Mount Goldthwait () is a prominent mountain (3,815 m) located 2.5 nautical miles (4.6 km) south of Mount Dalrymple in the north part of the Sentinel Range, Antarctica. Discovered by the Marie Byrd Land Traverse Party of 1957–58, under Charles R. Bentley, and named for Richard P. Goldthwait, consultant, Technical Panel on Glaciology, U.S. National Committee for the IGY, and later Director, Institute of Polar Studies, Ohio State University. <S> [["Mount Goldthwait", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Goldthwait", "height", "3,815 m"], ["Mount Goldthwait", "location", "Sentinel Range, Antarctica"], ["Mount Goldthwait", "discovered by", "Marie Byrd Land Traverse Party of 1957–58"], ["Mount Goldthwait", "named after", "Richard P. Goldthwait"], ["Richard P. Goldthwait", "role", "consultant, Technical Panel on Glaciology"], ["Richard P. Goldthwait", "affiliation", "U.S. National Committee for the IGY"], ["Richard P. Goldthwait", "later role", "Director, Institute of Polar Studies, Ohio State University"]]
The Goodwin Nunataks () are a small group of isolated nunataks lying about west of the Marshall Mountains of Antarctica, at the south side of Walcott Neve. They were named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names after Michael L. Goodwin, a United States Antarctic Research Program geomagmetist and seismologist at South Pole Station, 1960. <S> [["Goodwin Nunataks", "instance of", "Nunataks"], ["Goodwin Nunataks", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Goodwin Nunataks", "distance from", "Marshall Mountains"], ["Goodwin Nunataks", "located at", "Walcott Neve"], ["Goodwin Nunataks", "named after", "Michael L. Goodwin"], ["Michael L. Goodwin", "profession", "geomagmetist"], ["Michael L. Goodwin", "profession", "seismologist"], ["Michael L. Goodwin", "affiliation", "United States Antarctic Research Program"], ["United States Antarctic Research Program", "location", "South Pole Station"], ["South Pole Station", "year", "1960"]]
Gordon Peak is a rock peak marking the northwest end of the Robin Heights in the Sverdrup Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was photographed from the air by the Third German Antarctic Expedition (1938–39). It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by the Norwegian–British–Swedish Antarctic Expedition (NBSAE) (1949–52) and from air photos by the Norwegian expedition (1958–59). It was named for Robin de Quetterville Gordon, third in command and physicist with the NBSAE. <S> [["Gordon Peak", "instance of", "Rock peak"], ["Gordon Peak", "location", "Robin Heights"], ["Gordon Peak", "located in", "Sverdrup Mountains"], ["Gordon Peak", "located in", "Queen Maud Land"], ["Gordon Peak", "country", "Antarctica"], ["Gordon Peak", "photographed by", "Third German Antarctic Expedition"], ["Gordon Peak", "mapped by", "Norwegian cartographers"], ["Gordon Peak", "named after", "Robin de Quetterville Gordon"], ["Robin de Quetterville Gordon", "role", "Third in command and physicist with NBSAE"]]
Eohypsibiidae is a family of water bear or moss piglet, tardigrades in the class Eutardigrada. It contains the following species in three genera:* "Amphibolus"** "Amphibolus mahunkai" ** "Amphibolus markevichi" ** "Amphibolus nebulosus" ** "Amphibolus smreczinskii" ** "Amphibolus volubilis" ** "Amphibolus weglarskae" * "Eohypsibius"** "Eohypsibius nadjae" ** "Eohypsibius terrestris" * "Austeruseus" ** "Austeruseus balduri" ** "Austeruseus faroensis" ** "Austeruseus rokuri" <S> [["Eohypsibiidae", "instance of", "Family"], ["Eohypsibiidae", "contains", "Amphibolus"], ["Eohypsibiidae", "contains", "Eohypsibius"], ["Eohypsibiidae", "contains", "Austeruseus"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus mahunkai"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus markevichi"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus nebulosus"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus smreczinskii"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus volubilis"], ["Amphibolus", "species", "Amphibolus weglarskae"], ["Eohypsibius", "species", "Eohypsibius nadjae"], ["Eohypsibius", "species", "Eohypsibius terrestris"], ["Austeruseus", "species", "Austeruseus balduri"], ["Austeruseus", "species", "Austeruseus faroensis"], ["Austeruseus", "species", "Austeruseus rokuri"], ["Eohypsibiidae", "class", "Eutardigrada"]]
Gould Peak () is a peak standing north of Tennant Peak in the southern group of the Rockefeller Mountains, on Edward VII Peninsula in Marie Byrd Land, Antarctica. It was discovered by the Byrd Antarctic Expedition in 1929, and named by Richard E. Byrd for Charles ("Chips") Gould, a carpenter on the expedition. <S> [["Gould Peak", "instance of", "Peak"], ["Gould Peak", "location", "Edward VII Peninsula"], ["Gould Peak", "located north of", "Tennant Peak"], ["Gould Peak", "discovered by", "Byrd Antarctic Expedition"], ["Gould Peak", "named after", "Charles Gould"], ["Byrd Antarctic Expedition", "discovered", "Gould Peak"], ["Byrd Antarctic Expedition", "year", 1929], ["Charles Gould", "profession", "Carpenter"], ["Charles Gould", "nickname", "Chips"]]
Graptolite Island is an island long in the north-east part of Fitchie Bay, lying off the south-east portion of Laurie Island in the South Orkney Islands of Antarctica. James Weddell's chart published in 1825 shows two islands in essentially this position. Existence of a single island was determined in 1903 by the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition under William Speirs Bruce, who so named it because what were thought to be graptolite fossils were found there. Later analysis showed that the fossils on Graptolite Island were merely the remains of ancient plants. <S> [["Graptolite Island", "instance of", "Island"], ["Graptolite Island", "location", "Fitchie Bay"], ["Graptolite Island", "part of", "South Orkney Islands"], ["Graptolite Island", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Graptolite Island", "discovered by", "Scottish National Antarctic Expedition"], ["Graptolite Island", "named after", "Graptolite fossils"], ["Graptolite Island", "fossils", "ancient plants"]]
Gratton Nunatak () is a bare, linear nunatak lying at the south side of the mouth of McCarthy Glacier, Antarctica, where the latter enters Reedy Glacier. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960–64, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for John W. Gratton, a construction mechanic at Byrd Station in 1962. <S> [["Gratton Nunatak", "instance of", "Nunatak"], ["Gratton Nunatak", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Gratton Nunatak", "position", "south side of the mouth of McCarthy Glacier"], ["Gratton Nunatak", "adjacent to", "Reedy Glacier"], ["Gratton Nunatak", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Gratton Nunatak", "named after", "John W. Gratton"], ["John W. Gratton", "occupation", "construction mechanic"], ["John W. Gratton", "location", "Byrd Station"], ["Byrd Station", "year", "1962"]]
Grautskåla Cirque () is a cirque immediately north of The Altar in the Humboldt Mountains of Queen Maud Land, Antarctica. It was discovered and mapped from air photos by the Third German Antarctic Expedition, 1938–39. It was remapped by the Sixth Norwegian Antarctic Expedition, 1956–60, and named Grautskåla (the mash bowl) because of its appearance and association with nearby Schussel Cirque. It is a very cold place. <S> [["Grautskåla Cirque", "instance of", "Cirque"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "location", "Humboldt Mountains, Queen Maud Land, Antarctica"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "discovered by", "Third German Antarctic Expedition, 1938-39"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "remapped by", "Sixth Norwegian Antarctic Expedition, 1956-60"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "named", "Grautskåla"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "reason for name", "appearance and association with nearby Schussel Cirque"], ["Grautskåla Cirque", "description", "very cold place"]]
John Woolfe (23 March 1932 – 14 June 1969) was a British racing driver from England, who specialised in sports car racing. He was killed as a result of crashing on the first lap of the 1969 24 Hours of Le Mans race, an event which caused the traditional "Le Mans start" to be abolished the following year. <S> [["John Woolfe", "instance of", "Racing driver"], ["John Woolfe", "country", "England"], ["John Woolfe", "specialized in", "Sports car racing"], ["John Woolfe", "date of birth", "23 March 1932"], ["John Woolfe", "date of death", "14 June 1969"], ["John Woolfe", "cause of death", "Crashing on first lap of 1969 24 Hours of Le Mans race"], ["1969 24 Hours of Le Mans race", "resulted in", "Death of John Woolfe"], ["1969 24 Hours of Le Mans race", "event", "Traditional 'Le Mans start' abolished in following year"]]
Hailstorm Island is a rocky island, long, between Cameron Island and the east end of Burnett Island in the central part of the Swain Islands, Antarctica. It was first roughly mapped from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump, 1946–47, and included in a 1957 survey of the Swain Islands by Wilkes Station personnel under Carl R. Eklund. It was named by Eklund for Radioman Kenneth J. Hailstorm, U.S. Navy, a Naval support force member of the 1957 wintering party at Wilkes Station during the International Geophysical Year. <S> [["Hailstorm Island", "instance of", "Rocky island"], ["Hailstorm Island", "located between", "Cameron Island"], ["Hailstorm Island", "located between", "Burnett Island"], ["Hailstorm Island", "located in", "Swain Islands"], ["Swain Islands", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Hailstorm Island", "mapped by", "U.S. Navy Operation Highjump"], ["Hailstorm Island", "included in", "1957 survey of Swain Islands"], ["1957 survey of Swain Islands", "conducted by", "Wilkes Station personnel"], ["Wilkes Station personnel", "led by", "Carl R. Eklund"], ["Hailstorm Island", "named after", "Radioman Kenneth J. Hailstorm"], ["Radioman Kenneth J. Hailstorm", "affiliation", "U.S. Navy"], ["U.S. Navy", "part of", "Naval support force"], ["Naval support force", "part of", "1957 wintering party at Wilkes Station"], ["1957 wintering party at Wilkes Station", "during", "International Geophysical Year"]]
Hales Peak () is a peak rising from the northeast shoulder of Mount Cabeza in the northeast part of Brabant Island, Palmer Archipelago, Antarctica. It was mapped from air photos taken by Hunting Aerosurveys Ltd, 1956–57, and was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee for the Englishman Stephen Hales, curate of Teddington, who first estimated blood pressure, and made important advances in hygiene. <S> [["Hales Peak", "instance of", "Peak"], ["Hales Peak", "location", "Mount Cabeza"], ["Hales Peak", "region", "Brabant Island"], ["Hales Peak", "archipelago", "Palmer Archipelago"], ["Hales Peak", "continent", "Antarctica"], ["Hales Peak", "mapped by", "Hunting Aerosurveys Ltd"], ["Hales Peak", "year", "1956-57"], ["Hales Peak", "named after", "Stephen Hales"], ["Stephen Hales", "profession", "Curate"], ["Stephen Hales", "location", "Teddington"], ["Stephen Hales", "accomplishments", "estimated blood pressure"], ["Stephen Hales", "accomplishments", "made advances in hygiene"], ["Stephen Hales", "nationality", "Englishman"], ["Stephen Hales", "committee", "UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee"]]
Hale Glacier () is a glacier about long, located just east of Mount Simpson on Thurston Island, Antarctica, and flowing southwest to the Abbot Ice Shelf in Peacock Sound. It was delineated from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 in January 1960, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) for Lieutenant Bill J. Hale, U.S. Navy, a helicopter pilot aboard who made exploratory flights to Thurston Island in February 1960.Gould Knoll is a mostly ice-covered rock knoll that rises on the east margin of the glacier, at the point the glacier enters the Abbot Ice Shelf. It was named by US-ACAN after William G. Gould, a National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration specialist, from the 1960s to the mid-1990s, in the archiving of Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer (AVHRR) satellite images of the world, including those used for AVHRR image maps of the Antarctic continent. <S> [    ["Hale Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"],    ["Hale Glacier", "location", "Thurston Island, Antarctica"],    ["Hale Glacier", "flow direction", "southwest"],    ["Hale Glacier", "flows to", "Abbot Ice Shelf"],    ["Hale Glacier", "delineated by", "U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6"],    ["Hale Glacier", "named after", "Lieutenant Bill J. Hale, U.S. Navy"],    ["Gould Knoll", "instance of", "Rock knoll"],    ["Gould Knoll", "location", "east margin of Hale Glacier"],    ["Gould Knoll", "named after", "William G. Gould, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration specialist"],    ["William G. Gould", "occupation", "NOAA specialist"],    ["William G. Gould", "role", "archiving of AVHRR satellite images"],    ["AVHRR", "stands for", "Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer"]]
The 2011 New York Red Bulls season was the club's seventeenth year of existence, as well as its sixteenth season in Major League Soccer, the top-flight of American soccer.After a successful turnaround season in 2010, in which Red Bulls finished in third place overall before losing in the quarterfinals of the post-season tournament, the club started 2011 hoping to find consistency, make a deeper run in the MLS Cup Playoffs, and vie for the Supporters Shield. By season's end it was clear the club failed on all three fronts. Red Bulls were labeled the biggest underachievers in MLS after performing with a maddening inconsistency, struggling even to earn the 10th and final spot in an expanded playoff field, and falling again in the playoff quarterfinals.Prior to the 2011 MLS season, New York Red Bulls manager Hans Backe declared that the club's goal for the season was to win the Shield, claiming that it was more of a test for the league title rather than the MLS Cup, which he called a "crapshoot". As this goal drifted out of reach, Backe backtracked from his Supporters' Shield emphasis and remarkably blamed international call-ups due to the 2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup as the reason the Shield was unobtainable. New York ended the season 21 points shy of the Shield. At the conclusion of the season, Backe acknowledged that he didn't know the biennial CONCACAF tournament was being held in 2011. That lack of awareness seemed to haunt the club throughout the season, both on field and off. The average MLS regular season and playoff home attendance of the New York Red Bulls in 2011 was 20,000. <S> [["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "instance of", "Sports season"],["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "club's year of existence", "17"],["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "season in Major League Soccer", "16"],["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "top-flight of American soccer", "Major League Soccer"],["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "goal", "win Supporters Shield"],["2011 New York Red Bulls season", "average home attendance", "20,000"],["New York Red Bulls manager Hans Backe", "goal for season", "win Supporters Shield"],["New York Red Bulls manager Hans Backe", "reason for not achieving goal", "international call-ups due to 2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup"],["New York Red Bulls manager Hans Backe", "lack of awareness", "2011 CONCACAF tournament being held"],["Red Bulls", "performance", "inconsistent"],["Red Bulls", "playoff finish", "quarterfinals"],["Red Bulls", "biggest underachievers in MLS"],["Red Bulls", "struggle to earn playoff spot"],["Red Bulls", "fall in playoff quarterfinals"]]
Constant Mews (born 1954), D. Phil ("Oxon") is Professor of Medieval Thought and Director, Centre for Studies in Religion and Theology, Monash University, Melbourne. He is an authority on medieval religious thought, especially on the medieval philosopher and theologian, Peter Abelard, and on interfaith dialogue. He discovered and published what are possibly the original letters exchanged between Peter Abelard and his lover, Heloise. <S> [["Constant Mews", "instance of", "Professor"], ["Constant Mews", "birth year", 1954], ["Constant Mews", "degree", "D. Phil"], ["Constant Mews", "university", "Monash University"], ["Constant Mews", "location", "Melbourne"], ["Constant Mews", "expertise", "Medieval Thought"], ["Constant Mews", "director of", "Centre for Studies in Religion and Theology"], ["Constant Mews", "authority on", "Medieval religious thought"], ["Constant Mews", "authority on", "Peter Abelard"], ["Constant Mews", "authority on", "interfaith dialogue"], ["Constant Mews", "discovered", "original letters exchanged between Peter Abelard and Heloise"]]
Western Cattle in Storm is a $1 stamp issued by the United States Post Office Department as part of the 1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue. "Western Cattle in Storm" is one of nine commemorative postage stamps in the series, which marked the 1898 Trans-Mississippi Exposition held in Omaha, Nebraska. While the entire Trans-Mississippi Issue set has been praised for its quality, viewed by generations of U. S. stamp specialists as "one of the most beautiful sets of postage stamps our country has ever issued," the $1 stamp, also called the "Black Bull", stands out from the rest.The breed of cattle used in the issue were meant to represent the ruggedness of the American West, but actually derive from the Highlands of Scotland. That's because the design originated in a John MacWhirter painting (1878) depicting cattle in a winter storm in central Scotland. An engraving of this painting by one C. O. Murray was published at least twice in England, and this image, copied, without the permission of the painting's owner, Lord Blythswood, was used by an American cattle company on its calendar as a trademark of sorts."MacWhirter, however, was a Scot, and his painting, entitled "The Vanguard", was soon discovered to have been a depiction of Scottish cattle in a storm in Scotland," according to a company called Chicago Stamps. "It was actually painted in a small farmhouse near the Scottish highland town of Calendar. The scene did not depict an event west of the Mississippi, but it might have been, and few really cared about this detail, for cattle were an important part of the western U.S. economy." (Note: the correct spelling of the town is Callander.)This image caught the attention of the Post Office Department and Raymond Ostrander Smith, the staff designer of the Bureau of Engraving and Printing at the time, and it was adopted for the $1 design. Little did the designer know that the scene depicted was in Scotland, not the Western U.S., as was supposed. A full apology was later issued to the owner of the painting. Both the frame and the vignette of the stamp were engraved by Marcus W. Baldwin; the numerals and lettering were the work of Douglas S. Ronaldson. <S> [["Western Cattle in Storm", "instance of", "Stamp"],["Western Cattle in Storm", "issued by", "United States Post Office Department"],["Western Cattle in Storm", "part of", "1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue"],["Western Cattle in Storm", "one of", "nine commemorative postage stamps"],["1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue", "marked by", "1898 Trans-Mississippi Exposition"],["1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue", "praised for", "quality"],["1898 Trans-Mississippi Issue", "viewed by", "generations of U. S. stamp specialists"],["$1 stamp", "also called", "Black Bull"],["Cattle breed", "used in", "issue"],["Cattle breed", "meant to represent", "ruggedness of American West"],["Cattle breed", "actually derive from", "Highlands of Scotland"],["Design", "originated in", "John MacWhirter painting"],["Engraving", "of painting by", "C. O. Murray"],["Image", "copied without permission by", "American cattle company"],["John MacWhirter", "Scot", "painting entitled 'The Vanguard'"],["Painting", "depiction of", "Scottish cattle in a storm in Scotland"],["Painting", "actually painted in", "small farmhouse near Scottish highland town of Callander"],["Scene", "depicted in", "Scotland"],["Post Office Department", "caught attention of", "image"],["Raymond Ostrander Smith", "staff designer of", "Bureau of Engraving and Printing"],["Design", "adopted for", "$1 stamp"],["Apology", "issued to", "owner of painting"],["Frame and vignette of stamp", "engraved by", "Marcus W. Baldwin"],["Numerals and lettering of stamp", "work of", "Douglas S. Ronaldson"]]
The Moore Mountains () are a small but conspicuous group of mountains just north of New Year Pass in the Queen Elizabeth Range in Antarctica. They were observed in 1957 by the New Zealand southern party of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition (1956–58) and named for R.D. Moore, Treasurer of the Ross Sea Committee. <S> [["Moore Mountains", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Moore Mountains", "observed by", "New Zealand southern party"], ["Moore Mountains", "named after", "R.D. Moore"], ["Moore Mountains", "part of", "Queen Elizabeth Range"], ["Queen Elizabeth Range", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Queen Elizabeth Range", "near", "New Year Pass"], ["New Year Pass", "location", "Antarctica"], ["New Year Pass", "direction", "north"], ["Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition", "year", "1956-58"], ["Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition", "party", "New Zealand southern party"], ["Ross Sea Committee", "position", "Treasurer"]]
Chernobyl Way (, ) is an annual rally held on April 26 by the opposition in Belarus as a remembrance of the Chernobyl disaster.The first time it was held in 1989 with demands of urgent efforts in eliminating the consequences of the catastrophe. That year, about 30,000 participants marched from LUCH, Minsk Watch Plant, through the downtown to the Square of Independence and held a rally there.In 1996, the largest Chernobyl Way was held in Minsk marking the 10th anniversary since the Chernobyl disaster. It was the first Chernobyl Way during Lukashenko's presidency. About 50,000 people gathered together at the Academy of Sciences and marched on the main street of Minsk (Independence Avenue). There were many clashes with the police, the demonstrators were dispersed by OMON and many political activists protesting against Lukashenko’s regime were detained. Among those detained were journalists and opposition leaders, namely Yury Khadyka, Lyavon Barshchewski, Vyachaslau Siuchyk, Vincuk Viačorka. After this rally opposition leader Zianon Pazniak left the country. Staff of the Maksim Bahdanovič Literary Museum started helping the arrested and their families and this is how the Viasna Human Rights Center was created. <S> [["Chernobyl Way", "instance of", "Annual rally"], ["Chernobyl Way", "date", "April 26"], ["Chernobyl Way", "location", "Belarus"], ["Chernobyl Way", "purpose", "Remembrance of Chernobyl disaster"], ["Chernobyl Way", "first held", 1989], ["Chernobyl Way", "participants", 30000], ["Chernobyl Way", "route", "LUCH, Minsk Watch Plant, Square of Independence"], ["Chernobyl Way", "largest rally held", 1996], ["Chernobyl Way", "participants in 1996", 50000], ["Chernobyl Way", "clashes with police", "Yes"], ["Chernobyl Way", "dispersed by", "OMON"], ["Chernobyl Way", "detained activists", ["Yury Khadyka", "Lyavon Barshchewski", "Vyachaslau Siuchyk", "Vincuk Viačorka"]], ["Chernobyl Way", "opposition leader left country", "Zianon Pazniak"], ["Chernobyl Way", "creation of Viasna Human Rights Center", "Staff of Maksim Bahdanovič Literary Museum"]]
Moreton Point is a point north of Return Point at the western end of Coronation Island, in the South Orkney Islands off Antarctica. It was roughly charted by Captains George Powell and Nathaniel Palmer in 1821, and was named by Discovery Investigations personnel on the "Discovery II" who charted the islands in 1933. <S> [["Moreton Point", "instance of", "Point"], ["Moreton Point", "location", "Coronation Island"], ["Moreton Point", "direction", "north"], ["Moreton Point", "located in", "South Orkney Islands"], ["Moreton Point", "located near", "Return Point"], ["Moreton Point", "charted by", "Captains George Powell and Nathaniel Palmer"], ["Moreton Point", "named by", "Discovery Investigations personnel"], ["Discovery Investigations personnel", "ship", "Discovery II"], ["Discovery II", "year", "1933"]]
Morrell Reef () is a reef reported to lie close off the southeast coast of Bouvetøya, about northward of Cape Fie. It was first charted in 1898 by a German expedition under Carl Chun, and was recharted in December 1927 by a Norwegian expedition under Captain Harald Horntvedt. The reef was named by the Norwegians after Captain Benjamin Morrell, an American sealer who visited the northwest side of Bouvetøya in the "Wasp" in 1822, perhaps making the first landing on the island. <S> [["Morrell Reef", "instance of", "Reef"], ["Morrell Reef", "location", "Bouvetøya"], ["Morrell Reef", "discovered by", "Carl Chun"], ["Morrell Reef", "recharted by", "Captain Harald Horntvedt"], ["Morrell Reef", "named after", "Captain Benjamin Morrell"], ["Captain Benjamin Morrell", "nationality", "American"], ["Captain Benjamin Morrell", "occupation", "Sealer"], ["Captain Benjamin Morrell", "visited", "Bouvetøya"], ["Bouvetøya", "location", "Southeast coast"], ["Bouvetøya", "distance from", "Cape Fie"], ["Cape Fie", "direction", "Northward"], ["Cape Fie", "location", "Bouvetøya"], ["Cape Fie", "discovered by", "German expedition"], ["Cape Fie", "year of discovery", "1898"], ["Cape Fie", "recharted by", "Norwegian expedition"], ["Cape Fie", "year of recharting", "1927"]]
The Moss Braes () are west-facing slopes (s) situated west of Robin Peak on Signy Island, in the South Orkney Islands off Antarctica. They were named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1990 from the extensive moss banks on the dissected rocky slopes. <S> [["Moss Braes", "location", "Signy Island"], ["Moss Braes", "direction", "west"], ["Moss Braes", "named by", "UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee"], ["Moss Braes", "named in", "1990"], ["Moss Braes", "features", "moss banks"], ["Moss Braes", "features", "rocky slopes"], ["Signy Island", "location", "South Orkney Islands"], ["South Orkney Islands", "location", "Antarctica"]]
Moser Glacier () is a glacier flowing into Andvord Bay just southeast of Arago Glacier, on the west coast of Graham Land, Antarctica. It was charted by the Belgian Antarctic Expedition under Adrien de Gerlache, 1897–99, and was named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1960 for German physicist Ludwig F. Moser (1805–80), who in 1844 invented stereoscopic photography. <S> [["Moser Glacier", "located in", "Andvord Bay"], ["Moser Glacier", "located in", "Graham Land"], ["Moser Glacier", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Moser Glacier", "charted by", "Belgian Antarctic Expedition"], ["Moser Glacier", "named after", "Ludwig F. Moser"], ["Ludwig F. Moser", "nationality", "German"], ["Ludwig F. Moser", "profession", "physicist"], ["Ludwig F. Moser", "invented", "stereoscopic photography"], ["Belgian Antarctic Expedition", "leader", "Adrien de Gerlache"], ["Belgian Antarctic Expedition", "years", "1897-99"], ["UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee", "named after", "Ludwig F. Moser"], ["UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee", "year", "1960"]]
Maurice Brantley (born September 19, 1968, in Kansas City, Missouri) is a professional boxer in the Middleweight division. <S> [["Maurice Brantley", "profession", "Boxer"], ["Maurice Brantley", "birth date", "September 19, 1968"], ["Maurice Brantley", "birth place", "Kansas City, Missouri"], ["Maurice Brantley", "division", "Middleweight"]]
Kansas Glacier () is a steep glacier, long, draining northeast from Stanford Plateau, Antarctica, to enter Reedy Glacier just north of Blubaugh Nunatak. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960–64, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for the University of Kansas, Lawrence, Kansas, which has sent a number of research personnel to Antarctica. <S> [["Kansas Glacier", "type", "Glacier"], ["Kansas Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Kansas Glacier", "length", "long"], ["Kansas Glacier", "drains", "Stanford Plateau"], ["Kansas Glacier", "enters", "Reedy Glacier"], ["Kansas Glacier", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Kansas Glacier", "named by", "Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names"], ["Kansas Glacier", "named after", "University of Kansas"], ["University of Kansas", "location", "Lawrence, Kansas"], ["University of Kansas", "sends research personnel to", "Antarctica"]]
36 Greatest Hits! is a 2010 box set by American singer Frank Sinatra. This box set consists 36 songs he recorded for his own label, Reprise. <S> [["36 Greatest Hits!", "instance of", "Box set"], ["36 Greatest Hits!", "release year", 2010], ["36 Greatest Hits!", "artist", "Frank Sinatra"], ["36 Greatest Hits!", "label", "Reprise"], ["36 Greatest Hits!", "number of songs", 36]]
The Toe is a point marking the south side of the entrance to Harmony Cove and the north-west side of the entrance to Varvara Cove on the west side of Nelson Island, in the South Shetland Islands. This descriptive name seems first to appear on a chart based upon a 1935 survey by DI personnel on the "Discovery II". <S> [["The Toe", "instance of", "Point"], ["The Toe", "location", "South Shetland Islands"], ["The Toe", "marking", "South side of entrance to Harmony Cove"], ["The Toe", "marking", "North-west side of entrance to Varvara Cove"], ["The Toe", "location", "Nelson Island"], ["The Toe", "based upon", "1935 survey by DI personnel on Discovery II"]]
Mount Kaschak is a peak, high, standing west of Gambacorta Peak in the southern Neptune Range of the Pensacola Mountains, Antarctica. It was mapped from United States Geological Survey surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1956–66, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for John P. Kaschak, an aviation machinist at Ellsworth Station during the winter of 1958. <S> [["Mount Kaschak", "instance of", "Peak"], ["Mount Kaschak", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Kaschak", "located west of", "Gambacorta Peak"], ["Mount Kaschak", "part of", "Neptune Range"], ["Neptune Range", "located in", "Pensacola Mountains"], ["Mount Kaschak", "mapped from", "United States Geological Survey surveys"], ["Mount Kaschak", "mapped from", "U.S. Navy air photos from 1956–66"], ["Mount Kaschak", "named after", "John P. Kaschak"], ["John P. Kaschak", "profession", "aviation machinist"], ["John P. Kaschak", "location", "Ellsworth Station"], ["John P. Kaschak", "time period", "winter of 1958"], ["John P. Kaschak", "named by", "Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names"]]
Kehle Glacier () is a glacier draining the western slopes of the Worcester Range, Antarctica. It is near Mount Speyer and Mount Dawson-Lambton, and flows southwest into Mulock Glacier. The glacier was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names in 1964 for Ralph Kehle, a glaciologist at Little America V, 1959–60. <S> [["Kehle Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Kehle Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Kehle Glacier", "drains", "Worcester Range"], ["Kehle Glacier", "near", "Mount Speyer"], ["Kehle Glacier", "near", "Mount Dawson-Lambton"], ["Kehle Glacier", "flows into", "Mulock Glacier"], ["Kehle Glacier", "named after", "Ralph Kehle"], ["Ralph Kehle", "profession", "Glaciologist"], ["Ralph Kehle", "workplace", "Little America V"], ["Ralph Kehle", "years", "1959-60"], ["Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names", "named", "Kehle Glacier"], ["year", "1964"]]
Germaine Poinso-Chapuis (6 March 1901, Marseille, Bouches-du-Rhône – 20 February 1981) was a French politician. She was the first woman to hold a Cabinet-level post in the French government. Her political convictions have been characterized as bearing the influence of both Catholic and feminist traditions. <S> [["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "instance of", "Politician"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "birth date", "6 March 1901"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "birth place", "Marseille, Bouches-du-Rhône"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "death date", "20 February 1981"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "nationality", "French"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "first woman to hold", "Cabinet-level post in French government"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "political convictions influenced by", "Catholic traditions"], ["Germaine Poinso-Chapuis", "political convictions influenced by", "Feminist traditions"]]
Kelley Massif () is a rugged mountain massif, long, located immediately west of the Eland Mountains and along the south side of Clifford Glacier, in Palmer Land, Antarctica. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey in 1974, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Captain Hugh A. Kelley, U.S. Navy, Commander of Antarctic Support Activities during Operation Deep Freeze 1968 and 1969. <S> [["Kelley Massif", "instance of", "Mountain massif"], ["Kelley Massif", "location", "Palmer Land, Antarctica"], ["Kelley Massif", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Kelley Massif", "named after", "Captain Hugh A. Kelley, U.S. Navy"], ["Captain Hugh A. Kelley, U.S. Navy", "role", "Commander of Antarctic Support Activities during Operation Deep Freeze 1968 and 1969"]]
Kelley Nunatak () is a nunatak on the north side of Leverett Glacier in Antarctica, northeast of Mount Gould. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from ground surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960–63, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Herbert O. Kelley, a radioman with the Byrd Station winter party in 1958. <S> [["Kelley Nunatak", "instance of", "Nunatak"], ["Kelley Nunatak", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Kelley Nunatak", "located near", "Leverett Glacier"], ["Kelley Nunatak", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Kelley Nunatak", "named after", "Herbert O. Kelley"], ["Herbert O. Kelley", "occupation", "Radioman"], ["Herbert O. Kelley", "affiliation", "Byrd Station winter party"], ["Byrd Station winter party", "year", "1958"]]
Mount Randall () is a mountain rising to 3,000 m at the south end of Hackerman Ridge in the Victory Mountains, Victoria Land. The mountain, which forms the summit area in this part of the ridge, is 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) west of Mount Riddolls and 3.5 nautical miles (6 km) northeast of Mount Burrill, with which this name is associated. Named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) in 1994 after Richard R. Randall, geographer and cartographer, Executive Secretary, U.S. Board on Geographic Names, 1973–93, whose office included responsibility for geographic nomenclature in Antarctica. Succeeding Meredith F. Burrill (after whom Mount Burrill was named) as Executive Secretary, Randall combined with Burrill to direct a half-century of American geographic names research. <S> [["Mount Randall", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Randall", "height", "3,000 m"], ["Mount Randall", "location", "Victory Mountains, Victoria Land"], ["Mount Randall", "distance from Mount Riddolls", "2 nautical miles"], ["Mount Randall", "distance from Mount Burrill", "3.5 nautical miles"], ["Mount Randall", "named after", "Richard R. Randall"], ["Richard R. Randall", "profession", "Geographer and Cartographer"], ["Richard R. Randall", "role", "Executive Secretary, U.S. Board on Geographic Names"], ["Richard R. Randall", "years of service", "1973-1993"], ["Richard R. Randall", "responsibility", "Geographic nomenclature in Antarctica"], ["Richard R. Randall", "collaborator", "Meredith F. Burrill"], ["Meredith F. Burrill", "role", "Executive Secretary"], ["Meredith F. Burrill", "years of service", "unknown"], ["Meredith F. Burrill", "named after", "Mount Burrill"]]
Ranney Nunatak () is a nunatak in the southwest extremity of Gutenko Nunataks, in the Ford Ranges of Marie Byrd Land. It was first mapped by the United States Antarctic Service (USAS), 1939–41, and named by Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names (US-ACAN) for Charles R. Ranney, ionospheric physicist at Byrd Station, 1969. <S> [["Ranney Nunatak", "instance of", "Nunatak"], ["Ranney Nunatak", "located in", "Gutenko Nunataks"], ["Gutenko Nunataks", "located in", "Ford Ranges"], ["Ford Ranges", "located in", "Marie Byrd Land"], ["Ranney Nunatak", "mapped by", "United States Antarctic Service"], ["United States Antarctic Service", "years of operation", "1939–41"], ["Ranney Nunatak", "named after", "Charles R. Ranney"], ["Charles R. Ranney", "profession", "ionospheric physicist"], ["Charles R. Ranney", "location", "Byrd Station"], ["Byrd Station", "year established", "1969"]]
Mount Kendrick () is a massive ice-covered mountain, high, surmounting the east side of the Nilsen Plateau at the head of Bartlett Glacier, in the Queen Maud Mountains of Antarctica. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Captain H.E. Kendrick, Operations Officer on the staff of the Commander, U.S. Naval Support Force, Antarctica, in U.S. Navy Operation Deep Freeze 1967. <S> [["Mount Kendrick", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Kendrick", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Kendrick", "elevation", "high"], ["Mount Kendrick", "surmounts", "Nilsen Plateau"], ["Nilsen Plateau", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Nilsen Plateau", "glacier", "Bartlett Glacier"], ["Bartlett Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Kendrick", "named after", "Captain H.E. Kendrick"], ["Captain H.E. Kendrick", "role", "Operations Officer"], ["Captain H.E. Kendrick", "organization", "U.S. Navy"], ["U.S. Navy", "operation", "Operation Deep Freeze 1967"]]
The Kester Peaks are three aligned rock peaks standing together south of Mount Malville on the east side of the Forrestal Range, in the Pensacola Mountains of Antarctica. They were mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos from 1956–66, and were named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Larry T. Kester, a photographer with U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6 during Operation Deep Freeze in 1964. <S> [["Kester Peaks", "instance of", "Rock peaks"], ["Kester Peaks", "location", "Pensacola Mountains"], ["Kester Peaks", "country", "Antarctica"], ["Kester Peaks", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Kester Peaks", "named after", "Larry T. Kester"], ["Larry T. Kester", "role", "Photographer"], ["Larry T. Kester", "affiliation", "U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6"], ["U.S. Navy Squadron VX-6", "operation", "Operation Deep Freeze"]]
Peniston Lamb may refer to:* Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne (1745–1828), British politician* His son Peniston Lamb (1770–1805), British politician, MP for Newport 1793–96 and Hertfordshire 1802–05 <S> [["Peniston Lamb", "refer to", "Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne"], ["Peniston Lamb", "refer to", "Peniston Lamb (1770–1805)"], ["Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne", "occupation", "British politician"], ["Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne", "date of birth", "1745"], ["Peniston Lamb, 1st Viscount Melbourne", "date of death", "1828"], ["Peniston Lamb (1770–1805)", "occupation", "British politician"], ["Peniston Lamb (1770–1805)", "position", "MP for Newport 1793–96"], ["Peniston Lamb (1770–1805)", "position", "MP for Hertfordshire 1802–05"]]
Acrocercops delicata is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Java, Indonesia.The larvae feed on "Nephelium lappaceum". They mine the leaves of their host plant. <S> [["Acrocercops delicata", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Acrocercops delicata", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Acrocercops delicata", "location", "Java, Indonesia"], ["Acrocercops delicata", "food source", "Nephelium lappaceum"], ["Acrocercops delicata", "feeding behavior", "Leaf mining"], ["Nephelium lappaceum", "host plant", "Acrocercops delicata"]]
Acrocercops lophonota is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Java, Indonesia. <S> [["Acrocercops lophonota", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Acrocercops lophonota", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Acrocercops lophonota", "location", "Java, Indonesia"]]
Ravn Rock () is a submerged rock lying in the center of Neptunes Bellows, the entrance to Port Foster, Deception Island, in the South Shetland Islands. Charted by the French Antarctic Expedition under Charcot, 1908–10. Named for the whale catcher Ravn, based at Deception Island at that time. <S> [["Ravn Rock", "instance of", "Submerged rock"], ["Ravn Rock", "location", "Neptunes Bellows"], ["Neptunes Bellows", "part of", "Port Foster"], ["Port Foster", "location", "Deception Island"], ["Deception Island", "location", "South Shetland Islands"], ["Ravn Rock", "charted by", "French Antarctic Expedition"], ["French Antarctic Expedition", "leader", "Charcot"], ["French Antarctic Expedition", "year", "1908-10"], ["Ravn Rock", "named after", "whale catcher Ravn"], ["whale catcher Ravn", "based at", "Deception Island"]]
Mount Lupa () is a flat-topped, ice-covered mountain, over high, standing between Romulus Glacier and Martin Glacier close east-southeast of Black Thumb and east of the head of Rymill Bay, on the west coast of Graham Land, Antarctica. It was first roughly surveyed in 1936 by the British Graham Land Expedition under John Rymill. It was resurveyed in 1948–49 by the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey who applied the name. This mountain lies near the heads of Romulus and Remus Glaciers, and the name derives from the mythological story of the she-wolf (Lupa) which fed the twins Romulus and Remus after they had been thrown into the Tiber. <S> [["Mount Lupa", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Lupa", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Lupa", "height", "over high"], ["Mount Lupa", "surrounded by", "Romulus Glacier"], ["Mount Lupa", "surrounded by", "Martin Glacier"], ["Mount Lupa", "located near", "Black Thumb"], ["Mount Lupa", "located near", "Rymill Bay"], ["Mount Lupa", "located on", "Graham Land"], ["Mount Lupa", "first surveyed by", "British Graham Land Expedition"], ["Mount Lupa", "surveyed again by", "Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey"], ["Mount Lupa", "name origin", "mythological story of the she-wolf (Lupa) feeding Romulus and Remus"]]
Mount Lymburner () is a mountain, high, standing west-northwest of Mount Weems near the north end of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains of Antarctica. It was discovered by Lincoln Ellsworth on his trans-Antarctic flight of November 23, 1935, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for J.H. Lymburner, an assistant pilot on Ellsworth's expedition. <S> [["Mount Lymburner", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Lymburner", "height", "high"], ["Mount Lymburner", "location", "west-northwest of Mount Weems near the north end of the Sentinel Range in the Ellsworth Mountains of Antarctica"], ["Mount Lymburner", "discovered by", "Lincoln Ellsworth"], ["Mount Lymburner", "discovery date", "November 23, 1935"], ["Mount Lymburner", "named after", "J.H. Lymburner"], ["J.H. Lymburner", "role", "assistant pilot on Ellsworth's expedition"]]
The American Arachnological Society (AAS) is a scientific organization founded in 1972 in order to promote the study of arachnids by seeking to achieve closer cooperation and understanding between amateur and professional arachnologists along with publication of the "Journal of Arachnology." The society holds annual meetings around the United States and membership is open to all individuals who share the common objectives held by the society. <S> [["American Arachnological Society", "instance of", "Scientific organization"], ["American Arachnological Society", "founded in", "1972"], ["American Arachnological Society", "purpose", "Promote study of arachnids"], ["American Arachnological Society", "purpose", "Seek closer cooperation and understanding between amateur and professional arachnologists"], ["American Arachnological Society", "publication", "Journal of Arachnology"], ["American Arachnological Society", "holds", "Annual meetings around the United States"], ["American Arachnological Society", "membership open to", "Individuals who share common objectives"]]
Lystad Bay () is a bay wide which indents the west side of Horseshoe Island, in the northeast part of Marguerite Bay, Antarctica. It was first surveyed in 1936–37 by the British Graham Land Expedition under John Rymill, and was visited by the USMS "North Star" and of the United States Antarctic Service in 1940. The name was proposed by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Captain Isak Lystad of the "North Star". <S> [["Lystad Bay", "instance of", "Bay"], ["Lystad Bay", "location", "Horseshoe Island"], ["Lystad Bay", "located in", "Marguerite Bay"], ["Lystad Bay", "surveyed by", "British Graham Land Expedition"], ["Lystad Bay", "visited by", "USMS North Star"], ["Lystad Bay", "visited by", "United States Antarctic Service"], ["Lystad Bay", "name proposed by", "Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names"], ["Lystad Bay", "named after", "Captain Isak Lystad"]]
Lyons Cone () is a cone shaped peak north-northeast of the Matterhorn, rising to on the ridge separating the heads of Lacroix Glacier, Newall Glacier, and Suess Glacier in the Asgard Range, Victoria Land, Antarctica. It was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names after American geochemist William Berry Lyons, a veteran of expeditions to the Himalayas, Greenland, Iceland, and Antarctica, 1980–97, and chief scientist of the McMurdo Dry Valleys Long-Term Ecological Research field team, 1993–97. As a member of a University of New Hampshire field party, 1988–89, Lyons participated in glaciochemical investigations that collected two ice cores, deep, from the upper Newall Glacier, in proximity of this peak. <S> [["Lyons Cone", "instance of", "Peak"], ["Lyons Cone", "location", "Asgard Range, Victoria Land, Antarctica"], ["Lyons Cone", "named after", "William Berry Lyons"], ["William Berry Lyons", "profession", "Geochemist"], ["William Berry Lyons", "expeditions to", "Himalayas, Greenland, Iceland, Antarctica"], ["William Berry Lyons", "chief scientist of", "McMurdo Dry Valleys Long-Term Ecological Research field team"], ["University of New Hampshire field party", "investigations", "glaciochemical"], ["Newall Glacier", "proximity of", "Lyons Cone"]]
Spodnje Hoče () is a settlement in and the administrative centre of the Municipality of Hoče–Slivnica in northeastern Slovenia. It lies below the eastern Pohorje Hills on the edge of the flatlands on the right bank of the Drava River south of Maribor. The area is part of the traditional region of Styria. The municipality is now included in the Drava Statistical Region. <S> [["Spodnje Hoče", "instance of", "Settlement"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "located in", "Municipality of Hoče–Slivnica"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "region", "Styria"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "located in", "Drava Statistical Region"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "located below", "Pohorje Hills"], ["Pohorje Hills", "direction", "eastern"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "located on edge of", "flatlands"], ["Spodnje Hoče", "located on bank of", "Drava River"], ["Drava River", "direction", "south"], ["Drava River", "located south of", "Maribor"]]
Lucian Flemming (born November 19, 1966) is an Anguillan football player. He has played for Anguilla national team. <S> [["Lucian Flemming", "instance of", "Football player"], ["Lucian Flemming", "birth date", "November 19, 1966"], ["Lucian Flemming", "nationality", "Anguillan"], ["Lucian Flemming", "team", "Anguilla national team"]]
Carl Nielsen's Pan and Syrinx ("Pan og Syrinx") is a symphonic poem written for a concert of the composer's works which was held on 11 February 1918 in Copenhagen. <S> [["Carl Nielsen's Pan and Syrinx", "instance of", "Symphonic poem"], ["Carl Nielsen's Pan and Syrinx", "composer", "Carl Nielsen"], ["Carl Nielsen's Pan and Syrinx", "event", "Concert"], ["Concert", "date", "11 February 1918"], ["Concert", "location", "Copenhagen"]]
SN 1998aq is a supernova located in galaxy NGC 3982. It was discovered in 1998 by amateur astronomer Mark Armstrong. <S> [["SN 1998aq", "instance of", "Supernova"], ["SN 1998aq", "located in", "NGC 3982"], ["SN 1998aq", "discovered by", "Mark Armstrong"], ["Mark Armstrong", "profession", "amateur astronomer"]]
Murphys Ice Cream is a food company based in Dingle, County Kerry, Ireland. It uses the milk of Kerry cattle and serves coffees as well as ice creams and desserts. Seán and Kieran Murphy started Murphys Ice Cream in Dingle in 2000 with the goal of making the best ice cream in the world. They make a range of usual and unusual flavours, including brown bread and sea salt. <S> [["Murphys Ice Cream", "instance of", "Food company"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "based in", "Dingle"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "located in", "County Kerry"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "country", "Ireland"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "uses", "milk of Kerry cattle"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "serves", "coffees"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "serves", "ice creams"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "serves", "desserts"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "founders", "Seán Murphy"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "founders", "Kieran Murphy"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "founded in", "2000"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "goal", "making the best ice cream in the world"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "makes", "range of usual and unusual flavours"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "flavours include", "brown bread"], ["Murphys Ice Cream", "flavours include", "sea salt"]]
Louis Dufresne (18 January 1752, Champien, near Peronne – 11 October 1832) was a French ornithologist and taxidermist.Louis Dufresne was one of the naturalists on board the "Astrolabe", which accompanied by the "Boussole", left Brest in August 1785 on a voyage of discovery. The ships went first to Madeira and Tenerife, then to Trinidad and then to the coast of Brazil (including Santa Catarina Island). Rounding Cape Horn the expedition landed at Concepción and on to the Sandwich Islands and then sailed north along the coast of north-west America to Alaska. In 1786, the expedition resumed this time visiting Monterey before crossing the Pacific to land in Macao in China. In 1787 the boats returned to France.Six years later in 1793, Dufresne became a taxidermist and curator at Museum d'Histoire Naturelle. His work included the classification and arrangement of collections of invertebrates as well as vertebrates and he visited many parts of the world on behalf of the Museum. In 1802 he popularized the use of arsenical soap for preserving birds in an article in "Nouveau dictionnaire d'histoire naturelle" a technique which had enabled the Muséum to build the greatest collection of birds in the world.Dufresne also maintained a private collection which by 1818 consisted of 1,600 bird specimens (on wooden supports and with both with Latin and French names), 800 world eggs, 4,000 shells, fossils, amphibians, corals and 12,000 insects. This collection purchased for the University of Edinburgh in 1819. In 1854 the University transferred the Natural History Museum into the government ownership to form a publicly-funded national museum, which became the Royal Scottish Museum (now part of National Museums Scotland).In 1829 Dufresne was awarded the Legion of Honour. He died of lung disease. <S> [    ["Louis Dufresne", "instance of", "Ornithologist"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "instance of", "Taxidermist"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "birth date", "18 January 1752"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "birth place", "Champien, near Peronne"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "death date", "11 October 1832"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "nationality", "French"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "occupation", "Naturalist"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "occupation", "Curator"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "award", "Legion of Honour"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "death cause", "Lung disease"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "workplace", "Museum d'Histoire Naturelle"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "contribution", "Popularized use of arsenical soap for preserving birds"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "1,600 bird specimens"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "800 world eggs"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "4,000 shells"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "fossils"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "amphibians"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "corals"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection", "12,000 insects"],    ["Louis Dufresne", "collection location", "University of Edinburgh"],    ["University of Edinburgh", "acquisition", "Louis Dufresne's collection"],    ["University of Edinburgh", "transfer", "Natural History Museum"],    ["Natural History Museum", "ownership", "Government"],    ["Natural History Museum", "current status", "Royal Scottish Museum"],    ["Royal Scottish Museum", "current status", "National Museums Scotland"],    ["Astrolabe", "accompanied by", "Boussole"],    ["Astrolabe", "departure location", "Brest"],    ["Astrolabe", "departure date", "August 1785"],    ["Astrolabe", "route", "Madeira -> Tenerife -> Trinidad -> Brazil -> Concepción -> Sandwich Islands -> Alaska"],    ["Astrolabe", "return date", "1787"]]
"Born Again in Dixieland" is a song co-written and recorded by Canadian country music artist Jason McCoy. Released in June 1997, it was the lead single from his album "Playin' for Keeps". The song reached #3 on the "RPM" Country Tracks chart in September 1997. The song won a SOCAN Song of the Year award. <S> [["Born Again in Dixieland", "instance of", "Song"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "co-written by", "Jason McCoy"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "recorded by", "Jason McCoy"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "release date", "June 1997"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "album", "Playin' for Keeps"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "chart position", "#3 on RPM Country Tracks chart"], ["Born Again in Dixieland", "award", "SOCAN Song of the Year"]]
Brandon Tauszik (born 1986) is a photographer and filmmaker based in California.In 2011, Tauszik began covering the doomsday prophesies of Harold Camping and the Family Radio ministry. In 2014, Tauszik pioneered GIF-based storytelling with "Tapered Throne", a portrait of Oakland's black barbers.He has directed the music videos for rapper Antwon's "Helicopter" and "Living Every Dream", as well as producer RL Grime's "Heard Me". <S> [["Brandon Tauszik", "profession", "Photographer"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "profession", "Filmmaker"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "birth year", "1986"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "location", "California"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "coverage", "Doomsday prophesies of Harold Camping"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "coverage", "Family Radio ministry"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "innovation", "GIF-based storytelling"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "project", "Tapered Throne"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "subject", "Oakland's black barbers"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "music video director", "Antwon's Helicopter"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "music video director", "Antwon's Living Every Dream"], ["Brandon Tauszik", "music video director", "RL Grime's Heard Me"]]
Diphenolic acid is a carboxylic acid with molecular formula C17H18O4. Its IUPAC name is 4,4-bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)pentanoic acid, and it can be prepared by the condensation reaction of phenol with levulinic acid in the presence of hydrochloric acid. The equation for this synthesis is::2 C6H5OH + CH3C(O)CH2CH2COOH → CH3C("p"-C6H4OH)2CH2CH2COOH + H2ODiphenolic acid is a solid at room temperature, melting at 168–171 °C and boiling at 507 °C. According to its MSDS, diphenolic acid is soluble in ethanol, isopropanol, acetone, acetic acid, and methyl ethyl ketone, but insoluble in benzene, carbon tetrachloride, and xylene.Diphenolic acid may be a suitable replacement for bisphenol A as a plasticizer.Diphenolate esters have been used to synthesize epoxy resins as a replacement for the diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A.The diglycidyl ethers of n-alkyl diphenolate esters have similar thermomechanical properties to the diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A when cured, but the viscosity and glass transition temperature vary as a function of the ester length. Diphenolate esters have also been used to synthesize polycarbonates with a potential for water solubility. <S> [    ["Diphenolic acid", "has molecular formula", "C17H18O4"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "IUPAC name", "4,4-bis(4-hydroxyphenyl)pentanoic acid"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "melting point", "168–171 °C"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "boiling point", "507 °C"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "soluble in", ["ethanol", "isopropanol", "acetone", "acetic acid", "methyl ethyl ketone"]],    ["Diphenolic acid", "insoluble in", ["benzene", "carbon tetrachloride", "xylene"]],    ["Diphenolic acid", "potential replacement for", "bisphenol A"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "used to synthesize", ["epoxy resins", "polycarbonates"]],    ["epoxy resins", "replacement for", "diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A"],    ["polycarbonates", "potential for", "water solubility"],    ["epoxy resins", "thermomechanical properties similar to", "diglycidyl ether of bisphenol A"],    ["epoxy resins", "viscosity and glass transition temperature vary based on", "ester length"],    ["Diphenolic acid", "prepared by", "condensation reaction of phenol with levulinic acid in the presence of hydrochloric acid"]]
Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps is an album by Death in June released in November 2010. This version was available to download from iTunes in November 2010, the CD version with bonus tracks was limited to 3,000 copies. The album was also released as 3 separate 2x10" picture disc editions, as well as a USB version (MP3 & FLAC).It is their first studio release since 2008's The Rule of Thirds and marks a distinctive change in sound. Unlike the more neofolk sounds of their most recent releases this album is completely piano led, under the moniker of 'Totenkopf Torch Songs'. The 'Lounge Corps' part of the album is a selection of well-known Death in June tracks such as 'Rose Clouds of Holocaust' & 'Fall Apart' reworked in the style of this album & presented as an instrumental version. <S> [["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "instance of", "Album"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "released in", "November 2010"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "available on", "iTunes"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "limited to", "3,000 copies"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "also released as", "3 separate 2x10' picture disc editions"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "also released as", "USB version (MP3 & FLAC)"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "first studio release since", "2008's The Rule of Thirds"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "change in sound", "distinctive"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "sound led by", "piano"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "moniker", "Totenkopf Torch Songs"], ["Peaceful Snow/Lounge Corps", "Lounge Corps part", "selection of well-known Death in June tracks reworked in the style of the album & presented as an instrumental version"]]
Netty Simons (née Rothenberg) (b. 26 October 1913, d. 1 April 1994) was an American pianist, music editor, music educator and composer. <S> [["Netty Simons", "profession", "Pianist"], ["Netty Simons", "profession", "Music editor"], ["Netty Simons", "profession", "Music educator"], ["Netty Simons", "profession", "Composer"], ["Netty Simons", "birth date", "26 October 1913"], ["Netty Simons", "death date", "1 April 1994"], ["Netty Simons", "nationality", "American"], ["Netty Simons", "maiden name", "Rothenberg"]]
Beware the Gonzo is a 2010 romantic comedy-drama film written and directed by Bryan Goluboff. Ezra Miller stars as the eponymous Gonzo, a high school student who creates an underground newspaper. Zoe Kravitz, Jesse McCartney, Griffin Newman, Campbell Scott, and Amy Sedaris appear in supporting roles. Its title refers to a style of first-person confrontational journalism developed by Hunter S. Thompson in the early 1970s.The film debuted at the Tribeca Film Festival in April 2010. <S> [["Beware the Gonzo", "instance of", "Film"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "genre", "Romantic comedy-drama"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "writer", "Bryan Goluboff"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "director", "Bryan Goluboff"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "star", "Ezra Miller"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "character", "Gonzo"], ["Gonzo", "description", "high school student who creates an underground newspaper"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "supporting roles", "Zoe Kravitz, Jesse McCartney, Griffin Newman, Campbell Scott, Amy Sedaris"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "title refers to", "style of first-person confrontational journalism developed by Hunter S. Thompson in the early 1970s"], ["Beware the Gonzo", "debuted at", "Tribeca Film Festival in April 2010"]]
The Mystic Schooners are a collegiate summer baseball team that operates in the Mystic, Connecticut region. The franchise is one of the two oldest franchises in the New England Collegiate Baseball League.Originally known as the Eastern Tides, and later the Thread City Tides, playing in Willimantic, Connecticut, the franchise was purchased by former Boston Red Sox General Manager Dan Duquette in 2004. Duquette's club was first known as the Berkshire Dukes, playing their home games at the Dan Duquette Sports Academy in Hinsdale, Massachusetts. Duquette moved the team to nearby Pittsfield in 2005 after reaching a lease agreement with the city that brought the Dukes to historic Wahconah Park. In November 2008 the team changed its name to the Pittsfield American Defenders after the ownership group that owned the American Defenders of New Hampshire, which included Duquette, bought into the team.The team had struggled to compete in the NECBL since moving to Berkshire County, and did not enjoy a winning season or a playoff berth until 2008. The team's level of play has rebounded greatly since the disastrous summer of 2005, where the Dukes finished at a league-worst 11-31, the fourth fewest wins in NECBL history. The Defenders' fan base has continued to grow despite the team's struggles on the field, with a reported home attendance of 28,955 in 2007, the fourth-highest in the league.In December 2009, the Defenders were sold to the Bristol Collegiate Baseball Club which moved the original franchise back to its beginning state of Connecticut.On January 14, 2009 it was announced that the team's nickname would be the Bristol Nine, and team general manager Dan Kennedy unveiled a logo featuring "...the old looking player and the old style hat and the man with the mustache and the whole nine yards." The logo's design was credited to Bristol resident Brian Rooney. Shortly thereafter, it was revealed that the logo in question was actually the trademarked property of Top of the Third, Incorporated, owners of a minor-professional baseball team in Visalia, California. The logo, the creation of graphic designer Dan Simon, had originally been used by the California League's Mudville Nine. The Bristol Nine name was then abandoned, with team management adopting the Bristol Collegiate Baseball Club brand.Following a one-year stint in Bristol, the team moved to Mystic, Connecticut for the 2011 season and was rebranded as the Mystic Schooners. <S> [["Mystic Schooners", "instance of", "Collegiate summer baseball team"],["Mystic Schooners", "location", "Mystic, Connecticut"],["Mystic Schooners", "region", "New England Collegiate Baseball League"],["Mystic Schooners", "franchise age", "one of the two oldest franchises"],["Mystic Schooners", "former names", "Eastern Tides, Thread City Tides, Berkshire Dukes"],["Mystic Schooners", "purchased by", "Dan Duquette"],["Mystic Schooners", "home games", "Dan Duquette Sports Academy, Wahconah Park"],["Mystic Schooners", "struggles", "did not enjoy a winning season or playoff berth until 2008"],["Mystic Schooners", "fan base", "continued to grow despite struggles on the field"],["Mystic Schooners", "attendance", "28,955 in 2007"],["Mystic Schooners", "sold to", "Bristol Collegiate Baseball Club"],["Mystic Schooners", "nickname", "Bristol Nine"],["Mystic Schooners", "logo designer", "Brian Rooney"],["Mystic Schooners", "logo trademarked by", "Top of the Third, Incorporated"],["Mystic Schooners", "rebranded as", "Mystic Schooners"]]
The Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway, or Hangyong high-speed railway () or Hang-Yong Passenger Dedicated Railway) is a China Railway High-speed line between the major cities of Hangzhou and Ningbo in Zhejiang province. It spans approximately , with a design speed of .In the railway's short name, " stands for Hangzhou, and " () is a traditional short name for Ningbo.Early on, the railway was scheduled to open in June 2012; later, the end of 2012 became the target date. It was announced in October 2012 that the completion of the project had been postponed again. Test operations began at the start of 2013 and commercial operations began on 30 June 2013.The line runs parallel to the Xiaoshan–Ningbo railway. <S> [["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "instance of", "China Railway High-speed line"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "location", "Zhejiang province"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "length", "approximately"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "design speed", ""], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "short name", "Hangyong high-speed railway"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "short name", "Hang-Yong Passenger Dedicated Railway"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "scheduled opening date", "June 2012"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "target opening date", "end of 2012"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "test operations start date", "start of 2013"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "commercial operations start date", "30 June 2013"], ["Hangzhou–Ningbo high-speed railway", "parallel to", "Xiaoshan–Ningbo railway"]]
Mount Paine () is a massive, flat-topped mountain, 3,330 m, forming a buttress-type projection of the western part of the La Gorce Mountains, in the Queen Maud Mountains of Antarctica. Discovered in December 1934 by the Byrd Antarctic Expedition geological party under Quin Blackburn, and named by Byrd for Stuart D.L. Paine, navigator and radio operator of that party. <S> [["Mount Paine", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Paine", "height", "3,330 m"], ["Mount Paine", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Paine", "discovered by", "Byrd Antarctic Expedition geological party"], ["Mount Paine", "named after", "Stuart D.L. Paine"], ["Byrd Antarctic Expedition geological party", "leader", "Quin Blackburn"], ["Byrd Antarctic Expedition geological party", "members", "Stuart D.L. Paine"]]
Manfred Osten (born January 19, 1938) is a German poet and cultural historian. He was born in Ludwigslust in the region of Mecklenburg, which became part of the German Democratic Republic after World War II.He escaped to the Federal Republic of Germany in 1952. He received his higher education in Hamburg and Munich, where he studied law, philosophy, musicology, and literature. He earned a doctorate upon the completion of a thesis concerning the concept of natural law in the early writings of Schelling. At the conclusion of his studies, he joined the diplomatic service of the Federal Republic of Germany. His career as a diplomat included postings in France, Cameroon, Chad, Australia, Japan, and Hungary. From 1995 to 2004, he was the Secretary-General of the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation.He is an honorary Doctor of the Bulgarian Academy of Sciences, the University of Pécs, the University of Bucharest, and the Alexandru Ioan Cuza University of Iaşi. In 1993 he received the Order of the Rising Sun from the Japanese government. He is in addition a member of the Academy of Sciences and Literature in Mainz. In 2008 he was admitted to the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany.Among his many works are "Die Erotik Pfirsichs" "The Eroticism of the Peach" (about Japanese writers); "Das Geraubte Gedächtnis" "Stolen Memory" (about the relation between digital systems and the decline of cultural memory); "Goethes Entdeckung der Langsamkeit" "Goethe's Discovery of Slowness"; "Die Kunst, Fehler zu Machen" "The Art of Making Mistakes"; and his collection of poems "Im Kerngehäuse".He is a noted player of the viola and has a particular interest in the music of Robert Schumann. <S> [    ["Manfred Osten", "instance of", "German poet"],    ["Manfred Osten", "instance of", "Cultural historian"],    ["Manfred Osten", "birth date", "January 19, 1938"],    ["Manfred Osten", "birth place", "Ludwigslust, Mecklenburg"],    ["Manfred Osten", "country", "Germany"],    ["Manfred Osten", "education", "Hamburg"],    ["Manfred Osten", "education", "Munich"],    ["Manfred Osten", "study field", "Law"],    ["Manfred Osten", "study field", "Philosophy"],    ["Manfred Osten", "study field", "Musicology"],    ["Manfred Osten", "study field", "Literature"],    ["Manfred Osten", "doctorate", "Thesis on natural law in Schelling's early writings"],    ["Manfred Osten", "career", "Diplomatic service in Federal Republic of Germany"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "France"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "Cameroon"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "Chad"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "Australia"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "Japan"],    ["Manfred Osten", "postings", "Hungary"],    ["Manfred Osten", "position", "Secretary-General of Alexander von Humboldt Foundation"],    ["Manfred Osten", "honorary doctorate", "Bulgarian Academy of Sciences"],    ["Manfred Osten", "honorary doctorate", "University of Pécs"],    ["Manfred Osten", "honorary doctorate", "University of Bucharest"],    ["Manfred Osten", "honorary doctorate", "Alexandru Ioan Cuza University of Iaşi"],    ["Manfred Osten", "awards", "Order of the Rising Sun from Japanese government"],    ["Manfred Osten", "membership", "Academy of Sciences and Literature in Mainz"],    ["Manfred Osten", "awards", "Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany"],    ["Manfred Osten", "works", "Die Erotik Pfirsichs (The Eroticism of the Peach)"],    ["Manfred Osten", "works", "Das Geraubte Gedächtnis (Stolen Memory)"],    ["Manfred Osten", "works", "Goethes Entdeckung der Langsamkeit (Goethe's Discovery of Slowness)"],    ["Manfred Osten", "works", "Die Kunst, Fehler zu Machen (The Art of Making Mistakes)"],    ["Manfred Osten", "works", "Im Kerngehäuse (collection of poems)"],    ["Manfred Osten", "interest", "Viola"],    ["Manfred Osten", "interest", "Music of Robert Schumann"]]
Frank Keller is a professor of computational cognition at the School of Informatics, University of Edinburgh and director at the Institute for Language, Cognition and Computation.Keller got his B.S. from the University of Stuttgart and then got his Ph.D. from the University of Edinburgh. He then served as postdoc at Saarland University and Massachusetts Institute of Technology, before managing European Network on Vision and Language Committee and serving as a member of the European Association for Computational Linguistics' governing board. <S> [["Frank Keller", "position", "Professor of Computational Cognition"], ["Frank Keller", "works at", "School of Informatics, University of Edinburgh"], ["Frank Keller", "director at", "Institute for Language, Cognition and Computation"], ["Frank Keller", "education", "B.S. from University of Stuttgart"], ["Frank Keller", "education", "Ph.D. from University of Edinburgh"], ["Frank Keller", "worked as", "postdoc at Saarland University"], ["Frank Keller", "worked as", "postdoc at Massachusetts Institute of Technology"], ["Frank Keller", "managed", "European Network on Vision and Language Committee"], ["Frank Keller", "member of", "European Association for Computational Linguistics' governing board"]]
The South Fork Eel River Wilderness is a wilderness area located in Mendocino County, California. The wilderness was added to the National Wilderness Preservation System when the United States Congress passed the Northern California Coastal Wild Heritage Wilderness Act in 2006 (Public Law 109-362). The Department of the Interior's Bureau of Land Management (BLM) is the agency in charge.The wilderness is broken into two sections. The Red Mountain unit is dominated by Red Mountain and the Cedar Creek (South Fork Eel River) drainage. Elevations range from at the southwest end along Cedar Creek to , less than three miles away at the top Red Mountain. Terrain is generally steep, consisting of rugged drainages dropping abruptly into Cedar Creek canyon. A small area of fairly gentle slopes is found near the summit. A zone of reddish soil occupies the central part of the area and contrasts sharply with the surrounding landscape.These unusual soils have resulted in a unique vegetation cover of several species of pine and cypress trees intermixed with a low brush understory. Rare and endangered plant species occupy the landscape covered by these ultrabasic soils. These rare plants have been isolated over space and time on serpentine rock near the summit of Red Mountain. This edaphic sky island holds the northern range extension of Sargent cypress ("Cupressus sargentii"). This is also the only location to find Red Mountain buckwheat ("Eriogonum kelloggii") and Red Mountain stonecrop ("Sedum eastwoodiae"). Much of the area is designated and Research Natural Area (RNA) / Area of Critical Environmental Concern (ACEC).The red soil on Red Mountain is in the Littlered series. It is an Ultisol, a Haplohumult, with nearly 50% iron oxides. The main iron oxide is goethite (FeOOH), with enough hematite(Fe2O3)to make the soil red.The southern section called Cahto Peak unit consists of several Douglas fir forest watersheds, one of which is so pristine that it has been designated a Biosphere Reserve, a National Natural Landmark, and a Hydrologic Benchmark. Much of the area is designated a RNA / ACEC. <S> [["South Fork Eel River Wilderness", "instance of", "Wilderness area"],["South Fork Eel River Wilderness", "located in", "Mendocino County, California"],["South Fork Eel River Wilderness", "added to", "National Wilderness Preservation System"],["National Wilderness Preservation System", "passed by", "United States Congress"],["United States Congress", "passed", "Northern California Coastal Wild Heritage Wilderness Act"],["Northern California Coastal Wild Heritage Wilderness Act", "Public Law", "109-362"],["South Fork Eel River Wilderness", "managed by", "Department of the Interior's Bureau of Land Management"],["South Fork Eel River Wilderness", "divided into", "Red Mountain unit and Cahto Peak unit"],["Red Mountain unit", "dominated by", "Red Mountain and Cedar Creek drainage"],["Red Mountain unit", "elevations range from", "southwest end along Cedar Creek to top of Red Mountain"],["Red Mountain unit", "terrain", "steep with rugged drainages dropping into Cedar Creek canyon"],["Red Mountain unit", "vegetation cover", "several species of pine and cypress trees with low brush understory"],["Red Mountain unit", "unique vegetation cover due to", "unusual soils resulting in rare and endangered plant species"],["Red Mountain unit", "location of", "Sargent cypress, Red Mountain buckwheat, and Red Mountain stonecrop"],["Red Mountain unit", "designated as", "Research Natural Area (RNA) / Area of Critical Environmental Concern (ACEC)"],["Red Mountain unit", "soil type", "Littlered series, Ultisol, Haplohumult with 50% iron oxides"],["Cahto Peak unit", "consists of", "several Douglas fir forest watersheds"],["Cahto Peak unit", "designation", "Biosphere Reserve, National Natural Landmark, and Hydrologic Benchmark"],["Cahto Peak unit", "designated as", "RNA / ACEC"]]
Atheism in Christianity () is a 1968 book by the Marxist philosopher Ernst Bloch. The book offers a third way to the Christian/atheist either/or debate. Gareth Jenkins from "Socialist Review" says that Bloch "argues that there are liberatory, 'atheist' elements within Christianity with which socialists should make common cause." <S> [["Atheism in Christianity", "instance of", "Book"], ["Atheism in Christianity", "author", "Ernst Bloch"], ["Atheism in Christianity", "publication year", "1968"], ["Atheism in Christianity", "main idea", "Offering a third way to the Christian/atheist debate"], ["Ernst Bloch", "philosopher", "Marxist"], ["Gareth Jenkins", "source", "Socialist Review"], ["Ernst Bloch", "argument", "There are liberatory, 'atheist' elements within Christianity"], ["Socialists", "should", "make common cause with liberatory elements within Christianity"]]
Gunnestad Glacier () is a glacier long, flowing north between Mount Widerøe and Mount Walnum in the Sør Rondane Mountains of Antarctica. It was mapped by Norwegian cartographers in 1957 from air photos taken by U.S. Navy Operation Highjump, 1946–47, and named for Lieutenant Alf Gunnestad, a pilot with the Norwegian expedition under Lars Christensen, 1933–34. <S> [["Gunnestad Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "length", "long"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "direction", "north"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "between", "Mount Widerøe"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "between", "Mount Walnum"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "mapped by", "Norwegian cartographers"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "mapped in", "1957"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "mapped from", "air photos"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "air photos taken by", "U.S. Navy Operation Highjump"], ["Gunnestad Glacier", "named after", "Lieutenant Alf Gunnestad"], ["Lieutenant Alf Gunnestad", "role", "pilot"], ["Lieutenant Alf Gunnestad", "expedition", "Norwegian expedition under Lars Christensen"], ["Norwegian expedition under Lars Christensen", "year", "1933-34"]]
Guile Island () is an island lying southwest of Duchaylard Island, in the Biscoe Islands of Antarctica. It was charted by the British Graham Land Expedition under John Rymill, 1934–37, and so named by the UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee in 1959 because, while there appears to be a number of landing places on this island, numerous underwater rocks make approach dangerous, so requiring guile in the attempt. <S> [["Guile Island", "instance of", "Island"], ["Guile Island", "location", "Biscoe Islands"], ["Guile Island", "located southwest of", "Duchaylard Island"], ["Guile Island", "charted by", "British Graham Land Expedition"], ["British Graham Land Expedition", "leader", "John Rymill"], ["Guile Island", "named by", "UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee"], ["UK Antarctic Place-Names Committee", "year", "1959"], ["Guile Island", "reason for name", "numerous underwater rocks make approach dangerous"], ["Guile Island", "requirement", "guile in the attempt"]]
"Blues Run the Game" is a 1965 song by the American singer-songwriter Jackson C. Frank. The song was the opening track on Frank's self-titled debut album. <S> [["Blues Run the Game", "instance of", "Song"], ["Blues Run the Game", "release year", 1965], ["Blues Run the Game", "performed by", "Jackson C. Frank"], ["Blues Run the Game", "album", "Self-titled debut album"], ["Self-titled debut album", "track", "Opening track"]]
Gruendler Glacier () is a tributary glacier that drains the northern slopes of the Malta Plateau near Mount Hussey and flows north into Trainer Glacier, in the Victory Mountains of Victoria Land, Antarctica. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960–64, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for James D. Gruendler, a member of the United States Antarctic Research Program glaciological party to Roosevelt Island, 1967–68. <S> [["Gruendler Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Gruendler Glacier", "location", "Victory Mountains"], ["Gruendler Glacier", "located near", "Mount Hussey"], ["Gruendler Glacier", "drains into", "Trainer Glacier"], ["Gruendler Glacier", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Gruendler Glacier", "named after", "James D. Gruendler"], ["James D. Gruendler", "affiliation", "United States Antarctic Research Program"], ["United States Antarctic Research Program", "activity", "glaciological party to Roosevelt Island, 1967-68"]]
Trail Glacier () is a broken mountain glacier on the southern side of Mount Menzies, about 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) from the summit. It is about 5 nautical miles (9 km) long and 3 nautical miles (6 km) wide. The glacier flows from a snowfield at about 2,750 m down a steep slope for at least 900 m vertically, then spreads out and merges with the ice sheet a few mi from the south side of the mountain. Mapped from ANARE (Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions) air photos and surveys of the Prince Charles Mountains, 1960–61. Named by Antarctic Names Committee of Australia (ANCA) for D.S. Trail, geologist who led an ANARE field party to this feature in December 1961. <S> [["Trail Glacier", "located on", "Mount Menzies"], ["Trail Glacier", "distance from summit", "2 nautical miles"], ["Trail Glacier", "length", "5 nautical miles"], ["Trail Glacier", "width", "3 nautical miles"], ["Trail Glacier", "flows from", "snowfield at 2,750m"], ["Trail Glacier", "vertical drop", "900m"], ["Trail Glacier", "merges with", "ice sheet"], ["Trail Glacier", "mapped from", "ANARE air photos"], ["Trail Glacier", "named after", "D.S. Trail"], ["D.S. Trail", "profession", "geologist"], ["D.S. Trail", "led ANARE field party to", "Trail Glacier"], ["ANARE", "stands for", "Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions"], ["Prince Charles Mountains", "surveyed by", "ANARE in 1960-61"], ["Antarctic Names Committee of Australia", "named", "Trail Glacier"]]
Grimes Glacier () is a steep glacier descending from the east side of Anderson Massif, in the Heritage Range of the Ellsworth Mountains of Antarctica. It was mapped by the United States Geological Survey from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1961–66, and was named by the Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names for Master Chief Equipmentman Paul D. Grimes, U.S. Navy, who supervised the construction crews during relocation of Williams Air Field at McMurdo Sound in the closing month of U.S. Navy Operation Deep Freeze 1965. <S> [["Grimes Glacier", "located in", "Heritage Range"], ["Grimes Glacier", "located in", "Ellsworth Mountains"], ["Grimes Glacier", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Grimes Glacier", "mapped by", "United States Geological Survey"], ["Grimes Glacier", "named after", "Master Chief Equipmentman Paul D. Grimes, U.S. Navy"], ["Paul D. Grimes", "affiliation", "U.S. Navy"], ["Paul D. Grimes", "role", "supervised construction crews"], ["Williams Air Field", "location", "McMurdo Sound"], ["U.S. Navy Operation Deep Freeze 1965", "event", "relocation of Williams Air Field"]]
Trinity Nunatak () is a large nunatak in the stream of the Mawson Glacier, about 5 nautical miles (9 km) north of the Convoy Range in Victoria Land. Mapped in 1957 by the New Zealand Northern Survey party of the Commonwealth Trans-Antarctic Expedition (1956–58), which applied the name because of its three summits. <S> [["Trinity Nunatak", "instance of", "Nunatak"], ["Trinity Nunatak", "located in", "Victoria Land"], ["Trinity Nunatak", "distance from Convoy Range", "5 nautical miles"], ["Trinity Nunatak", "mapped by", "New Zealand Northern Survey party"], ["Trinity Nunatak", "reason for name", "three summits"]]
Trollkjelneset Headland () is a snow-domed headland rising between Krylvika Bight and the mouth of Jutulstraumen Glacier in Queen Maud Land. Mapped by Norwegian cartographers from surveys and air photos by Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition (NBSAE) (1949–52) and air photos by the Norwegian expedition (1958–59) and named Trollkjelneset (cape of the troll's cauldron). <S> [["Trollkjelneset Headland", "instance of", "Headland"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "location", "Queen Maud Land"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "features", "Snow-domed"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "between", "Krylvika Bight"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "between", "Mouth of Jutulstraumen Glacier"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "mapped by", "Norwegian cartographers"], ["Norwegian cartographers", "source", "Surveys"], ["Norwegian cartographers", "source", "Air photos"], ["Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition", "date", "1949-1952"], ["Norwegian expedition", "date", "1958-1959"], ["Trollkjelneset Headland", "name", "Trollkjelneset"], ["Trollkjelneset", "meaning", "Cape of the troll's cauldron"]]
Trousers Rock () is a rock with a prominent wave-cut arch, lying immediately west of Cook Rock and 0.3 nautical miles (0.6 km) northeast of Vindication Island in the South Sandwich Islands. Charted in 1930 and given this descriptive name by DI personnel on the "Discovery II". <S> [["Trousers Rock", "instance of", "Rock"], ["Trousers Rock", "location", "South Sandwich Islands"], ["Trousers Rock", "proximity", "Cook Rock"], ["Trousers Rock", "distance", "0.3 nautical miles"], ["Trousers Rock", "distance", "0.6 km"], ["Trousers Rock", "direction", "northeast"], ["Trousers Rock", "charted in", "1930"], ["Trousers Rock", "named by", "DI personnel"], ["Trousers Rock", "ship", "Discovery II"]]
Mount Dodge () is a mainly ice-free peak in Antarctica, high, on a mountain spur descending northward from the Prince Olav Mountains, at the confluence of Holzrichter Glacier and Gough Glacier. It was discovered by the U.S. Ross Ice Shelf Traverse Party (1957–58) under A.P. Crary, and named for Professor Carroll W. Dodge, who analyzed and reported upon lichens and lichen parasites for the Byrd Antarctic Expedition (1933–35). <S> [["Mount Dodge", "instance of", "Peak"], ["Mount Dodge", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Mount Dodge", "height", "high"], ["Mount Dodge", "discovered by", "U.S. Ross Ice Shelf Traverse Party"], ["Mount Dodge", "named after", "Professor Carroll W. Dodge"], ["Mount Dodge", "analysis", "lichens and lichen parasites"], ["U.S. Ross Ice Shelf Traverse Party", "year", "1957-58"], ["U.S. Ross Ice Shelf Traverse Party", "leader", "A.P. Crary"], ["Byrd Antarctic Expedition", "year", "1933-35"]]
Dogwatch Saddle is a snow saddle between Mount Brøgger and Mount Morrison, separating the glacial catchments of Benson Glacier and Cleveland Glacier in the Prince Albert Mountains, Victoria Land. A New Zealand Antarctic Research Programme field party made a late night temporary camp on the saddle in January 1990. The name commemorates the midnight hours kept at this location. <S> [["Dogwatch Saddle", "instance of", "Snow saddle"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "located between", "Mount Brøgger"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "located between", "Mount Morrison"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "separates", "Benson Glacier"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "separates", "Cleveland Glacier"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "located in", "Prince Albert Mountains"], ["Prince Albert Mountains", "located in", "Victoria Land"], ["New Zealand Antarctic Research Programme field party", "made camp on", "Dogwatch Saddle"], ["Camp", "location", "Dogwatch Saddle"], ["Name", "commemorates", "midnight hours at Dogwatch Saddle"], ["Dogwatch Saddle", "commemorates", "midnight hours"]]
Punchbowl Glacier () is a glacier that flows southwards between Poibrene Heights and Metlichina Ridge, and enters the north end of Exasperation Inlet, north of Jorum Glacier, on the east side of Graham Land, Antarctica. Surveyed by Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS) in 1947 and 1955. The name applied by United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) is descriptive of shape as the glacier is hemmed in by mountains. <S> [["Punchbowl Glacier", "instance of", "Glacier"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "location", "Antarctica"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "flows between", "Poibrene Heights and Metlichina Ridge"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "enters", "Exasperation Inlet"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "north of", "Jorum Glacier"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "surveyed by", "Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey (FIDS)"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "surveyed in", "1947 and 1955"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "named by", "United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC)"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "descriptive of", "shape"], ["Punchbowl Glacier", "hemmed in by", "mountains"]]
Gouvernøren Harbor () is a small harbor indenting the east side of Enterprise Island just west of Pythia Island in Wilhelmina Bay, off the west coast of Graham Land, Antarctica. The name was applied by whalers using the harbor because the whaling vessel "Gouvernøren I" was wrecked there in 1916. <S> [["Gouvernøren Harbor", "located in", "Enterprise Island"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "located in", "Wilhelmina Bay"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "located in", "Graham Land"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "located in", "Antarctica"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "named after", "Gouvernøren I"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "event", "wrecked in 1916"], ["Gouvernøren Harbor", "used by", "whalers"]]
Frank Teruggi, Jr. (1949–1973) was an American student, journalist, and member of the Industrial Workers of the World, from Chicago, Illinois, who became one of the victims of General Augusto Pinochet's military shortly after the September 11, 1973 Pinochet "coup d'état" against Socialist President Salvador Allende.A Chilean court in 2014 found that the United States played a key role in Teruggi's murder. <S> [["Frank Teruggi, Jr.", "occupation", "student"], ["Frank Teruggi, Jr.", "occupation", "journalist"], ["Frank Teruggi, Jr.", "member of", "Industrial Workers of the World"], ["Frank Teruggi, Jr.", "location", "Chicago, Illinois"], ["Frank Teruggi, Jr.", "victim of", "General Augusto Pinochet's military"], ["General Augusto Pinochet's military", "event", "September 11, 1973 Pinochet coup d'état"], ["September 11, 1973 Pinochet coup d'état", "against", "Socialist President Salvador Allende"], ["Chilean court", "year", 2014], ["Chilean court", "found", "United States played a key role in Teruggi's murder"]]
Edgware Way Grassland or Edgware Way Rough is a 6.7 hectare Site of Metropolitan Importance for Nature Conservation in Edgware in the London Borough of Barnet. It is traversed by Edgwarebury Brook and contains traces of a planned railway viaduct and embankment. This was part of a planned extension of the Northern line from Edgware to Bushey, which was cancelled when the introduction of the Green Belt after the Second World War led to the cancellation of the developments which the railway was to serve. Part of the site is the Environment Agency's Edgwarebury Park Flood Storage Area. The reserve is typical unimproved London Clay grassland. Damp, herb rich areas have uncommon plants characteristic of old meadows such as great burnet, sneezewort and devil's bit scabious. The brook is lined by sedges and water-cress, while breeding birds include yellowhammer and spotted flycatcher.The reserve adjoins Edgwarebury Park. It is private land, but is crossed by a public footpath from Edgware Way which starts just west of the junction with Spur Road. <S> [["Edgware Way Grassland", "instance of", "Site of Metropolitan Importance for Nature Conservation"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "located in", "Edgware"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "located in", "London Borough of Barnet"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "size", "6.7 hectares"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "features", "Edgwarebury Brook"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "features", "planned railway viaduct"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "features", "embankment"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "features", "Environment Agency's Edgwarebury Park Flood Storage Area"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "contains", "uncommon plants"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "contains", "breeding birds"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "adjoins", "Edgwarebury Park"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "accessed by", "public footpath"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "starts at", "Edgware Way"], ["Edgware Way Grassland", "starts at", "Spur Road"]]
Jean Khayat (; born 3 May 1942) is a Tunisian fencer. He competed in the individual foil and sabre events at the 1960 Summer Olympics. <S> [["Jean Khayat", "instance of", "Fencer"], ["Jean Khayat", "birth date", "3 May 1942"], ["Jean Khayat", "country of citizenship", "Tunisia"], ["Jean Khayat", "competition", "1960 Summer Olympics"], ["Jean Khayat", "event", "Individual foil"], ["Jean Khayat", "event", "Sabre"]]
Robert E. Rich Jr. (born January 25, 1941) is an American billionaire, the chairman and majority owner of Rich Products Corporation, the largest family-owned frozen foods manufacturer in the US, based in Buffalo, New York. He has a net worth of $5.65 billion as of August 2017. <S> [["Robert E. Rich Jr.", "instance of", "American billionaire"], ["Robert E. Rich Jr.", "birth date", "January 25, 1941"], ["Robert E. Rich Jr.", "occupation", "Chairman"], ["Robert E. Rich Jr.", "owner of", "Rich Products Corporation"], ["Rich Products Corporation", "type", "Frozen foods manufacturer"], ["Rich Products Corporation", "ownership", "Majority owner: Robert E. Rich Jr."], ["Rich Products Corporation", "location", "Buffalo, New York"], ["Robert E. Rich Jr.", "net worth", "$5.65 billion (August 2017)"]]
CBZ Bank Limited, also CBZ Bank, is a commercial bank in Zimbabwe. It is one of the financial services institutions licensed by the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe, the central bank and national banking regulator. <S> [["CBZ Bank Limited", "instance of", "Commercial bank"], ["CBZ Bank Limited", "country", "Zimbabwe"], ["CBZ Bank Limited", "licensed by", "Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe"], ["Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe", "type", "Central bank"], ["Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe", "regulator of", "National banking institutions"]]
Phyllocnistis intermediella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae, known from Florida, U.S.A.The hostplants for the species include "Mastichodendron foetidissimum", and "Sideroxylon pallidum". They mine the leaves of their host plant. The mine is found on the underside of the leaf. It has the form of a long, whitish, irregular serpentine just below the epidermis, confined to one side of the leaf and not crossing the main rib. <S> [["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "location", "Florida, U.S.A."], ["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "host plant", "Mastichodendron foetidissimum"], ["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "host plant", "Sideroxylon pallidum"], ["Phyllocnistis intermediella", "feeding behavior", "mine leaves"], ["mine leaves", "location", "underside of leaf"], ["mine leaves", "form", "long, whitish, irregular serpentine"], ["mine leaves", "position", "confined to one side of leaf"], ["mine leaves", "position", "not crossing main rib"]]
Easton Land District is a land district (cadastral division) of Western Australia, located within the Kimberley Land Division in the Kimberley region of the state. <S> [["Easton Land District", "instance of", "Land district"], ["Easton Land District", "located in", "Western Australia"], ["Easton Land District", "located within", "Kimberley Land Division"], ["Easton Land District", "region", "Kimberley region"], ["Kimberley Land Division", "located in", "Western Australia"]]
Waachiim Spiritwolf is a Native American professional mixed martial artist who last competed in the Welterweight division. A professional competitor since from 2006 until 2015, he competed for King of the Cage, Tachi Palace Fights, Bellator, and Strikeforce. <S> [["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "instance of", "Professional mixed martial artist"], ["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "nationality", "Native American"], ["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "division", "Welterweight"], ["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "competitor since", "2006"], ["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "competitor until", "2015"], ["Waachiim Spiritwolf", "competitions"], ["King of the Cage", "Tachi Palace Fights", "Bellator", "Strikeforce"]]
Phyllocnistis nepenthae is a moth of the family Gracillariidae, known from Sumatra, Indonesia. The hostplant for the species is "Nepenthes tobaica". <S> [["Phyllocnistis nepenthae", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Phyllocnistis nepenthae", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Phyllocnistis nepenthae", "location", "Sumatra, Indonesia"], ["Phyllocnistis nepenthae", "hostplant", "Nepenthes tobaica"]]
The Complete Fighter's Handbook is a supplemental rulebook published in 1989 for the 2nd edition of the "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game. <S> [["The Complete Fighter's Handbook", "instance of", "Supplemental rulebook"], ["The Complete Fighter's Handbook", "published in", "1989"], ["The Complete Fighter's Handbook", "for game", "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons 2nd edition"]]
The Complete Wizard's Handbook is a supplementary rulebook published in 1990 for the 2nd edition of the "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game. <S> [["The Complete Wizard's Handbook", "instance of", "Supplementary rulebook"], ["The Complete Wizard's Handbook", "published in", "1990"], ["The Complete Wizard's Handbook", "for game", "Advanced Dungeons & Dragons 2nd edition"]]
"On Physical Lines of Force" is a four-part paper written by James Clerk Maxwell published in 1861. In it, Maxwell derived the equations of electromagnetism in conjunction with a "sea" of "molecular vortices" which he used to model Faraday's lines of force. Maxwell had studied and commented on the field of electricity and magnetism as early as 1855/6 when "On Faraday's Lines of Force" was read to the Cambridge Philosophical Society. Maxwell made an analogy between the density of this medium and the magnetic permeability, as well as an analogy between the transverse elasticity and the dielectric constant, and using the results of a prior experiment by Wilhelm Eduard Weber and Rudolf Kohlrausch performed in 1856, he established a connection between the speed of light and the speed of propagation of waves in this medium.The paper ushered in a new era of classical electrodynamics and catalyzed further progress in the mathematical field of vector calculus. Because of this, it is considered one of the most historically significant publications in physics and science in general, comparable with Einstein's "Annus Mirabilis papers" and Newton's "Principia Mathematica". <S> [["On Physical Lines of Force", "instance of", "Paper"], ["On Physical Lines of Force", "author", "James Clerk Maxwell"], ["On Physical Lines of Force", "publication year", 1861], ["James Clerk Maxwell", "studied", "electricity and magnetism"], ["James Clerk Maxwell", "publication", "On Faraday's Lines of Force"], ["On Faraday's Lines of Force", "read to", "Cambridge Philosophical Society"], ["Maxwell", "made analogy between", "density of medium and magnetic permeability"], ["Maxwell", "made analogy between", "transverse elasticity and dielectric constant"], ["Maxwell", "established connection between", "speed of light and speed of propagation of waves"], ["Paper", "ushered in", "new era of classical electrodynamics"], ["Paper", "catalyzed", "progress in mathematical field of vector calculus"], ["Paper", "considered", "historically significant publication in physics and science"], ["Paper", "comparable with", "Einstein's Annus Mirabilis papers"], ["Paper", "comparable with", "Newton's Principia Mathematica"]]
The Staten Island Tunnel is an abandoned, incomplete railway/subway tunnel in New York City. It was intended to connect railways on Staten Island (precursors to the modern-day Staten Island Railway) to the BMT Fourth Avenue Line of the New York City Subway, in Brooklyn, via a new crossing under the Narrows. Planned to extend , the tunnel would have been among the world's longest at the time of its planning, in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.Construction began in 1923, and the tunnel was excavated into the Narrows before New York City Mayor John Hylan, a former Brooklyn–Manhattan Transit Corporation (BMT) employee and initial proponent of the tunnel, canceled the project in 1925. The tunnel lies dormant under Owl's Head Park in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. Later proposals to complete the tunnel, including the 1939 plans for the Independent Subway System's ambitious Second System, were never funded.Modern proposals for completion of the tunnel have come from New York City Councilman Lewis Fidler, who in 2007 proposed a 0.33% tax for the tri-state region to pay for the construction. The tunnel was listed as one of many projects that could receive federal funds that were to have been allocated to the Access to the Region's Core tunnel, which was canceled in October 2010. State Senator Diane Savino was among the supporters of the tunnel; Savino stated that if built, the tunnel would cost $3 billion and would improve quality of life for Staten Islanders, reduce traffic, and increase the attractiveness of the borough for investment. <S> [    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "instance of", "Railway/subway tunnel"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "location", "New York City"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "intended to connect", "Staten Island Railway"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "intended to connect", "BMT Fourth Avenue Line"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "location", "Brooklyn"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "location", "Narrows"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "length", "among world's longest"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "construction began", 1923],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "canceled by", "John Hylan"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "location", "Owl's Head Park"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "location", "Bay Ridge"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "proposed by", "Lewis Fidler"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "proposed tax for construction", "0.33%"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "listed as project for federal funds", "Access to the Region's Core tunnel"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "supporter", "Diane Savino"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "estimated cost", "$3 billion"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "benefits", "improve quality of life for Staten Islanders"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "benefits", "reduce traffic"],    ["Staten Island Tunnel", "benefits", "increase attractiveness of borough for investment"]]
Caloptilia wakayamensis is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Honshū island, Japan.The wingspan is 10–11 mm.The larvae feed on "Acer palmatum". They probably mine the leaves of their host plant. <S> [["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "location", "Honshū island, Japan"], ["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "wingspan", "10-11 mm"], ["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "food source", "Acer palmatum"], ["Caloptilia wakayamensis", "feeding behavior", "leaf mining"]]
The Jenderal Soedirman University (, abbreviated as UNSOED) is a public university located in Purwokerto, Central Java, Indonesia and was established on September 23, 1963. The university named after Jenderal Soedirman (English: General Sudirman), the first commander-in-chief of the Indonesian Army during the country's fight for independence; he was born in the Banyumas region.UNSOED is the only public university in the ex-Banyumas residency. Thus affecting the student composition, from 25,782 of total active students in 2008, students from local Banyumas region accounted for almost 35% while the rest are from other regions in Indonesia as far as Sumatera and Sulawesi. About 5000 students enrolled at the university every year.To improve services for the students, UNSOED provided facilities and activities such as a students economic union (KOPMA), scholarships, medical services and medical infrastructure, life insurance, libraries, laboratory, student learning center, student activity center, web-based academic information system, academic infrastructure (campuses, auditorium, rectorate and administration center), arts and sports organizations and dormitory. <S> [    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "instance of", "Public university"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "located in", "Purwokerto, Central Java, Indonesia"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "established on", "September 23, 1963"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "named after", "Jenderal Soedirman"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "only public university in", "ex-Banyumas residency"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "total active students in 2008", "25,782"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "students from local Banyumas region", "35%"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "students from other regions in Indonesia", "65%"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "enrolled students every year", "5000"],    ["Jenderal Soedirman University", "provided facilities and activities", ["students economic union (KOPMA)", "scholarships", "medical services and infrastructure", "life insurance", "libraries", "laboratory", "student learning center", "student activity center", "web-based academic information system", "academic infrastructure", "arts and sports organizations", "dormitory"]]]
The Rijeka Thermal Power Station (, TE Rijeka, also known as "TE Urinj") is an oil-fired power station east of Rijeka at Kostrena, Croatia. It was built between 1974 and 1978 and it has one generation unit with capacity of 320 MW. The height of the boiler house including its rooftop flue gas stack is .Turbine for the power station was supplied by Ansaldo Energia. Ansaldo Energia was also awarded engineering, procurement and construction contract. Boilers were supplied by Waagner-Biro.The power station is owned and operated by Hrvatska elektroprivreda. Its annual production varies, averaging 917 GWh, but only 141 GWh in 2011. It is expected to undergo decommissioning in 2020, but it is doubtful that it will remain operational until then because of its pollution problem. , Rijeka Thermal Power Station is offline, ready to resume generation within 160 hours of notice. <S> [["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "instance of", "Power station"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "location", "Kostrena, Croatia"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "built between", "1974 and 1978"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "generation unit capacity", "320 MW"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "boiler house height", "unknown"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "turbine supplier", "Ansaldo Energia"], ["Ansaldo Energia", "awarded contract for", "engineering, procurement and construction"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "boiler supplier", "Waagner-Biro"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "owner", "Hrvatska elektroprivreda"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "annual production", "averaging 917 GWh"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "expected decommissioning year", "2020"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "current status", "offline"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "resumption time", "within 160 hours of notice"], ["Rijeka Thermal Power Station", "pollution problem", "yes"]]
Phyllonorycter pygmaea is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is known from Japan (the islands of Hokkaidō, Kyūshū, Shikoku and Honshū), Korea and the Russian Far East.The wingspan is 5-5.5 mm.The larvae feed on "Castanea crenata", "Quercus acutissima", "Quercus crispula", "Quercus mongolica" and "Quercus serrata". They mine the leaves of their host plant. The mine has the form of a ptychonomous blotch mine on the underside of the leaf. <S> [["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "location", "Japan"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "location", "Korea"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "location", "Russian Far East"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "wingspan", "5-5.5 mm"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae feed on", "Castanea crenata"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae feed on", "Quercus acutissima"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae feed on", "Quercus crispula"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae feed on", "Quercus mongolica"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae feed on", "Quercus serrata"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "larvae mine the leaves of", "host plant"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "mine form", "ptychonomous blotch mine"], ["Phyllonorycter pygmaea", "location of mine", "underside of the leaf"]]
The Karadağ Border General Forces Corps of the Ottoman Empire () was an "ad hoc" corps under the command of the Ottoman Western Army during the First Balkan War. It was formed in the vicinity of Yakova (Gjakova) and Pirzerin (Prizren) with remnant units of İpek Detachment and Priştine Detachment and its headquarters was established in Derbe-i Bala (Debar) on November 9, 1912. <S> [["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "instance of", "Military unit"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "country", "Ottoman Empire"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "commander", "Ottoman Western Army"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "formed in", "Yakova"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "formed in", "Pirzerin"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "remnant units of", "İpek Detachment"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "remnant units of", "Priştine Detachment"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "headquarters established in", "Derbe-i Bala"], ["Karadağ Border General Forces Corps", "established on", "November 9, 1912"]]
Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov (; born 1 November 1955) is a Russian professional association football official and a former player. <S> [["Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov", "occupation", "Association football official"], ["Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov", "birth date", "1 November 1955"], ["Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov", "nationality", "Russian"], ["Nikolay Nikolayevich Leonov", "former occupation", "Player"]]
South Barrier () is a rocky ridge descending southward from Budd Peak along the east margin of Fiftyone Glacier and terminating at Lambeth Bluff in southern Heard Island. The descriptive name was applied by ANARE (Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions) in 1948. <S> [["South Barrier", "location", "Heard Island"], ["South Barrier", "description", "rocky ridge"], ["South Barrier", "direction", "southward"], ["South Barrier", "origin", "Budd Peak"], ["South Barrier", "terminates at", "Lambeth Bluff"], ["South Barrier", "applied by", "ANARE"], ["ANARE", "full form", "Australian National Antarctic Research Expeditions"], ["ANARE", "year", "1948"]]
Mount Sourabaya () is a mountain (915 m) 1 nautical mile (1.9 km) northwest of Mount Darnley, Bristol Island, in the South Sandwich Islands. Named by United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1971. The name refers to the whaling factory ship Sourabaya, from which an eruption of the island was witnessed in 1935.The most recent eruption of Mount Sourabaya began between 19 April and 23 April 2016 <S> [["Mount Sourabaya", "instance of", "Mountain"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "height", "915 m"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "location", "Bristol Island, South Sandwich Islands"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "distance from Mount Darnley", "1 nautical mile"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "named by", "United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "year named", "1971"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "meaning of name", "refers to whaling factory ship Sourabaya"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "witnessed eruption in", "1935"], ["Mount Sourabaya", "most recent eruption began between", "19 April and 23 April 2016"]]
Søråsen Ridge () is a broad, snow-covered ridge that separates the Quar and Ekström Ice shelves, on the coast of Queen Maud Land. The feature was first mapped and named "Søråsen" (the south ridge) by the Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition, 1949–52. <S> [["Søråsen Ridge", "instance of", "Ridge"], ["Søråsen Ridge", "location", "Queen Maud Land"], ["Søråsen Ridge", "separates", "Quar Ice Shelf"], ["Søråsen Ridge", "separates", "Ekström Ice Shelf"], ["Søråsen Ridge", "mapped by", "Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition"], ["Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic Expedition", "year", "1949-52"]]
Somers Glacier () is a glacier flowing northwest into Trooz Glacier on Kiev Peninsula, the west coast of Graham Land. First charted by the British Graham Land Expedition (BGLE) under Rymill, 1934–37. Named by the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) in 1959 for Henri Somers, chief engineer of the BelgAE's ship Belgica, which explored in the area in 1897–99. <S> [["Somers Glacier", "flow direction", "northwest"], ["Somers Glacier", "flows into", "Trooz Glacier"], ["Somers Glacier", "location", "Kiev Peninsula"], ["Kiev Peninsula", "located on", "west coast of Graham Land"], ["British Graham Land Expedition", "charted", "Somers Glacier"], ["British Graham Land Expedition", "year", "1934-37"], ["United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee", "named", "Somers Glacier"], ["United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee", "year", "1959"], ["Henri Somers", "profession", "chief engineer"], ["Henri Somers", "associated with", "BelgAE"], ["BelgAE", "ship", "Belgica"], ["BelgAE", "expedition year", "1897-99"]]
Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL (4 February 1909 – 2 March 1999) was an Irish peer, soldier and polo player. <S> [["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "occupation", "Soldier"], ["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "occupation", "Polo player"], ["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "nationality", "Irish"], ["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "title", "Peer"], ["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "birth date", "4 February 1909"], ["Brigadier Richard Gustavus Hamilton-Russell DSO, LVO, DL", "death date", "2 March 1999"]]
Cecil Jensen (January 17, 1902 - May 1976) was an American editorial cartoonist.Born in Ogden, Utah, Jensen studied at the Chicago Academy of Fine Arts. After moving to California, Jensen worked at the "Los Angeles Illustrated Daily News", eventually as editorial cartoonist. <S> [["Cecil Jensen", "occupation", "Editorial cartoonist"], ["Cecil Jensen", "birth date", "January 17, 1902"], ["Cecil Jensen", "death date", "May 1976"], ["Cecil Jensen", "birth place", "Ogden, Utah"], ["Cecil Jensen", "education", "Chicago Academy of Fine Arts"], ["Cecil Jensen", "worked at", "Los Angeles Illustrated Daily News"], ["Los Angeles Illustrated Daily News", "position", "Editorial cartoonist"]]
The 1996 Stockholm Open was a men's tennis tournament played on indoor carpet courts at the Kungliga tennishallen in Stockholm, Sweden and was part of the World Series of the 1996 ATP Tour. It was the 28th edition of the tournament and was held from 4 November until 10 November 1996. Third-seeded Thomas Enqvist won his second consecutive singles title at the event. <S> [["1996 Stockholm Open", "instance of", "Tennis tournament"], ["1996 Stockholm Open", "location", "Kungliga tennishallen"], ["1996 Stockholm Open", "surface", "Indoor carpet courts"], ["1996 Stockholm Open", "part of", "World Series of 1996 ATP Tour"], ["1996 Stockholm Open", "date", "4 November 1996 - 10 November 1996"], ["Thomas Enqvist", "won", "1996 Stockholm Open"], ["Thomas Enqvist", "title", "Second consecutive singles title"]]
Jihad and Genocide is a 2011 book by Richard L. Rubenstein. <S> [["Jihad and Genocide", "title", "Book"], ["Jihad and Genocide", "author", "Richard L. Rubenstein"], ["Jihad and Genocide", "publication year", 2011]]
Yana Rattigan (born Yana Stadnyk 20 January 1987 in Lviv, Ukrainian SSR, USSR) is a Ukrainian born wrestler who competes internationally for Great Britain and England. She competed in the 2009 World Wrestling Championships finishing 5th in the 48 kg category and was 7th in the same weight category at the 2010 World Wrestling Championships. Her most notable performance came in the 2010 European Wrestling Championships where she won a silver medal, a feat repeated in 2013. She was the first woman to win a medal at European championship level for Britain. In 2014, representing England she again won the silver medal at the 2014 Commonwealth Games. <S> [["Yana Rattigan", "birth date", "20 January 1987"], ["Yana Rattigan", "place of birth", "Lviv, Ukrainian SSR, USSR"], ["Yana Rattigan", "nationality", "Ukrainian"], ["Yana Rattigan", "competes for", "Great Britain"], ["Yana Rattigan", "competes for", "England"], ["Yana Rattigan", "competition", "2009 World Wrestling Championships"], ["Yana Rattigan", "finish", "5th in 48 kg category"], ["Yana Rattigan", "competition", "2010 World Wrestling Championships"], ["Yana Rattigan", "finish", "7th in 48 kg category"], ["Yana Rattigan", "notable performance", "2010 European Wrestling Championships"], ["Yana Rattigan", "medal", "silver"], ["Yana Rattigan", "repeated feat", "2013 European Wrestling Championships"], ["Yana Rattigan", "first woman to win medal", "European championship level for Britain"], ["Yana Rattigan", "competition", "2014 Commonwealth Games"], ["Yana Rattigan", "representing", "England"], ["Yana Rattigan", "medal", "silver"]]
William Madison McDonald (June 22, 1866 – July 5, 1950), nicknamed "Gooseneck Bill", was an American politician, businessman, and banker of great influence in Texas during the late nineteenth century. Part of the Black and Tan faction, by 1892 he was elected to the Republican Party of Texas's state executive committee, as temporary chairman in 1896, and as permanent state chairman in 1898.During this period, McDonald was also elected as top leader of two black fraternal organizations, serving as Grand Secretary of the state's black Masons for 50 years. In 1906 he founded Fort Worth's first African-American-owned bank as an enterprise of the state Masons; under his management, the bank survived the Great Depression. The black chapters of Masons banked with him, McDonald made loans to black businessmen, and he became probably the first black millionaire in Texas. <S> [["William Madison McDonald", "instance of", "American politician"], ["William Madison McDonald", "instance of", "Businessman"], ["William Madison McDonald", "instance of", "Banker"], ["William Madison McDonald", "nickname", "Gooseneck Bill"], ["William Madison McDonald", "birth date", "June 22, 1866"], ["William Madison McDonald", "death date", "July 5, 1950"], ["William Madison McDonald", "location", "Texas"], ["William Madison McDonald", "affiliation", "Black and Tan faction"], ["William Madison McDonald", "affiliation", "Republican Party of Texas"], ["William Madison McDonald", "role", "Temporary chairman"], ["William Madison McDonald", "role", "Permanent state chairman"], ["William Madison McDonald", "role", "Grand Secretary"], ["William Madison McDonald", "role", "Founder of Fort Worth's first African-American-owned bank"], ["William Madison McDonald", "achievement", "Survived the Great Depression"], ["William Madison McDonald", "achievement", "First black millionaire in Texas"], ["William Madison McDonald", "affiliation", "State Masons"], ["William Madison McDonald", "affiliation", "Black Masons"], ["William Madison McDonald", "activity", "Made loans to black businessmen"]]
The Sunnylvsfjorden is a fjord in Stranda and Fjord in the Møre og Romsdal county of Norway. The long Sunnylvsfjorden is one of the innermost branches of the large Storfjorden. The fjord ranges from wide and reaches below sea level at its deepest point, just west of Skrenakken near the mouth of the fjord. The famous Geirangerfjorden branches off to the west from the Sunnylvsfjorden.Just south of the village of Helsem, the Storfjorden splits off into the Norddalsfjorden (to the east) and Sunnylvsfjorden (to the south). The village of Hellesylt sits at the end of this fjord. The historic Me-Åkernes farm lies on a cliff on the north side of the fjord. This former municipality of Sunnylven was centered on this fjord. <S> [["Sunnylvsfjorden", "instance of", "Fjord"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "located in", "Stranda"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "located in", "Møre og Romsdal county"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "country", "Norway"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "branch of", "Storfjorden"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "depth", "below sea level"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "deepest point", "west of Skrenakken"], ["Sunnylvsfjorden", "branch off", "Geirangerfjorden"], ["Storfjorden", "split into", "Norddalsfjorden"], ["Storfjorden", "split into", "Sunnylvsfjorden"], ["Hellesylt", "located at", "end of Sunnylvsfjorden"], ["Me-Åkernes farm", "located on", "north side of Sunnylvsfjorden"], ["Sunnylven", "centered on", "Sunnylvsfjorden"]]
Léon Danchin (21 June 1887 - 4 August 1938) was a French artist known for his drawings of animals, primarily sporting dogs. He was also a sculptor.Danchin was born in Lille (France) on 21 June 1887, the second of six children of Albert and Margaret Danchin. For centuries, the Danchin family lived in northern France, in Anchin in Hainaut, where the family name originated. In 1919, Danchin married Simone Meesemaecker.For ease of working, Danchin moved his family to Chantilly, close to Paris. His first works sold very well in France, and also in Belgium, the United States, and England. Danchin later moved to Bergues, in the French Flanders, where he was able to hunt regularly. It was during this period that he drew many of the hunting scenes for which he is renowned.Today, Galerie Hautecœur in Paris manages the re-productions of Danchin's art. <S> [["Léon Danchin", "instance of", "Artist"], ["Léon Danchin", "known for", "Drawings of animals, primarily sporting dogs"], ["Léon Danchin", "also", "Sculptor"], ["Léon Danchin", "born in", "Lille, France"], ["Léon Danchin", "date of birth", "21 June 1887"], ["Léon Danchin", "parents", "Albert and Margaret Danchin"], ["Danchin family", "location", "Anchin in Hainaut, northern France"], ["Léon Danchin", "married", "Simone Meesemaecker"], ["Léon Danchin", "moved to", "Chantilly, close to Paris"], ["Léon Danchin", "first works sold well in", "France, Belgium, United States, England"], ["Léon Danchin", "later moved to", "Bergues, French Flanders"], ["Galerie Hautecœur", "location", "Paris"], ["Galerie Hautecœur", "manages", "re-productions of Danchin's art"]]
IIFL Holdings Limited (formerly India Infoline Limited) d/b/a IIFL and India Infoline, is an Indian diversified financial services company headquartered in Mumbai. The organisation was founded by Nirmal Jain. IIFL and its group companies are backed by Canadian investor Prem Watsa, private equity firm General Atlantic and CDC Group, the UK Government's private equity arm. IIFL is ranked among the top seven financial conglomerates in India and as the top independent financial services firm in India in terms of market capitalisation. Nirmal Jain is the Chairman of the group, while R Venkataraman is the Group Managing Director and Co-Promoter. <S> [["IIFL Holdings Limited", "formerly known as", "India Infoline Limited"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "also known as", "IIFL"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "also known as", "India Infoline"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "type", "Financial services company"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "headquartered in", "Mumbai"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "founded by", "Nirmal Jain"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "backed by", "Canadian investor Prem Watsa"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "backed by", "private equity firm General Atlantic"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "backed by", "CDC Group"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "ranked among", "top seven financial conglomerates in India"], ["IIFL Holdings Limited", "ranked as", "top independent financial services firm in India in terms of market capitalisation"], ["Nirmal Jain", "role", "Chairman of the group"], ["R Venkataraman", "role", "Group Managing Director and Co-Promoter"]]
George Menzies (30 September 1930 – 16 March 2016) was a New Zealand rugby league player and coach who represented New Zealand at three World Cups and coached New Zealand at another World Cup. In 2007 he was named the greatest New Zealand had ever produced. <S> [["George Menzies", "instance of", "Rugby league player"], ["George Menzies", "instance of", "Coach"], ["George Menzies", "country", "New Zealand"], ["George Menzies", "represented", "New Zealand"], ["George Menzies", "World Cups", 3], ["George Menzies", "coached", "New Zealand"], ["George Menzies", "World Cup", 1], ["George Menzies", "named", "Greatest New Zealand produced"]]
Raging Fighter is a 1993 fighting video game developed and published by Konami for the Nintendo Game Boy. It was first released in Japan on March 26, 1993, and later released in North America and Europe in June 1993. <S> [["Raging Fighter", "instance of", "Video game"], ["Raging Fighter", "developed by", "Konami"], ["Raging Fighter", "published by", "Konami"], ["Raging Fighter", "platform", "Nintendo Game Boy"], ["Raging Fighter", "release date", "March 26, 1993 (Japan)"], ["Raging Fighter", "release date", "June 1993 (North America, Europe)"]]
Dr. S. M. Pandit (Sambanand Monappa Pandit; 25 March 1916 – 30 March 1993) was one of the most popular and much sought-after painters of his times, especially in the school of Realism in contrast to the contemporaneous net-traditionalist Bengal Renaissance and other Indian modern art movements. Most of his subjects oscillated between events from classical Indian literature including the Ramayana, the Mahabharata, the Puranas, and the contemporary cinema of his times. He infused a rare blend of artistic virtuosity and filmi glamour to his portrayal of romantic characters like Radha-Krishna, Nala-Damayanti, and Viswamitra-Menaka as also the many heroes and heroines of Hindi cinema. In addition to his critically acclaimed masterpieces he also illustrated many popular film posters, film magazines and various other publications in what can collectively be termed as "calendar art". His works remain hugely popular even today. His mythological paintings and calendar art have been collected widely. He is also widely celebrated in the Indian calendar industry for his "realistic" depiction (albeit inspired by contemporary Indian cinema) of themes from Hindu mythology. In these paintings he emphasised the physical forms of the heroes, heroines, gods and goddesses in marked contrast to traditional and classical styles of Indian painting. In his paintings, Pandit depicted his subjects as handsome, muscular, valorous men and sensuously beautiful, voluptuous women set in surroundings suggestive of cinema settings and sceneries. <S> [    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "instance of", "Painter"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "birth date", "25 March 1916"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "death date", "30 March 1993"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "style", "Realism"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "subjects", ["Ramayana", "Mahabharata", "Puranas", "contemporary cinema"]],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "portrayal", ["Radha-Krishna", "Nala-Damayanti", "Viswamitra-Menaka"]],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "illustrated", ["film posters", "film magazines", "publications"]],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "popular for", ["mythological paintings", "calendar art"]],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "depiction style", "realistic"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "themes", "Hindu mythology"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "emphasis on", ["physical forms", "heroes", "heroines", "gods", "goddesses"]],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "setting", "cinema settings"],    ["Dr. S. M. Pandit", "celebrated in", "Indian calendar industry"]]
"Get Dumb" is a 2007 single by Swedish DJs Axwell, Steve Angello and Sebastian Ingrosso, (the three later known as Swedish House Mafia) along with Dutch DJ Laidback Luke. It was the first of two songs to feature all four artists, followed by "Leave the World Behind" in 2009. The song was also the first ever collaboration by the Swedish trio before their formation as a supergroup. The song charted in the Netherlands, peaking at #45. <S> [["Get Dumb", "instance of", "Single"], ["Get Dumb", "release year", 2007], ["Get Dumb", "artists", ["Axwell", "Steve Angello", "Sebastian Ingrosso", "Laidback Luke"]], ["Axwell", "nationality", "Swedish"], ["Steve Angello", "nationality", "Swedish"], ["Sebastian Ingrosso", "nationality", "Swedish"], ["Laidback Luke", "nationality", "Dutch"], ["Swedish House Mafia", "members", ["Axwell", "Steve Angello", "Sebastian Ingrosso"]], ["Leave the World Behind", "release year", 2009], ["Leave the World Behind", "artists", ["Axwell", "Steve Angello", "Sebastian Ingrosso", "Laidback Luke"]], ["Swedish House Mafia", "formation year", "super group"], ["Netherlands", "chart position", "#45"]]
The North Island snipe ("Coenocorypha barrierensis"), also known as the little barrier snipe or tutukiwi, is an extinct species of bird in the sandpiper family, Scolopacidae, that was endemic to New Zealand. <S> [["North Island snipe", "species of", "bird"], ["North Island snipe", "family", "Scolopacidae"], ["North Island snipe", "endemic to", "New Zealand"], ["North Island snipe", "common name", "little barrier snipe"], ["North Island snipe", "common name", "tutukiwi"], ["North Island snipe", "extinct", "true"]]
