Crataegus opaca, known as the western mayhaw, is a shrub or small tree of the southern United States. It is one of several species of hawthorn with fruits known as "mayhaws". <S> [["Crataegus opaca", "common name", "Western mayhaw"], ["Crataegus opaca", "type", "Shrub"], ["Crataegus opaca", "type", "Small tree"], ["Crataegus opaca", "location", "Southern United States"], ["Crataegus opaca", "fruit", "Mayhaws"], ["Crataegus opaca", "species of", "Hawthorn"]]
TARKI Social Research Institute is an independent research centre located in Budapest, Hungary. TARKI conducts applied socioeconomic research in social stratification, labour markets, income distribution, intergenerational transfers, tax-benefit systems, consumption and lifestyle patterns and attitudes. Senior staff at TARKI all have PhD’s and many hold professorial appointments at major universities. <S> [["TARKI Social Research Institute", "instance of", "Research centre"],["TARKI Social Research Institute", "location", "Budapest, Hungary"],["TARKI Social Research Institute", "research focus", "applied socioeconomic research"],["TARKI Social Research Institute", "research areas", ["social stratification", "labour markets", "income distribution", "intergenerational transfers", "tax-benefit systems", "consumption and lifestyle patterns", "attitudes"]],["TARKI Social Research Institute", "staff qualifications", "PhD's"],["TARKI Social Research Institute", "staff appointments", "professorial appointments at major universities"]]
Irene Hickson (August 14, 1915 – November 24, 1995) was an American catcher who played from through in the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League. Listed at , 116 lb., she batted and threw right-handed.At age 27, Irene Hickson became one of the oldest players signed by the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League for its inaugural season. Although averaging .171 lifetime, she was known as an opportune hitter with runners in scoring position during the late innings. Most importantly, Hickson was a solid fielding catcher with a strong throwing arm, and had a reputation as a good handler of pitchers. On the playing field, she collected 2,388 putouts and 561 assists in 621 games, committing only 130 errors in 3,079 chances for a .958 career fielding average. A member of two champion teams, she won the batting title in the 1943 championship series and in 1946 set an all-time record with five walks received in a single game. <S> [    ["Irene Hickson", "birth date", "August 14, 1915"],    ["Irene Hickson", "death date", "November 24, 1995"],    ["Irene Hickson", "nationality", "American"],    ["Irene Hickson", "position", "Catcher"],    ["Irene Hickson", "league", "All-American Girls Professional Baseball League"],    ["Irene Hickson", "batting hand", "Right-handed"],    ["Irene Hickson", "throwing hand", "Right-handed"],    ["Irene Hickson", "age", "27"],    ["Irene Hickson", "career batting average", ".171"],    ["Irene Hickson", "fielding average", ".958"],    ["Irene Hickson", "putouts", "2,388"],    ["Irene Hickson", "assists", "561"],    ["Irene Hickson", "errors", "130"],    ["Irene Hickson", "champion teams", "2"],    ["Irene Hickson", "batting title", "1943"],    ["Irene Hickson", "record", "five walks received in a single game"]]
Herbert Blankenhorn (15 December 1904 in Mülhausen – 10 August 1991 in Badenweiler) was a German diplomat. From 1929 he was member of the Foreign Office, and from 1938 was a member of the Nazi Party (NSDAP). At the time, he was counsellor in the German legation in Bern, Switzerland. Philippe Mottu had been encouraged by Canon de Bavier, the Procurator of the Abbey of St. Maurice in the Vatican, to meet him as he was in reality an anti-Nazi. Mottu says, 'At the moment when the Third Reich was triumphant on the battlefield, he explained to me why, according to his conviction, Germany was going to lose the war. It was my first contact with one of the men who took part in the German resistance.' [Philippe Mottu, ‘Caux is the place!’, Caux Doc, 1997, p. 10-11] In 1943 he launched the economy department of the German legation in Bern and was Head of the Foreign Office. After 1945 he became one of the most influential German professional diplomats. He joined the CDU in 1946 and served as the West German ambassador to Italy, France(1963-1965) and the United Kingdom (1965–1970).He was the son of officer Karl Blankenhorn (1878-1963). <S> [["Herbert Blankenhorn", "birth date", "15 December 1904"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "birth place", "Mülhausen"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "death date", "10 August 1991"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "death place", "Badenweiler"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "nationality", "German"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "occupation", "Diplomat"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "member of", "Nazi Party"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "member of", "CDU"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "father", "Karl Blankenhorn"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "position", "Counsellor"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "position", "Head of the Foreign Office"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "position", "West German ambassador to Italy"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "position", "West German ambassador to France"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "position", "West German ambassador to the United Kingdom"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "department", "Economy department of the German legation in Bern"], ["Herbert Blankenhorn", "resistance", "German resistance"], ["Philippe Mottu", "encouraged by", "Canon de Bavier"], ["Philippe Mottu", "quote", "'At the moment when the Third Reich was triumphant on the battlefield, he explained to me why, according to his conviction, Germany was going to lose the war. It was my first contact with one of the men who took part in the German resistance.'"], ["Canon de Bavier", "position", "Procurator of the Abbey of St. Maurice in the Vatican"], ["Canon de Bavier", "encouraged", "Philippe Mottu"]]
Museum of Slavonia () is the largest general-type museum in Croatia.Museum of Slavonia was established in 1877 in Osijek. Since 1946, it is located in the City Magistracy building, constructed in 1702 for the purposes of the Vienna Chamber, town government and police. Today, among the museums numerous collections, the most prized are the Roman Mursa and numismatic collections. The Museum's library contains more than 70,000 books. <S> [["Museum of Slavonia", "instance of", "Museum"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "country", "Croatia"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "established in", "1877"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "location", "Osijek"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "building", "City Magistracy"], ["City Magistracy", "constructed in", "1702"], ["City Magistracy", "purpose", "Vienna Chamber, town government, police"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "collections", "Roman Mursa, numismatic"], ["Museum of Slavonia", "library contains", "70,000 books"]]
Kurt Blecha (February 25, 1923 – March 1, 2013) was a German politician. He was a Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED) official and head of the press office, and the chairman of the Council of Ministers of the GDR.Blecha was born in Ústí nad Labem, Czechoslovakia. Blecha joined the Nazi Party in 1941 and was drafted into military service. He came in 1943 in Soviet captivity and was active in the National Committee for Free Germany.He joined the SED in 1946. From the 1950s to 1989 he was part of the Board of the Journalists Association of the GDR. From 1953 to 1958 he was deputy director and then as successor to Fritz Beyling until 1989 in the Head of the Press Office to the Chairman of the Ministers of the GDR. Blecha was awarded, inter alia, the Patriotic Order of Merit in 1983 and 1988 with the honor Clasp to the Patriotic Order of Merit.His daughter, Sigrid, was the second wife of East German foreign buyer Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski. <S> [    ["Kurt Blecha", "instance of", "German politician"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "birth date", "February 25, 1923"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "death date", "March 1, 2013"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "birth place", "Ústí nad Labem, Czechoslovakia"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "political party", "Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED)"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "occupation", "Head of the press office"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "occupation", "Chairman of the Council of Ministers of the GDR"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "awards", "Patriotic Order of Merit (1983)"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "awards", "Patriotic Order of Merit with Clasp (1988)"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "daughter", "Sigrid"],    ["Sigrid", "relationship", "second wife of Alexander Schalck-Golodkowski"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "Nazi Party member since", "1941"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "captured by Soviets", "1943"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "joined SED", "1946"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "Board member of Journalists Association of the GDR", "1950s-1989"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "deputy director of Press Office", "1953-1958"],    ["Kurt Blecha", "successor to Fritz Beyling as Head of Press Office", "1989"]]
