Operation Dragon Strike was a NATO counter-insurgent mission in Kandahar province, Afghanistan, against Taliban forces, which started on September 15, 2010. <S> [["Operation Dragon Strike", "instance of", "NATO counter-insurgent mission"], ["Operation Dragon Strike", "location", "Kandahar province, Afghanistan"], ["Operation Dragon Strike", "target", "Taliban forces"], ["Operation Dragon Strike", "start date", "September 15, 2010"]]
Rosemary's Billygoat is an American heavy metal/hard rock band formed in Los Angeles South Bay in 1991, consisting of singer Mike Odd, guitarist Neal Gargantua, bassist Pat Trick and drummer Paul Bearer.Influenced both musically and visually by the likes of Alice Cooper, Rob Zombie, Gwar, Kiss and Black Sabbath, Rosemary's Billygoat are best known for their theatrical horror-themed stage shows which incorporate many comically absurd props and stunts, including pyrotechnics, fire breathing, electric chairs, mock crucifixion, flaming pentagrams and various costumed monsters and creatures. Musically, the band has been described as "aggro and dark yet jovial", showcasing an "oozing brew of doom, stoner metal, dark psychedelic rock and hardcore punk".Over the last two decades, Rosemary's Billygoat have attracted a strong cult following in the Los Angeles punk and metal underground, having shared stages with the likes of such cult bands as Gwar, W.A.S.P., The Dickies, Circle Jerks, 45 Grave, Haunted Garage and more; in 2013, the "OC Weekly" newspaper ranked Rosemary's Billygoat number 10 on their list of the ten greatest shock rock bands of all time. <S> [    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "instance of", "Band"],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "origin", "Los Angeles South Bay"],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "formed in", 1991],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "members", ["Mike Odd", "Neal Gargantua", "Pat Trick", "Paul Bearer"]],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "influenced by", ["Alice Cooper", "Rob Zombie", "Gwar", "Kiss", "Black Sabbath"]],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "known for", "theatrical horror-themed stage shows"],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "musical style", ["doom metal", "stoner metal", "psychedelic rock", "hardcore punk"]],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "cult following in", "Los Angeles punk and metal underground"],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "shared stages with", ["Gwar", "W.A.S.P.", "The Dickies", "Circle Jerks", "45 Grave", "Haunted Garage"]],    ["Rosemary's Billygoat", "ranked number", 10, "OC Weekly's list of the ten greatest shock rock bands of all time"]]
Geoffrey Norman Gaunt was a Spitfire pilot during the Battle of Britain. He served in the RAF as part of No. 609 Squadron West Riding of Yorkshire Squadron RAF. He was killed in action on 15 September 1940. Gaunt was from a well-known textile family and screen star James Mason was a cousin. He was buried in his family plot at Salendine Nook Baptist Church with his grandparents and later his father was also buried there in 1958. He was good friends with David Moore Crook.Geoffrey Norman Gaunt served with 609 Squadron Auxiliary Air Force before the war and received some flying training with the unit. He was commissioned into the Auxiliary Air Force in April 1940 and completed his training at the Flying Training School at Cranwell, Lincolnshire in June and July 1940. Gaunt then went to 7 Operational Training Unit at Hawarden, near RAF Sealand, in the North Wales-Chester area. After converting to Spitfire Mark Ones there, Geoffrey Gaunt rejoined 609 Spitfire Squadron on 16 August 1940 at Warmwell in Dorset, close to Weymouth, for the protection of Portland Naval Base and places from Bristol, Somerset, Dorset, Devon, and Cornwall.Earlier, in May 1940 609 West Riding squadron flew sorties in support of Operation Dynamo - the evacuation of the British Expeditionary Force from Dunkirk during the Battle of France. One-third of the squadron's pilots were lost during a three-day period.In the Battle of Britain, which started in July 1940, the squadron operated from Middle Wallop, with half the squadron operating from the forward base at Warmwell in Dorset. During August 1940, the squadron destroyed 46 enemy aircraft but nearly all the pre-war auxiliary pilots were lost, either killed or missing. In October 1940, 609 became the first squadron to achieve 100 confirmed aerial victories.Geoffrey Gaunt had rejoined 609 Squadron on 16 August and got into many combats through the month. He shared in the destruction of a Messerschmitt BF110 fighter on 25 August which was shared Destroyed with P/O Noel Agazarian, who was later a Battle of Britain fighter ace.Geoffrey Gaunt was killed on 15 September 1940 when he was shot down during an attack on German bombers over London. His Spitfire, R6690, crashed and burned out near Kenley. This day was later known as "Battle of Britain Day" as the continued strength of the RAF fighter defence decided Hitler to postpone and then cancel his planned invasion of Britain.David Crook wrote a book titled Spitfire Pilot, published by Faber and Faber in 1942, which describes his friends including Geoffrey Gaunt who were killed, one by one as the Battle of Britain carried on through 1940. The book immortalizes these men and Crook also, for he was to die along with his friends in wartime. These included: Geoffrey Gaunt, Noel Agazarian, John Dundas, and Phillip "Pip" Barran.# A Spitfire flown by "Aggy" Agazarian and pilots including David More Crook, John Dundas, (also killed, like Agazarian and Crook in wartime) hangs today in the Imperial War Museum at Lambeth, London.# A Memorial Hut to 609 West Riding squadron, complete with a replica Spitfire, a series of wartime portraits of these pilots, relics and memorabilia is at Elvington Airfield for the Yorkshire Air Museum, near York, in tribute to these men like Geoffrey Gaunt who were killed in wartime. <S> [["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "occupation", "Spitfire pilot"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "served in", "RAF"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "squadron", "No. 609 Squadron West Riding of Yorkshire Squadron RAF"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "date of death", "15 September 1940"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "buried at", "Salendine Nook Baptist Church"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "family relation", "James Mason"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "friend", "David Moore Crook"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "training location", "Cranwell, Lincolnshire"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "operational training unit", "7 Operational Training Unit at Hawarden"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "rejoined squadron", "609 Spitfire Squadron"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "location", "Warmwell in Dorset"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "location", "Middle Wallop"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "location", "Kenley"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "aircraft", "Spitfire R6690"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "killed in action", "shot down during an attack on German bombers over London"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "memorialized in book", "Spitfire Pilot by David Crook"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "memorialized in museum", "Imperial War Museum at Lambeth"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "memorialized in hut", "Memorial Hut at Elvington Airfield for the Yorkshire Air Museum"],["Geoffrey Norman Gaunt", "memorialized in hut", "contains replica Spitfire and wartime portraits"]]
Legions of Thyatis is an adventure module published in 1990 for the "Dungeons & Dragons" fantasy role-playing game. <S> [["Legions of Thyatis", "instance of", "Adventure module"], ["Legions of Thyatis", "published in", "1990"], ["Legions of Thyatis", "for game", "Dungeons & Dragons"], ["Dungeons & Dragons", "genre", "Fantasy role-playing game"]]
Eriogonum spectabile is a rare species of wild buckwheat known by the common name Barron's buckwheat. It is endemic to Plumas County, California, where it is known from two occurrences in Lassen National Forest near Chester. There are approximately 250 individuals in existence. It grows in scrubby, forested mountain habitat, only on glaciated andesite substrates. This rare plant was discovered in 1997 and described to science as a new species in 2001.This is a small, compact shrub growing in a mat up to 25 centimeters wide and 15 tall. The spreading stems bear woolly foliage, each leaf with an oval blade up to 2 centimeters long by 1 wide. The plant blooms with slender, erect flowering stems bearing umbels of flowers. The flowers are white, aging pink, hairy and glandular, and about half a centimeter long.The main threat to this species is logging. Other threats include herbivory, competition with other plants, climate change, and changes in the fire regime of its native forest. <S> [["Eriogonum spectabile", "instance of", "Species"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "common name", "Barron's buckwheat"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "endemic to", "Plumas County, California"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "occurrences", "Lassen National Forest near Chester"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "number of individuals", "approximately 250"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "habitat", "scrubby, forested mountain habitat"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "substrates", "glaciated andesite"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "discovered", "1997"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "described as new species", "2001"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "size", "small, compact shrub up to 25 cm wide and 15 cm tall"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "foliage", "woolly"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "leaf size", "2 cm long by 1 cm wide"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "flowering stems", "slender, erect"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "flower color", "white, aging pink"], ["Eriogonum spectabile", "flower size", "about 0.5 cm long"], ["main threat to Eriogonum spectabile", "logging"], ["other threats to Eriogonum spectabile", "herbivory, competition with other plants, climate change, changes in fire regime"]]
The Heart Specialist is a 2006 American romantic comedy-drama film written, produced and directed by Dennis Cooper, and starring Wood Harris, Zoe Saldana, Brian J. White and Mýa. Originally released under the title Ways of the Flesh, the film premiered at the 2006 Boston Film Festival and remained unreleased until 2011, when it was granted a limited theatrical release by Freestyle Releasing. <S> [["The Heart Specialist", "instance of", "Film"], ["The Heart Specialist", "genre", "Romantic comedy-drama"], ["The Heart Specialist", "year", "2006"], ["The Heart Specialist", "country", "United States"], ["The Heart Specialist", "writer", "Dennis Cooper"], ["The Heart Specialist", "producer", "Dennis Cooper"], ["The Heart Specialist", "director", "Dennis Cooper"], ["The Heart Specialist", "cast", "Wood Harris"], ["The Heart Specialist", "cast", "Zoe Saldana"], ["The Heart Specialist", "cast", "Brian J. White"], ["The Heart Specialist", "cast", "Mýa"], ["The Heart Specialist", "original title", "Ways of the Flesh"], ["The Heart Specialist", "premiere", "2006 Boston Film Festival"], ["The Heart Specialist", "release date", "2011"], ["The Heart Specialist", "distributor", "Freestyle Releasing"]]
The Boston Bridge is a structure that crosses the Youghiogheny River between Versailles and Elizabeth Township, Pennsylvania. Its name is derived from the Massachusetts city only indirectly: the bridge is named for the Boston neighborhood of Elizabeth Township, which in turn was named for the New England city.The bridge, which opened in 1931, carries Pennsylvania Route 48 on two relatively narrow lanes. Many of its features were carefully preserved during a 1989 rehabilitation, down to its original pedestrian railings. Designed entirely for vehicular traffic, the structure changed the future of Elizabeth Township; the lack of streetcar tracks led to the abandonment of a line that served the then-rural community's small industrial settlements, while the newfound ease of access for motorists to the area's manufacturing regions opened up the township to suburbanization. <S> [["Boston Bridge", "instance of", "Structure"], ["Boston Bridge", "crosses", "Youghiogheny River"], ["Boston Bridge", "location", "Versailles"], ["Boston Bridge", "location", "Elizabeth Township"], ["Boston Bridge", "name derived from", "Massachusetts city"], ["Boston Bridge", "named for", "Boston neighborhood of Elizabeth Township"], ["Boston Bridge", "opened in", "1931"], ["Boston Bridge", "carries", "Pennsylvania Route 48"], ["Boston Bridge", "features preserved during", "1989 rehabilitation"], ["Boston Bridge", "designed for", "vehicular traffic"], ["Boston Bridge", "changed future of", "Elizabeth Township"], ["Boston Bridge", "led to abandonment of", "streetcar line"], ["Boston Bridge", "opened up township to", "suburbanization"]]
Štajerska Vas (; ) is a small village in the Municipality of Slovenske Konjice in eastern Slovenia. It lies immediately northeast of Loče. The area is part of the traditional region of Styria and is now included in the Savinja Statistical Region. The settlement of Štajerska Vas was created in 1999, when it was administratively separated from Spodnji Jernej. <S> [["Štajerska Vas", "instance of", "Village"], ["Štajerska Vas", "located in", "Municipality of Slovenske Konjice"], ["Štajerska Vas", "region", "Styria"], ["Štajerska Vas", "included in", "Savinja Statistical Region"], ["Štajerska Vas", "created in", "1999"], ["Štajerska Vas", "administratively separated from", "Spodnji Jernej"], ["Štajerska Vas", "located northeast of", "Loče"]]
Thomas Edwardston (died 1396), was an Augustinian friar.Edwardston is said to have been born at a place called Edwardston in Suffolk, whence he derived his name. He studied at the University of Oxford, where he obtained the D.D. degree. He became a friar eremite of the order of St. Augustine at the monastery of Clare in his native county, and was eventually made prior. He was confessor to Lionel, duke of Clarence, and accompanied him to Italy on the occasion of his marriage with the daughter of the Duke of Milan.On his return to England, Edwardston took over the charge of archiepiscopal duties, but in what diocese is not known; it was probably in a temporary vacancy, for it does not appear that he was ever raised to the full dignity of an archbishop. He died at Clare 20 May 1396, and was buried in his monastery. He was the author of "Sermones Solemnes", "Determinationes Theologicæ", and "Lecturæ Scholasticæ". <S> [    ["Thomas Edwardston", "instance of", "Augustinian friar"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "death date", "1396"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "birth place", "Edwardston, Suffolk"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "education", "University of Oxford"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "degree obtained", "D.D."],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "order", "St. Augustine"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "monastery", "Clare"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "prior of", "Clare monastery"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "confessor to", "Lionel, duke of Clarence"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "accompaniment", "Italy"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "marriage with", "daughter of Duke of Milan"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "return to England", "charge of archiepiscopal duties"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "diocese", "unknown"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "death place", "Clare"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "burial place", "monastery"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "author of", "Sermones Solemnes"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "author of", "Determinationes Theologicæ"],    ["Thomas Edwardston", "author of", "Lecturæ Scholasticæ"]]
Nandanpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency) was an assembly constituency in Paschim Medinipur district in the Indian state of West Bengal. <S> [["Nandanpur", "instance of", "Vidhan Sabha constituency"], ["Nandanpur", "located in", "Paschim Medinipur district"], ["Nandanpur", "located in", "West Bengal"], ["Nandanpur", "country", "India"]]
The Localism Act 2011 (c. 20) is an Act of Parliament that changes the powers of local government in England. The aim of the act is to facilitate the devolution of decision-making powers from central government control to individuals and communities. The measures affected by the Act include an increase in the number of elected mayors, referendums and the "Local authority’s general power of competence" (Part 1, chapter 1) which states "A local authority has power to do anything that individuals generally may do".The official summary of the act is: Although the act was envisaged as having the potential to bring about wide-scale decentralisation, there have been few significant examples of its implementation. Mayor of Hackney Jules Pipe criticised it, saying that it "does not challenge the deep-rooted centralisation in the UK". One notable outcome of the act has been the combined authorities formed by local authorities pooling their powers of transport and economy and gaining certain functions delegated from central government. As a result, there have been calls for legislation to bring about further devolution to the Core Cities Group, leading to the introduction of the Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016. <S> [    ["Localism Act 2011", "instance of", "Act of Parliament"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "country", "England"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "aim", "facilitate devolution of decision-making powers"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "measures affected", "increase in number of elected mayors, referendums, Local authority’s general power of competence"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "official summary", "potential for wide-scale decentralisation, few significant examples of implementation"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "criticism", "Mayor of Hackney Jules Pipe"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "notable outcome", "formation of combined authorities by local authorities"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "result", "calls for further devolution to Core Cities Group"],    ["Localism Act 2011", "result", "introduction of Cities and Local Government Devolution Act 2016"]]
Acalyptris krugeri is a moth of the family Nepticulidae. It was described by Vári in 1963. It is known from South Africa (it was described from Kruger National Park).The larvae feed on "Schotia brachypetala". <S> [["Acalyptris krugeri", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "family", "Nepticulidae"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "described by", "Vári"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "year described", "1963"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "country", "South Africa"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "location described", "Kruger National Park"], ["Acalyptris krugeri", "larvae feed on", "Schotia brachypetala"]]
Atesh Salih is an actor and male model turned interior designer. He is best known for his stint for Giorgio Armani and has also done photo shoots for fashion magazines such as Wallpaper*, GQ and Vogue Hommes. He has also modeled for Cerruti, Swatch, among others. <S> [["Atesh Salih", "profession", "Actor"], ["Atesh Salih", "profession", "Male model"], ["Atesh Salih", "profession", "Interior designer"], ["Atesh Salih", "best known for", "Giorgio Armani"], ["Atesh Salih", "photo shoots for", "Wallpaper*"], ["Atesh Salih", "photo shoots for", "GQ"], ["Atesh Salih", "photo shoots for", "Vogue Hommes"], ["Atesh Salih", "modeled for", "Cerruti"], ["Atesh Salih", "modeled for", "Swatch"]]
Sin Du-ho (born 13 October 1934) is a South Korean fencer. He competed in the individual and team foil and épée events at the 1964 Summer Olympics. <S> [["Sin Du-ho", "instance of", "Fencer"], ["Sin Du-ho", "country", "South Korea"], ["Sin Du-ho", "born on", "13 October 1934"], ["Sin Du-ho", "competed in", "1964 Summer Olympics"], ["Sin Du-ho", "events", "Individual foil, Team foil, Individual épée, Team épée"]]
Jim Jumani Johansson (legally "Jim Jumani Immanuel Masauko Kamuzu Banda") (2 May 1973 – 26 January 2019) was a Malawian-Swedish man who claimed to be the son of the late Malawian President Hastings Kamuzu Banda (1898-1997). He changed his name to Jim Jumani Immanuel Masauko Kamuzu Banda. Johansson says that it was after Banda died in 1997 that 'some government officials' told him about who his father really was. Officially, Banda died childless and unmarried. His claim and resemblance to the former dictator opened up many unanswered questions about the legacy of Banda. Johansson became a celebrity overnight in Malawi owing to his uncanny resemblance to the former president and his measures to seek legal means of proving his identity. Malawians were divided on whether he was the true heir but the public demanded a right to know as well. Focus Gwede, the head of Banda's Special Branch of Secret Police Services, came out in support of Johansson, claiming in 2010 that Banda had fathered three children. <S> [    ["Jim Jumani Johansson", "date of birth", "2 May 1973"],    ["Jim Jumani Johansson", "date of death", "26 January 2019"],    ["Jim Jumani Johansson", "nationality", "Malawian-Swedish"],    ["Jim Jumani Johansson", "claim", "son of Hastings Kamuzu Banda"],    ["Jim Jumani Johansson", "name change", "Jim Jumani Immanuel Masauko Kamuzu Banda"],    ["Hastings Kamuzu Banda", "date of birth", "1898"],    ["Hastings Kamuzu Banda", "date of death", "1997"],    ["Hastings Kamuzu Banda", "childless", "true"],    ["Hastings Kamuzu Banda", "unmarried", "true"],    ["Focus Gwede", "position", "head of Banda's Special Branch of Secret Police Services"],    ["Focus Gwede", "support", "Jim Jumani Johansson"],    ["Focus Gwede", "claim", "Banda fathered three children"]]
Mary Knight Wood Mason (17 April 1857 – 20 December 1944) was an American pianist, music educator and composer. She was born in Easthampton, Massachusetts, the daughter of Lieutenant-governor, manufacturer and philanthropist Horatio G. Knight and Mary Ann Huntoon Knight. She was educated at Charlier Institute in New York City and Miss Porter's School in Farmington, Connecticut, studying music with Karl Klauser, Benjamin Johnson Lang and Henry Holden Huss.Knight married Charles Greenleaf Wood of Boston in 1879, and Alfred Bishop Mason of New York in 1914, after which she lived in New York City and summered at a cabin in the Catskill Mountains. She died in Florence, Italy. <S> [    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "instance of", "Pianist"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "instance of", "Music educator"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "instance of", "Composer"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "birth date", "17 April 1857"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "death date", "20 December 1944"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "birth place", "Easthampton, Massachusetts"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "father", "Horatio G. Knight"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "mother", "Mary Ann Huntoon Knight"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "education", "Charlier Institute, New York City"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "education", "Miss Porter's School, Farmington, Connecticut"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "music teachers", "Karl Klauser"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "music teachers", "Benjamin Johnson Lang"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "music teachers", "Henry Holden Huss"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "spouse", "Charles Greenleaf Wood"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "spouse", "Alfred Bishop Mason"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "residence", "New York City"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "summer residence", "Catskill Mountains"],    ["Mary Knight Wood Mason", "death place", "Florence, Italy"]]
Ahmed Walid Ferhat (born 22 July 1986 in El Harrach, Algiers Province) is an Algerian professional footballer. He currently plays as a forward for the Algerian Ligue 2 club Olympique de Médéa. <S> [["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "instance of", "Professional footballer"], ["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "date of birth", "22 July 1986"], ["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "place of birth", "El Harrach, Algiers Province"], ["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "nationality", "Algerian"], ["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "position", "Forward"], ["Ahmed Walid Ferhat", "current club", "Olympique de Médéa"], ["Olympique de Médéa", "league", "Algerian Ligue 2"]]
The Mikhailovsky Palace () is a grand ducal palace in Saint Petersburg, Russia. It is located on Arts Square and is an example of Empire style neoclassicism. The palace currently houses the main building of the Russian Museum and displays its collections of early, folk, eighteenth, and nineteenth century art. It was originally planned as the residence of Grand Duke Michael Pavlovich, the youngest son of Emperor Paul I. Work had not yet begun on the Mikhailovsky Palace, when Paul was overthrown and killed in a palace coup that brought Michael's elder brother to the throne as Alexander I. The new emperor resurrected the idea for a new palace by the time Michael was 22, and plans were drawn up by Carlo Rossi to develop a new site in Saint Petersburg. The palace, built in the neoclassic style, became the centrepiece of an ensemble that took in new streets and squares. It was lavishly decorated, with the interiors costing more than the main construction work. It was gifted to Grand Duke Michael and his new wife, Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna, by the Emperor in 1825. The grand ducal family had comfortable apartments furnished to their individual tastes. Grand Duke Michael carried out some of his military duties there, while his wife hosted salons that brought together many of the leading members of Saint Petersburg society and culture. The Grand Duchess continued this lifestyle after her husband's death in 1849, until her own death in 1873. The palace was passed on to the couple's daughter, Grand Duchess Catherine Mikhailovna.Over the years of their residency, the family renovated and refurbished the palace's rooms in keeping with contemporary tastes. By the time of Grand Duchess Catherine's death in 1894, the staterooms were no longer in regular use—the family resided for the most part in the palace's wings. With the death of the Grand Duchess, the palace was inherited by her children, who were members of the family of the Dukes of Mecklenburg-Strelitz. Concerned about the palace passing out of the Romanov family, Emperor Alexander III decided to buy it back for the state. He died before this could be arranged, but the negotiations were carried out on behalf of his son Emperor Nicholas II, by Minister of Finance Sergei Witte. Nicholas gave it to the newly established Russian Museum, in honour of his father, with the remit that it collect and display domestic art. The palace was extensively renovated to fit its new role, with some of the interiors retained. One wing was demolished and rebuilt, later becoming the Russian Museum of Ethnography, while a new extension, the Benois wing, was added in the 1910s. <S> [["Mikhailovsky Palace", "instance of", "Grand ducal palace"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "located in", "Saint Petersburg, Russia"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "style", "Empire style neoclassicism"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "currently houses", "main building of the Russian Museum"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "displays collections of", "early, folk, eighteenth, and nineteenth century art"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "planned as residence of", "Grand Duke Michael Pavlovich"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "built by", "Carlo Rossi"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "gifted to", "Grand Duke Michael and Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna by the Emperor in 1825"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "resided by", "Grand Duke Michael and Grand Duchess Elena Pavlovna"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "inherited by", "Grand Duchess Catherine Mikhailovna"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "renovated and refurbished by", "the family over the years"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "bought back for the state by", "Emperor Alexander III"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "given to", "Russian Museum by Emperor Nicholas II"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "renovated for new role by", "Russian Museum"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "demolished and rebuilt to become", "Russian Museum of Ethnography"],["Mikhailovsky Palace", "new extension added in the 1910s called", "Benois wing"]]
Marcel Rooney, O.S.B. was the eighth Abbot Primate of the Benedictine Confederation. He was born on 20 September 1937, professed solemn vows 12 September 1958 and was ordained to the priesthood on 21 September 1963. He was elected Abbot of Conception Abbey on 14 April 1993, was blessed 10 May 1993, was elected Abbot Primate and Abbot of Sant’Anselmo on 18 September 1996 and resigned on 3 September 2000. <S> [["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "position", "Abbot Primate"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "birth date", "20 September 1937"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "solemn vows date", "12 September 1958"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "ordination date", "21 September 1963"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "Abbot of Conception Abbey election date", "14 April 1993"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "Abbot of Conception Abbey blessing date", "10 May 1993"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "Abbot Primate and Abbot of Sant’Anselmo election date", "18 September 1996"], ["Marcel Rooney, O.S.B.", "resignation date", "3 September 2000"]]
Rehar is a small town in Bijnor district, in Uttar Pradesh state, India. <S> [["Rehar", "instance of", "Town"], ["Rehar", "located in", "Bijnor district"], ["Rehar", "located in", "Uttar Pradesh state"], ["Rehar", "country", "India"]]
From the Towers of the Moon is an opera in one act by Robert Moran, with a libretto by Michael John LaChiusa. It is based on the classic Japanese tale "Princess Kaguya", or "The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter", which tells of a princess from the Moon who comes to Earth. Moran knew the story as "The Tale of the Shining Princess" and had seen a film adaptation of the legend, "Princess from the Moon", made by Kon Ichikawa in 1987. Moran's third opera, it was commissioned and premiered by the Minnesota Opera in 1992. Four excerpts, written for string quartet, were recorded as "Music from the Towers of the Moon" by the Balanescu Quartet. <S> [["From the Towers of the Moon", "instance of", "Opera"], ["From the Towers of the Moon", "composer", "Robert Moran"], ["From the Towers of the Moon", "librettist", "Michael John LaChiusa"], ["From the Towers of the Moon", "based on", "Princess Kaguya"], ["Princess Kaguya", "also known as", "The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter"], ["Princess Kaguya", "origin", "Japan"], ["Princess Kaguya", "plot", "princess from the Moon comes to Earth"], ["Robert Moran", "opera count", 3], ["Minnesota Opera", "commissioned and premiered", "From the Towers of the Moon"], ["Balanescu Quartet", "recorded", "Music from the Towers of the Moon"]]
The 31st Golden Raspberry Awards, or Razzies, was a parodic award ceremony that was held on February 26, 2011, at the Barnsdall Gallery Theatre in Hollywood, California to honor the worst films the film industry had to offer in 2010. The nominations were announced on January 24. Per Razzies tradition, both the nominee announcements and ceremony preceded the corresponding Academy Awards functions by one day. "The Last Airbender" was the big winner of 2010, with five awards, including Worst Picture. <S> [["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "instance of", "Award ceremony"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "date", "February 26, 2011"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "location", "Barnsdall Gallery Theatre"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "city", "Hollywood"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "state", "California"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "purpose", "Honor worst films"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "year", "2010"], ["31st Golden Raspberry Awards", "big winner", "The Last Airbender"], ["The Last Airbender", "awards", "5"], ["The Last Airbender", "category", "Worst Picture"]]
The Ganesha University of Education is a university located in Singaraja, Bali, Indonesia. The university has been previously known by the name IKIP Singaraja. <S> [["Ganesha University of Education", "instance of", "University"], ["Ganesha University of Education", "location", "Singaraja, Bali, Indonesia"], ["Ganesha University of Education", "previous name", "IKIP Singaraja"]]
A PhD-MBA or MBA-PhD is a dual degree program offered in some cases by schools of science, engineering or social science, jointly with business schools. The program generally lasts four to eight years and results in the candidate earning both a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) degree and a Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree. Students may apply to the joint program before matriculating to either program, or after matriculating to the PhD programme. The programme often attracts entrepreneurs and venture capitalists.Some of the leading PhD-MBA programs are offered by universities like:* The Wake Forest University PhD/MBA program was established in 1999 and was the first of its type in the nation. The program is a joint degree between the Wake Forest University Graduate School of Arts and Sciences and the Wake Forest Schools of Business. Dr. Dwayne Godwin is the program director. The degrees are earned concurrently and the average time to awarding both degrees is 5.2 years. * The University of Delaware's Department of Biological Sciences and the Alfred Lerner College of Business and Economics, jointly administer this program since 2006.* Dartmouth, in USA since 2009,* Yale University, Yale Graduate School of Arts and Sciences with Yale School of Management* University of Miami* Penn State College of Medicine* The alliance of two members of Sorbonne University and the Collège des Ingénieurs: UMPC for Sciences and Technology and Paris-Sorbonne for Humanities, in France since 2009,* or the similar alliance of KIT and the Collège des Ingénieurs, in Germany since 2010,* National University of Singapore (since 2011).These programs are aimed at creating entrepreneurs and future technology leaders. <S> [    ["PhD-MBA", "is a", "dual degree program"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "schools of science, engineering, or social science"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered jointly with", "business schools"],    ["PhD-MBA", "lasts", "four to eight years"],    ["PhD-MBA", "results in", "earning both a PhD and MBA degree"],    ["PhD-MBA", "attracts", "entrepreneurs and venture capitalists"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "Wake Forest University"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "University of Delaware"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "Dartmouth"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "Yale University"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "University of Miami"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "Penn State College of Medicine"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "Sorbonne University and Collège des Ingénieurs"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "KIT and Collège des Ingénieurs"],    ["PhD-MBA", "offered by", "National University of Singapore"],    ["PhD-MBA", "aimed at", "creating entrepreneurs and future technology leaders"]]
