Shuhei Fukuda (Japanese:福田 秀平, born February 2, 1989) is a Japanese professional baseball player for the Chiba Lotte Marines of the Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB). He previously played for the Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks. He played for the Brisbane Bandits of the Australian Baseball League in 2010.On November 26, Fukuda signed with the Chiba Lotte Marines. <S> [["Shuhei Fukuda", "nationality", "Japanese"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "date of birth", "February 2, 1989"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "occupation", "Professional baseball player"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "team", "Chiba Lotte Marines"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "previous team", "Fukuoka SoftBank Hawks"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "played for", "Brisbane Bandits"], ["Shuhei Fukuda", "league", "Nippon Professional Baseball"], ["Brisbane Bandits", "league", "Australian Baseball League"], ["Fukuda", "signed with", "Chiba Lotte Marines"]]
Weymouth Lifeboat Station is the base for Royal National Lifeboat Institution (RNLI) search and rescue operations at Weymouth in Dorset, England. The first lifeboat was stationed in the town in 1869. Since 2002 it has operated a all-weather lifeboat (ALB) and an inshore lifeboat (ILB). <S> [["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "instance of", "Base"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "location", "Weymouth"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "operated by", "Royal National Lifeboat Institution"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "location", "Dorset"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "country", "England"], ["First lifeboat", "stationed in", "Weymouth"], ["First lifeboat", "year", "1869"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "operates", "all-weather lifeboat"], ["Weymouth Lifeboat Station", "operates", "inshore lifeboat"], ["All-weather lifeboat", "abbreviation", "ALB"], ["Inshore lifeboat", "abbreviation", "ILB"]]
Pirlitor was a medieval fortress in Mount Durmitor, in Old Herzegovina (part of present-day Montenegro), built at the edge of the deep canyon of the Tara River. Only a part of the wall at the fortress's highest point has survived to the present day. It is located 16 km from the town of Žabljak, at the altitude of about 1450 meters. Pirlitor overlooked the medieval road between Nikšić and Pljevlja, at the place where the road descended from Durmitor's Lake Plateau into the canyon.Pirlitor is not mentioned in medieval sources. It is known that Voivode Sandalj Hranić had a court on the Lake Plateau, where his successor Voivode Stjepan Vukčić negotiated peace with the Ragusans in 1453. This court could actually be Pirlitor, since it is the only fortification known to have been built on the plateau.According to the Serbian epic poetry, Pirlitor belonged to Voivode Momčilo, a man of immense size and strength who possessed magical attributes: a winged horse named Jabučilo and a sabre with eyes. His sister Jevrosima was the legendary mother of Prince Marko, one of the greatest heroes of Serbian epic poems. In one of them, the situation of the "Pirlitor Castle" is described like this: <S> [["Pirlitor", "instance of", "Medieval fortress"], ["Pirlitor", "location", "Mount Durmitor"], ["Pirlitor", "located in", "Old Herzegovina"], ["Old Herzegovina", "part of", "Montenegro"], ["Pirlitor", "surviving feature", "Part of wall at highest point"], ["Pirlitor", "distance from town", "16 km"], ["Pirlitor", "altitude", "1450 meters"], ["Pirlitor", "overlooking", "Medieval road between Nikšić and Pljevlja"], ["Pirlitor", "historical figure", "Voivode Sandalj Hranić"], ["Voivode Sandalj Hranić", "successor", "Voivode Stjepan Vukčić"], ["Voivode Stjepan Vukčić", "negotiated peace with", "Ragusans in 1453"], ["Pirlitor", "mentioned in", "Serbian epic poetry"], ["Pirlitor", "belonged to", "Voivode Momčilo"], ["Voivode Momčilo", "possessions", "Winged horse named Jabučilo and a sabre with eyes"], ["Voivode Momčilo", "sister", "Jevrosima"], ["Jevrosima", "mother of", "Prince Marko"], ["Prince Marko", "hero of", "Serbian epic poems"]]
Departing is the second full-length album by Canadian indie rock band The Rural Alberta Advantage, released March 1, 2011 on Paper Bag Records in Canada and Saddle Creek Records in the United States.In a review of their December 2010 concert performance at Lee's Palace, "The Globe and Mail" recommended the album as a must-hear for 2011.The album was named as a longlisted nominee for the 2011 Polaris Music Prize.The song "Tornado '87" is about the Edmonton tornado of July 31, 1987, which occurred when band leader Nils Edenloff was living in that city. <S> [["Departing", "instance of", "Album"], ["Departing", "released on", "March 1, 2011"], ["Departing", "record label", "Paper Bag Records"], ["Departing", "record label", "Saddle Creek Records"], ["Departing", "country", "Canada"], ["Departing", "country", "United States"], ["The Rural Alberta Advantage", "band member", "Nils Edenloff"], ["The Rural Alberta Advantage", "band leader", "Nils Edenloff"], ["The Rural Alberta Advantage", "song", "Tornado '87"], ["Edmonton tornado", "date", "July 31, 1987"], ["Edmonton tornado", "location", "Edmonton"], ["The Globe and Mail", "reviewed", "December 2010 concert performance at Lee's Palace"], ["The Globe and Mail", "recommended", "must-hear for 2011"], ["Polaris Music Prize", "year", "2011"], ["Polaris Music Prize", "nominee", "longlisted"]]
Joan Perry (July 7, 1911 – September 16, 1996), born Elizabeth Rosiland Miller, was an American film actress, model, and singer. Known as Betty Miller when she was a model, <S> [["Joan Perry", "instance of", "Film actress"], ["Joan Perry", "instance of", "Model"], ["Joan Perry", "instance of", "Singer"], ["Joan Perry", "birth date", "July 7, 1911"], ["Joan Perry", "death date", "September 16, 1996"], ["Joan Perry", "birth name", "Elizabeth Rosiland Miller"], ["Joan Perry", "also known as", "Betty Miller"]]
Yale Publishing Course (YPC), located on the campus of Yale University in New Haven, Connecticut, is an intensive program for magazine, book and online publishing professionals. The course focuses on teaching leadership skills for today's increasingly global, increasingly digital environment. YPC's curriculum is geared to middle and upper-level professionals from all over the world. Its speakers include publishing and media executives as well as faculty from the Yale School of Management and Yale University Press staff. The Yale Course is the only advanced-level program for senior managers in the publishing industry.The program combines plenary sessions with smaller group discussions focused on specific issues and case studies. The curriculum includes sessions on such topics as: strategic planning; financial management and entrepreneurship; best practices in the use of new technology and content delivery; legal challenges in multi-platform publishing; licensing and marketing internationally; and the future of digital dissemination. Faculty office hours facilitate one-on-one meetings with students to explore specific questions or challenges. <S> [["Yale Publishing Course", "located in", "Yale University"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "located in", "New Haven, Connecticut"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "program for", "magazine, book and online publishing professionals"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "focuses on", "teaching leadership skills"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "geared to", "middle and upper-level professionals"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "speakers include", "publishing and media executives"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "speakers include", "faculty from Yale School of Management"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "speakers include", "Yale University Press staff"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "combines", "plenary sessions with smaller group discussions"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "strategic planning"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "financial management and entrepreneurship"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "best practices in the use of new technology and content delivery"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "legal challenges in multi-platform publishing"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "licensing and marketing internationally"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "curriculum includes sessions on", "future of digital dissemination"], ["Yale Publishing Course", "faculty office hours facilitate", "one-on-one meetings with students"]]
Kalungu District is a district in Central Uganda. It is named after the main town of the district, Kalungu, where the district headquarters are located. <S> [["Kalungu District", "instance of", "District"], ["Kalungu District", "located in", "Central Uganda"], ["Kalungu District", "named after", "Kalungu"], ["Kalungu District", "headquarters located in", "Kalungu"]]
Phyllonorycter acaciella is a moth of the family Gracillariidae. It is found in southern Europe, but not on the Iberian Peninsula and Balkan Peninsula.The larvae feed on "Ulmus glabra", "Ulmus laevis" and "Ulmus minor". They mine the leaves of their host plant. They create a lower-surface (but sometimes upper-surface) weakly folded tentiform mine. The folded side of the mine is ochraceous. The pupa is blackish and found within the mine, in a very loose cocoon. <S> [["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "instance of", "Moth"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "family", "Gracillariidae"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "habitat", "Southern Europe"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "host plant", "Ulmus glabra"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "host plant", "Ulmus laevis"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "host plant", "Ulmus minor"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "feeding behavior", "Leaf mining"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "mine type", "Tentiform"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "mine color", "Ochraceous"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "pupa color", "Blackish"], ["Phyllonorycter acaciella", "cocoon location", "Within mine"]]
Maura McNiel (April 11, 1921 – July 18, 2020) was an American feminist whose actions paved the way for women's studies, modern social work, advocacy on behalf of abused women, promotion of the Equal Rights Amendment, and passage of Title IX. McNiel was active for over forty years in the Dallas women's movement. She died on July 18, 2020, aged 99. <S> [["Maura McNiel", "instance of", "American feminist"], ["Maura McNiel", "birth date", "April 11, 1921"], ["Maura McNiel", "death date", "July 18, 2020"], ["Maura McNiel", "age", "99"], ["Maura McNiel", "contributions", "paved the way for women's studies, modern social work, advocacy on behalf of abused women, promotion of the Equal Rights Amendment, and passage of Title IX"], ["Maura McNiel", "active in", "Dallas women's movement for over forty years"]]
Bhandgaon is a village in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of state of Maharashtra, India. <S> [["Bhandgaon", "instance of", "Village"], ["Bhandgaon", "located in", "Parner taluka"], ["Bhandgaon", "located in", "Ahmednagar district"], ["Bhandgaon", "located in", "Maharashtra"], ["Bhandgaon", "country", "India"]]
Ali S. Khan is an American practicing physician and former Director of the Office of Public Health Preparedness and Response (PHPR) at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Since July 2014, he has served as Dean of the College of Public Health and Retired Assistant Surgeon General at the University of Nebraska Medical Center in Omaha, Nebraska. <S> [["Ali S. Khan", "nationality", "American"], ["Ali S. Khan", "occupation", "Physician"], ["Ali S. Khan", "position", "Former Director of PHPR"], ["Ali S. Khan", "organization", "Centers for Disease Control and Prevention"], ["Ali S. Khan", "position", "Dean of College of Public Health"], ["Ali S. Khan", "position", "Retired Assistant Surgeon General"], ["Ali S. Khan", "organization", "University of Nebraska Medical Center"], ["Ali S. Khan", "location", "Omaha, Nebraska"]]
Patharwadi is a village in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of state of Maharashtra, India.The Village Patharwadi is 2 km away from the famous village Nighoj, wherein Goddess Malaganga Temple is famous for worship. The population of Pataharwadi is between about 3000 to 3500.In Patharwadi itself includes the small sections of Bodagewadi, Ghodoba vasti, Khillarwasti, Derul Mala etc. Most of the students study at Nighoj for their secondary education as there is only the Z. P primary school available in village. Nearly 10% of the total population is living in the city of Mumbai. Many of the people are highly educated and work as government servants, in their own businesses or in the private sector.The village is famous for its Yatra and saptah.Bodagewadi is also having temple of Malganaga Devi. The Famous Pot Holes of Nighoj is only 2 km distance from BodagewadiBodagewadi is famous for Lezim Mandal & Kranti Yuva Group. <S> [["Patharwadi", "instance of", "Village"], ["Patharwadi", "located in", "Parner taluka"], ["Patharwadi", "located in", "Ahmednagar district"], ["Patharwadi", "located in", "Maharashtra"], ["Patharwadi", "country", "India"], ["Patharwadi", "distance from", "Nighoj", "2 km"], ["Patharwadi", "population", "3000 to 3500"], ["Patharwadi", "includes", "Bodagewadi"], ["Patharwadi", "includes", "Ghodoba vasti"], ["Patharwadi", "includes", "Khillarwasti"], ["Patharwadi", "includes", "Derul Mala"], ["Patharwadi", "education", "Z. P primary school"], ["Patharwadi", "population living in", "Mumbai", "10%"], ["Patharwadi", "famous for", "Yatra"], ["Patharwadi", "famous for", "saptah"], ["Bodagewadi", "instance of", "Village"], ["Bodagewadi", "distance from", "Nighoj", "2 km"], ["Bodagewadi", "famous for", "Lezim Mandal"], ["Bodagewadi", "famous for", "Kranti Yuva Group"], ["Bodagewadi", "has temple of", "Malganaga Devi"], ["Nighoj", "famous for", "Pot Holes"]]
Pimpri Pathar is a village in Parner taluka in Ahmednagar district of state of Maharashtra, India. <S> [["Pimpri Pathar", "instance of", "Village"], ["Pimpri Pathar", "located in", "Parner taluka"], ["Pimpri Pathar", "located in", "Ahmednagar district"], ["Pimpri Pathar", "located in", "Maharashtra, India"]]
Treemont Manor is a historic home located at Colonie in Albany County, New York. It was built in 1929 and is an "L" shaped Georgian Revival style mansion. It set within a formal English garden. The main house is two and one half stories with a gable roof, with a two-story servant's wing attached. Also on the property is a contributing guest house.It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985. <S> [["Treemont Manor", "instance of", "Historic home"], ["Treemont Manor", "located at", "Colonie, Albany County, New York"], ["Treemont Manor", "built in", "1929"], ["Treemont Manor", "architectural style", "Georgian Revival"], ["Treemont Manor", "features", "Formal English garden"], ["Treemont Manor", "stories", "2.5"], ["Treemont Manor", "roof style", "Gable"], ["Treemont Manor", "includes", "Servant's wing"], ["Treemont Manor", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places in 1985"]]
The Knocks is an American electronic music duo consisting of Ben "B-Roc" Ruttner and James "JPatt" Patterson. They are known for their own releases on labels such as Kitsuné, Big Beat Records, Neon Gold and Atlantic Records and for their remixes featured on HypeMachine, Beatport, and various DJs' set lists. They are also known for their singles "Classic," featuring the duo Powers, "I Wish (My Taylor Swift)" which was collaborated with Matthew Koma and "Kiss The Sky", featuring Wyclef Jean. Their debut album, "55", was released on March 4, 2016. Their sophomore album, "New York Narcotic", was released on September 28, 2018, spawning singles “Ride or Die” featuring Foster the People and “Brazilian Soul”, Best Friend featuring Sofi Tukker. <S> [["The Knocks", "instance of", "Music duo"], ["The Knocks", "members", "Ben Ruttner"], ["The Knocks", "members", "James Patterson"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "releases on Kitsuné"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "releases on Big Beat Records"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "releases on Neon Gold"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "releases on Atlantic Records"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "remixes on HypeMachine"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "remixes on Beatport"], ["The Knocks", "known for", "remixes on DJs' set lists"], ["The Knocks", "singles", "Classic"], ["Classic", "features", "Powers"], ["The Knocks", "singles", "I Wish (My Taylor Swift)"], ["I Wish (My Taylor Swift)", "collaborated with", "Matthew Koma"], ["The Knocks", "singles", "Kiss The Sky"], ["Kiss The Sky", "features", "Wyclef Jean"], ["The Knocks", "albums", "55"], ["55", "release date", "March 4, 2016"], ["The Knocks", "albums", "New York Narcotic"], ["New York Narcotic", "release date", "September 28, 2018"], ["New York Narcotic", "singles", "Ride or Die"], ["Ride or Die", "features", "Foster the People"], ["New York Narcotic", "singles", "Brazilian Soul"], ["Brazilian Soul", "features", "Sofi Tukker"]]
Cousin Sarah is a horror film released in October 2011. Directed by Jenni Gold, the film stars Leah Pipes. Produced by Multi-Valence Productions in association with Willoughby Pictures, the story is by Alexander Garcia, with Alexander Garcia as the writer, and Nathaniel Morin as co-writer. <S> [["Cousin Sarah", "instance of", "Horror film"], ["Cousin Sarah", "release date", "October 2011"], ["Cousin Sarah", "director", "Jenni Gold"], ["Cousin Sarah", "star", "Leah Pipes"], ["Cousin Sarah", "producer", "Multi-Valence Productions"], ["Cousin Sarah", "producer", "Willoughby Pictures"], ["Cousin Sarah", "story by", "Alexander Garcia"], ["Cousin Sarah", "writer", "Alexander Garcia"], ["Cousin Sarah", "co-writer", "Nathaniel Morin"]]
The Infinity Concerto () is a 1984 fantasy novel written by Greg Bear. The plot centers around teenager Michael Perrin's search for what is a "Song of Power" and why some think he can create such a thing. Transported to another realm, he discovers beings known as "the "Sidhe" intervened in Coleridge's incomplete poem, "Kubla Khan". They have stopped others from creating "Songs of Power" and now they are looking at him."The Infinity Concerto" was followed in 1986 by "The Serpent Mage". <S> [["The Infinity Concerto", "instance of", "Fantasy novel"], ["The Infinity Concerto", "author", "Greg Bear"], ["The Infinity Concerto", "publication year", "1984"], ["The Infinity Concerto", "plot centers around", "Michael Perrin's search for a 'Song of Power'"], ["Michael Perrin", "age", "teenager"], ["Michael Perrin", "search for", "Song of Power"], ["Song of Power", "creation", "Michael Perrin"], ["Michael Perrin", "transported to", "another realm"], ["Another realm", "inhabited by", "beings known as 'the Sidhe'"], ["The Sidhe", "intervened in", "Coleridge's incomplete poem 'Kubla Khan'"], ["The Sidhe", "stopped others from creating 'Songs of Power'"], ["The Sidhe", "looking at", "Michael Perrin"], ["The Infinity Concerto", "followed by", "The Serpent Mage"], ["The Serpent Mage", "publication year", "1986"]]
Mark Hodgson (19 November 1880 – 17 October 1967) was a British trade union leader.Born in Hull, Hodgson grew up in Sunderland, studying at Diamond Hall School before taking an apprenticeship as a plater in the shipyard. He joined the United Society of Boilermakers and Iron and Steel Shipbuilders, and in 1913 became the Tyne and Wear delegate on the union's executive council. From 1923 to 1936, he served as the union's chairman, then was elected as its general secretary.While general secretary, Hodgson negotiated on behalf of members during World War II, and took a number of local and national positions. In 1938, he was awarded the OBE, and in 1945 he received a knighthood. He stood down as secretary in 1948, taking a job as chairman of the Northern Regional Board for Industry, serving in this role until 1965. <S> [["Mark Hodgson", "instance of", "British trade union leader"], ["Mark Hodgson", "birth date", "19 November 1880"], ["Mark Hodgson", "death date", "17 October 1967"], ["Mark Hodgson", "birth place", "Hull"], ["Mark Hodgson", "education", "Diamond Hall School"], ["Mark Hodgson", "apprenticeship", "plater in shipyard"], ["Mark Hodgson", "union membership", "United Society of Boilermakers and Iron and Steel Shipbuilders"], ["Mark Hodgson", "union role", "Tyne and Wear delegate"], ["Mark Hodgson", "union role", "chairman"], ["Mark Hodgson", "union role", "general secretary"], ["Mark Hodgson", "honors", "OBE"], ["Mark Hodgson", "honors", "knighthood"], ["Mark Hodgson", "job", "chairman of Northern Regional Board for Industry"], ["Mark Hodgson", "job duration", "1948-1965"], ["Mark Hodgson", "negotiated on behalf of members", "World War II"]]
Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton (7 May 1860 – 24 April 1925) was one of the principal investors and developers of Western Canada, particularly at Winnipeg, Vancouver and Calgary. In the Canadian West, the town of Nanton, Alberta is named for him, and twelve cities and towns have streets named 'Nanton'. Committed to victory in the Great War, he gave over half of his fortune to the war effort and worked himself to an early grave supporting Canadian soldiers in Europe while maintaining Winnipeg's economy. In recognition of his war services he was knighted by George V in 1917 and made a Knight of the Order of St. John of Jerusalem. He died in office as President of The Dominion Bank in Toronto, but is most closely associated with Winnipeg, his home for over forty years and where he is buried. <S> [["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "date of birth", "7 May 1860"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "date of death", "24 April 1925"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "occupation", "Investor"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "occupation", "Developer"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Western Canada"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Winnipeg"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Vancouver"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Calgary"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Nanton, Alberta"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Toronto"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Europe"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Winnipeg"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "location", "Toronto"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "association", "Winnipeg"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "association", "Nanton, Alberta"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "association", "George V"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "association", "Order of St. John of Jerusalem"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "association", "The Dominion Bank"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "contribution", "Great War"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "contribution", "War effort"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "contribution", "Canadian soldiers"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "contribution", "Winnipeg's economy"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "honors", "Knighted by George V in 1917"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "honors", "Knight of the Order of St. John of Jerusalem"], ["Sir Augustus Meredith Nanton", "burial place", "Winnipeg"]]
Masai Ujiri (born 7 July 1970) is a Nigerian-Canadian professional basketball executive and former player, and is the president of basketball operations of the Toronto Raptors in the National Basketball Association (NBA).After a modest playing career, Ujiri became a scout in 2002, first for the Orlando Magic and then the Denver Nuggets. In 2008, he joined the backroom staff of the Toronto Raptors. Ujiri returned to the Nuggets in 2010 as general manager and executive vice president of basketball operations, and helped turn the team's fortunes around, returning them to the playoffs. As a result, he was named the NBA Executive of the Year in 2013. The following season, Ujiri returned to the Raptors as general manager. In the summer of 2016, Masai Ujiri relinquished his title as general manager to Jeff Weltman and accepted the position of president of basketball operations. Weltman was later succeeded by Bobby Webster as general manager a year later. As president, Ujiri worked to usher in a period of sustained success, helping the team win its first NBA championship in 2019.Masai Ujiri was shoved by a law enforcement officer at a basketball game on June 14th, 2019. Masai claimed that this occurred because he is black. <S> [    ["Masai Ujiri", "instance of", "Professional basketball executive"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "instance of", "Former player"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "country of citizenship", "Nigeria"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "country of citizenship", "Canada"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "position held", "President of basketball operations"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "position held", "General manager"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "position held", "Executive vice president of basketball operations"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "position held", "Scout"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "employer", "Toronto Raptors"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "employer", "Orlando Magic"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "employer", "Denver Nuggets"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "award received", "NBA Executive of the Year"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "event", "Shoved by law enforcement officer"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "date of event", "June 14th, 2019"],    ["Masai Ujiri", "claim", "Shoved because he is black"],    ["Toronto Raptors", "event", "Win first NBA championship in 2019"],    ["Jeff Weltman", "succeeded by", "Bobby Webster"]]
Los Trancos Creek (meaning "barriers" or "cattle guards" from the Spanish "Las Trancas") is a creek that flows northerly from Monte Bello Ridge on the northeast slope of the Santa Cruz Mountains to its confluence with San Francisquito Creek at Stanford University in California, United States. The creek forms the boundary between northwestern Santa Clara County and southeastern San Mateo County. <S> [["Los Trancos Creek", "flows from", "Monte Bello Ridge"], ["Los Trancos Creek", "flows to", "San Francisquito Creek"], ["Los Trancos Creek", "location", "California, United States"], ["Los Trancos Creek", "boundary between", "Santa Clara County and San Mateo County"], ["Los Trancos Creek", "meaning", "barriers or cattle guards"], ["Los Trancos Creek", "origin", "Spanish Las Trancas"]]
Selçuk Baştürk (born 29 April 1986 in Üsküdar, İstanbul) is a Turkish professional footballer who plays as a defender for Kozanspor.He started his career with Fenerbahçe A2 and he started his professional career with Mersin Büyükşehir Belediyespor and also played for Turgutluspor.His contract will end on 31 May 2011 by his profile in Turkey Football Federation. <S> [["Selçuk Baştürk", "birth date", "29 April 1986"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "birth place", "Üsküdar, İstanbul"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "nationality", "Turkish"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "occupation", "professional footballer"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "position", "defender"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "current team", "Kozanspor"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "previous teams", "Fenerbahçe A2, Mersin Büyükşehir Belediyespor, Turgutluspor"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "contract end date", "31 May 2011"], ["Selçuk Baştürk", "organization", "Turkey Football Federation"]]
Van Denbergh-Simmons House is a historic home located at Colonie in Albany County, New York. The house was in three phases: the northeast section was built between about 1720 and 1760; the northwest section about 1790; and the south section about 1847. The northeast section is a -story Dutch house with a 1-story porch. The northwest section is a -story ell containing a large kitchen and bee hive oven. The south section is a 2-story Italian Villa style addition with a hipped roof and large square tower at the northwest corner. Also on the property are the remains of a barn foundation.It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1985. <S> [    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "instance of", "Historic home"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "located at", "Colonie, Albany County, New York"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "consists of", "Northeast section"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "consists of", "Northwest section"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "consists of", "South section"],    ["Northeast section", "built between", "1720 and 1760"],    ["Northwest section", "built about", "1790"],    ["South section", "built about", "1847"],    ["Northeast section", "description", "1-story Dutch house with a 1-story porch"],    ["Northwest section", "description", "1.5-story ell containing a large kitchen and bee hive oven"],    ["South section", "description", "2-story Italian Villa style addition with a hipped roof and large square tower at the northwest corner"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places in 1985"],    ["Van Denbergh-Simmons House", "includes", "Remains of a barn foundation"]]
The Chapter of Toledo is a meeting of the heads of the different provinces of the Order of Saint Augustine in Toledo, Spain in 1589. This meeting is considered an important part of the history of the order because this gave birth to the so-called Augustinian Recollection, through the so-called “Fifth Determination”.Today, both the Order of Augustinian Recollects and the Order of Discalced Augustinians trace their beginnings from the fifth determination which says::"Since there is among us, or at least maybe, some who have greater love for monastic perfection and want to follow a more austere plan of life, we ought to favour their legitimate desire by not placing obstacles to the Holy Spirit; having previously consulted our most Reverend Father General and implored his leave, we determine that in our Province three or more monasteries of men and as many of women be designated or established; in them a more austere kind of life is to be practised; its manner is to be regulated, after mature reflection, by the Father Provincial with his definitorum." <S> [["Chapter of Toledo", "instance of", "Meeting"], ["Chapter of Toledo", "location", "Toledo, Spain"], ["Chapter of Toledo", "year", 1589], ["Chapter of Toledo", "importance", "Birth of Augustinian Recollection"], ["Chapter of Toledo", "resulted in", "Fifth Determination"], ["Fifth Determination", "content", "Establishment of more austere monasteries"], ["Fifth Determination", "influenced", "Order of Augustinian Recollects"], ["Fifth Determination", "influenced", "Order of Discalced Augustinians"], ["Fifth Determination", "approval", "Father General"], ["Fifth Determination", "regulation", "Father Provincial with definitorum"]]
Goodrich School is a historic school building located in Colonie in Albany County, New York. It consists of a one-story, gable roofed rectangular brick building built about 1922 with a one-story, rectangular hipped roof wing dated to about 1926. On the south side are a series of two additions completed during the 1950s. The building is in the Classical Revival style and features a prominent portico with curved underside supported by six Doric order fluted columns. Atop the roof is an octagonal wood cupola with a copper roof.It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2000. <S> [["Goodrich School", "instance of", "Historic school building"],["Goodrich School", "located in", "Colonie"],["Goodrich School", "located in", "Albany County"],["Goodrich School", "built in", "1922"],["Goodrich School", "building material", "Brick"],["Goodrich School", "architectural style", "Classical Revival"],["Goodrich School", "features", "Portico"],["Goodrich School", "features", "Doric order fluted columns"],["Goodrich School", "features", "Wood cupola"],["Goodrich School", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places"]]
The Monastery of Saint Saviour () is a Catholic Franciscan monastery located on 1 Saint Francis Street, east of the New Gate in the Old City of Jerusalem. The site was purchased from the Georgian Orthodox Church in 1560 with permission by Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent of the Ottoman Empire, and the monastery was constructed in stages. The church building was erected in 1885, with renovation in 1985. The site includes a printing press, an organ workshop, a library and a Catholic school. <S> [["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "instance of", "Catholic Franciscan monastery"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "located at", "1 Saint Francis Street"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "located in", "Old City of Jerusalem"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "purchased from", "Georgian Orthodox Church"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "purchased in", "1560"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "permission by", "Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "belonged to", "Ottoman Empire"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "constructed in", "stages"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "church building erected in", "1885"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "renovated in", "1985"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "includes", "printing press"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "includes", "organ workshop"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "includes", "library"], ["Monastery of Saint Saviour", "includes", "Catholic school"]]
Jiří Jech (born December 22, 1975) is a Czech football referee. He was a full international for FIFA from 2007 to 2010, and served as a referee in 2010 World Cup qualifiers. <S> [["Jiří Jech", "instance of", "Football referee"], ["Jiří Jech", "nationality", "Czech"], ["Jiří Jech", "born on", "December 22, 1975"], ["Jiří Jech", "role", "Full international for FIFA"], ["Jiří Jech", "years active", "2007 to 2010"], ["Jiří Jech", "served as referee in", "2010 World Cup qualifiers"]]
John Brandard (Birmingham 1812 – 15 December 1863 London) was an English lithographic artist. He designed many hundred illustrated title-pages for sheet music in what Michael Bryan judged "a pretty, though weak, style". John Brandard was the second of three sons born to Thomas Brandard (d. 1830), engraver and copperplate printer, of Barford Street, Deritend, Birmingham, and his wife, Ann. His older brother was Robert Brandard. John Brandard was baptized on 13 March 1812 at St Martin's church in Birmingham. He began his career as an engraver, mainly of commercial designs. On 17 January 1833 he married Maria Chater at Edgbaston in Birmingham. They had five children, one of whom, Walter Robert Brandard (1842–1869), was also briefly a designer of sheet music covers. He worked in a lifelong partnership with the lithographic printers M. & N. Hanhart, for whom he produced designs for Louis-Antoine Jullien from 1844 until 1856, when Jullien was ruined following a fire which destroyed his entire stock of music."Brandard took the chromolithograph, which had been first used in connection with music in 1841, to an incredibly high level of sophistication, using half a dozen or more stones to produce a single image, printed on paper of a far higher quality than had been used for this purpose hitherto... The colours red and blue predominate in his palette of the 1840s, along with some exquisitely diaphanous draughtsmanship and plentiful use of gold, especially in filigree borders. This latter was something Brandard may have learned when copying medieval illuminations for the Hanharts’ bound music albums. His covers convey an illusion of luxury and refinement, and are clearly aimed at the wealthier sections of society..."Brandard employed two full-time assistants, allowing him to produce artwork quickly and prolifically, mainly concentrating on ballet and opera. His portraits of dancers were admired by Degas. He usually charged 20 guineas for his original artwork and lived well from the proceeds of his art. Described as " an imposing, dandified figure", he would often arrive at theatres in Drury Lane or Covent Garden in his own coach and horses. He was succeeded by Alfred Concanen as master of the illustrated sheet music cover.John Brandard died at his home 8 Southampton Place in Chalk Farm, north London, on 15 December 1863.Collections of his work are held at Reading University, at the Theatre Museum in Covent Garden, the Victoria and Albert Museum, the British Library at the Bodleian Library in Oxford and the largest collection in America is with Lynch Resources in Edmonds, Wa. <S> [["John Brandard", "instance of", "Lithographic artist"],["John Brandard", "birth place", "Birmingham"],["John Brandard", "death place", "London"],["John Brandard", "father", "Thomas Brandard"],["John Brandard", "mother", "Ann"],["John Brandard", "brother", "Robert Brandard"],["John Brandard", "baptized at", "St Martin's church"],["John Brandard", "married to", "Maria Chater"],["John Brandard", "children", "five"],["John Brandard", "partnered with", "M. & N. Hanhart"],["John Brandard", "collaborated with", "Louis-Antoine Jullien"],["John Brandard", "employed", "two full-time assistants"],["John Brandard", "admired by", "Degas"],["John Brandard", "died at", "8 Southampton Place"],["John Brandard", "collections held at", "Reading University, Theatre Museum, Victoria and Albert Museum, British Library, Bodleian Library, Lynch Resources"],["John Brandard", "style", "pretty, though weak"],["John Brandard", "career", "engraver and lithographic artist"],["John Brandard", "specialty", "illustrated title-pages for sheet music"],["John Brandard", "artwork price", "20 guineas"],["John Brandard", "lived in", "Chalk Farm"],["John Brandard", "transportation", "own coach and horses"],["John Brandard", "successor", "Alfred Concanen"]]
Robert Arp (born March 20, 1970) is an American philosopher known for his work in ethics, modern philosophy, ontology, philosophy of biology, cognitive science, evolutionary psychology, religious studies, and philosophy and popular culture. He currently works as an adjunct professor teaching philosophy courses in the classroom and online at numerous schools in the Kansas City, Missouri area and other areas of the United States. <S> [["Robert Arp", "profession", "Philosopher"], ["Robert Arp", "nationality", "American"], ["Robert Arp", "birth date", "March 20, 1970"], ["Robert Arp", "work areas", ["Ethics", "Modern philosophy", "Ontology", "Philosophy of biology", "Cognitive science", "Evolutionary psychology", "Religious studies", "Philosophy and popular culture"]], ["Robert Arp", "current job", "Adjunct professor"], ["Robert Arp", "teaching location", ["Kansas City, Missouri", "United States"]]]
Dwan Hurt (March 29, 1963 – November 25, 2016) was an American basketball coach and dean at Junipero Serra High School, was named 2010 State Coach of the Year by Cal-Hi Sports; Daily Breeze Coach of the Year 2010; and coached his high school alma mater, the Serra Cavaliers, to the 2010 California Interscholastic Federation Division III Boys Basketball State Championship. He also led Serra to State Division IV title in 1993. Hurt died in his sleep on November 25, 2016. <S> [["Dwan Hurt", "instance of", "Basketball coach"], ["Dwan Hurt", "instance of", "Dean"], ["Dwan Hurt", "birth date", "March 29, 1963"], ["Dwan Hurt", "death date", "November 25, 2016"], ["Dwan Hurt", "nationality", "American"], ["Dwan Hurt", "awards", "2010 State Coach of the Year"], ["Dwan Hurt", "awards", "Daily Breeze Coach of the Year 2010"], ["Dwan Hurt", "coached", "Serra Cavaliers"], ["Serra Cavaliers", "instance of", "High school basketball team"], ["Serra Cavaliers", "championships", "2010 California Interscholastic Federation Division III Boys Basketball State Championship"], ["Serra Cavaliers", "championships", "1993 State Division IV title"], ["Dwan Hurt", "cause of death", "died in his sleep"]]
Seaview Hospital was a historic tuberculosis sanatorium, now a national historic district located at Willowbrook on Staten Island, New York. The complex was planned and built between 1905 and 1938 and was the largest and most costly municipal facility for the treatment of tuberculosis of its date in the United States. <S> [["Seaview Hospital", "instance of", "Tuberculosis sanatorium"], ["Seaview Hospital", "location", "Willowbrook, Staten Island, New York"], ["Seaview Hospital", "status", "National historic district"], ["Seaview Hospital", "planned and built", "1905-1938"], ["Seaview Hospital", "size", "largest"], ["Seaview Hospital", "cost", "most costly"], ["Seaview Hospital", "facility for", "treatment of tuberculosis"], ["Seaview Hospital", "country", "United States"]]
Martin Cox (born August 12, 1956) is a former Canadian Football League wide receiver.Cox played his college football at Vanderbilt University. In his first CFL season, with the Ottawa Rough Riders, he caught 32 passes for 546 yards and 7 touchdowns, winning him the Frank M. Gibson Trophy as top rookie in the CFL East. He later played with the Toronto Argonauts and Winnipeg Blue Bombers.Cox finished his career in 1983 in the United States Football League with the Tampa Bay Bandits. <S> [["Martin Cox", "instance of", "Canadian Football League wide receiver"], ["Martin Cox", "date of birth", "August 12, 1956"], ["Martin Cox", "college", "Vanderbilt University"], ["Martin Cox", "team", "Ottawa Rough Riders"], ["Martin Cox", "team", "Toronto Argonauts"], ["Martin Cox", "team", "Winnipeg Blue Bombers"], ["Martin Cox", "league", "United States Football League"], ["Martin Cox", "team", "Tampa Bay Bandits"], ["Ottawa Rough Riders", "number of passes caught", 32], ["Ottawa Rough Riders", "number of yards", 546], ["Ottawa Rough Riders", "number of touchdowns", 7], ["Ottawa Rough Riders", "award", "Frank M. Gibson Trophy"], ["Frank M. Gibson Trophy", "recipient", "Martin Cox"], ["Frank M. Gibson Trophy", "category", "top rookie in the CFL East"]]
Samba Diakité (born 24 January 1989) is a French-born Malian professional footballer who plays as a midfielder for Kuwaiti club Al Tadhamon SC and the Mali national team. <S> [["Samba Diakité", "date of birth", "24 January 1989"], ["Samba Diakité", "nationality", "French"], ["Samba Diakité", "nationality", "Malian"], ["Samba Diakité", "occupation", "professional footballer"], ["Samba Diakité", "position", "midfielder"], ["Samba Diakité", "plays for", "Al Tadhamon SC"], ["Samba Diakité", "plays for", "Mali national team"]]
Horizon Nuclear Power is a British energy company that was expected to build new nuclear power stations in the United Kingdom. It was established in 2009, with its head office in Gloucester, and is now owned by Hitachi.On 17 January 2019, Horizon suspended its UK nuclear development programme. <S> [["Horizon Nuclear Power", "instance of", "Energy company"], ["Horizon Nuclear Power", "country", "United Kingdom"], ["Horizon Nuclear Power", "established in", "2009"], ["Horizon Nuclear Power", "head office", "Gloucester"], ["Horizon Nuclear Power", "owned by", "Hitachi"], ["Horizon Nuclear Power", "suspended", "UK nuclear development programme on 17 January 2019"]]
Peter Sainthill (8 July 1593 – 12 August 1648) of Bradninch in Devon, England, was twice elected a Member of Parliament for Tiverton in Devon, in the Short Parliament 1640 and in the Long Parliament in November 1640. He was a strong supporter of the Royalist side in the Civil War. He was "a man of culture and unaffected simplicity of character, (who) represents the Cavalier cause at its best". He was the subject of a lengthy Puritan verse satire, known as "Peter's Banquet" or "The Cavalier in the Dumps", written circa 1645. <S> [["Peter Sainthill", "date of birth", "8 July 1593"], ["Peter Sainthill", "date of death", "12 August 1648"], ["Peter Sainthill", "place of birth", "Bradninch, Devon, England"], ["Peter Sainthill", "occupation", "Member of Parliament"], ["Peter Sainthill", "political affiliation", "Royalist"], ["Peter Sainthill", "description", "man of culture and unaffected simplicity of character"], ["Peter Sainthill", "representation", "Cavalier cause"], ["Peter Sainthill", "subject of", "Peter's Banquet"], ["Peter Sainthill", "subject of", "The Cavalier in the Dumps"], ["Peter Sainthill", "written", "circa 1645"], ["Peter Sainthill", "elected as Member of Parliament for", "Tiverton, Devon"], ["Peter Sainthill", "elected in", "Short Parliament 1640"], ["Peter Sainthill", "elected in", "Long Parliament November 1640"]]
Nkhaba is an "inkhundla" of Swaziland, located in the Hhohho District. Its population as of the 2007 census was 15,704. Areas under Nkhaba are Jubukweni, Mhlosheni(formerly Forbes Reef)next to Malolotja Game Reserve, Hawane, Mahebedla east and west, Mnyokane, Malanti, Luvinjelweni etc. It is one of the coldest places in Swaziland. <S> [["Nkhaba", "instance of", "Inkhundla"], ["Nkhaba", "located in", "Hhohho District"], ["Nkhaba", "population", "15,704 (2007 census)"], ["Nkhaba", "areas", "Jubukweni, Mhlosheni, Hawane, Mahebedla, Mnyokane, Malanti, Luvinjelweni"], ["Nkhaba", "features", "one of the coldest places in Swaziland"]]
Timpisini is an "inkhundla" of Swaziland, located in the Hhohho District. Its population as of the 2007 census was 8,471. <S> [["Timpisini", "instance of", "Inkhundla"], ["Timpisini", "country", "Swaziland"], ["Timpisini", "located in", "Hhohho District"], ["Timpisini", "population", "8,471 (2007 census)"]]
Rottøya is an island in the municipality of Aure in Møre og Romsdal county, Norway. The island lies between the mainland and the large island of Ertvågsøya. The small island of Ruøya lies just to the north of Rottøya. The Mjosund Bridge crosses the Mjosundet strait, connecting Rottøya to the island of Ertvågsøya to the west. The Smalsund Bridge crosses the Smalsundet strait, connecting Rottøya to the island of Ruøya to the north. The larger Aursundet strait is located to the east of the island. <S> [["Rottøya", "instance of", "Island"], ["Rottøya", "located in", "Aure"], ["Rottøya", "located in", "Møre og Romsdal county"], ["Rottøya", "country", "Norway"], ["Rottøya", "lies between", "Mainland"], ["Rottøya", "lies between", "Ertvågsøya"], ["Ruøya", "instance of", "Island"], ["Ruøya", "located in", "North of Rottøya"], ["Mjosund Bridge", "crosses", "Mjosundet strait"], ["Mjosund Bridge", "connects", "Rottøya to Ertvågsøya"], ["Smalsund Bridge", "crosses", "Smalsundet strait"], ["Smalsund Bridge", "connects", "Rottøya to Ruøya"], ["Aursundet strait", "located to the east of", "Rottøya"]]
