Everett Owen Alldredge (September 22, 1912 – September 9, 1973) was an American archivist and records manager, and a leader in the American archival community.Everett O. Alldredge was born and raised in Mount Vernon, Indiana, and completed his undergraduate studies in history at DePauw University. He joined the staff of the National Archives in 1940, and spent most of his 31-year career involved in records management. From 1959 to 1971 he served as Assistant Archivist for Records Management. He was also an active member of the archival profession, serving as president of the Society of American Archivists from 1963 to 1964.Alldredge received the Emmett Leahy Award in 1969.Alldredge died of cancer two years after his retirement, on September 9, 1973. <S> [["Everett Owen Alldredge", "instance of", "Archivist"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "instance of", "Records manager"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "country", "United States"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "birth date", "September 22, 1912"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "death date", "September 9, 1973"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "place of birth", "Mount Vernon, Indiana"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "education", "DePauw University"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "career", "National Archives"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "position", "Assistant Archivist for Records Management"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "organization", "Society of American Archivists"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "award", "Emmett Leahy Award"], ["Everett Owen Alldredge", "cause of death", "cancer"]]
Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital, also known as Larue D. Carter Memorial Hospital is a historic hospital complex and national historic district located at Indianapolis, Indiana. The district resources were developed between 1930 and 1951 by the Veterans Administration, and encompasses 15 contributing buildings, 2 contributing sites, 2 contributing structures and 5 contributing objects on the hospital campus. The main complex is connected by an enclosed corridor and consists of the main hospital building (1931), kitchen/mess hall/boiler house/attendants' quarters, general medical building (1939), and recreation building (1941). The buildings reflect the Colonial Revival and Classical Revival styles of architecture.The name of the eponymous Dr. Carter had previously been attached to the state's first intensive-treatment psychiatric hospital, a facility within a large assembly of buildings (which then also included both the University of Indiana Indianapolis campus and the V.A. Hospital), in recognition of his leadership role in the state's Mental Health Association, at a time when the Civil War-era Central State Hospital psychiatric facility, in the same city, was being pilloried as an obsolete relic reflecting inhumane approaches to mental illness.This V.A. facility was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2012. <S> [    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "also known as", "Larue D. Carter Memorial Hospital"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "type", "historic hospital complex"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "location", "Indianapolis, Indiana"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "developed by", "Veterans Administration"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "encompasses", "15 contributing buildings"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "encompasses", "2 contributing sites"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "encompasses", "2 contributing structures"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "encompasses", "5 contributing objects"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "connected by", "enclosed corridor"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "consists of", "main hospital building"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "consists of", "kitchen/mess hall/boiler house/attendants' quarters"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "consists of", "general medical building"],    ["Indianapolis Veterans Administration Hospital", "consists of", "recreation building"],    ["main hospital building", "built in", "1931"],    ["general medical building", "built in", "1939"],    ["recreation building", "built in", "1941"],    ["main hospital building", "style of architecture", "Colonial Revival"],    ["general medical building", "style of architecture", "Classical Revival"],    ["Larue D. Carter", "previously attached to", "state's first intensive-treatment psychiatric hospital"],    ["Larue D. Carter", "leadership role in", "state's Mental Health Association"],    ["Central State Hospital", "location", "Indianapolis"],    ["Central State Hospital", "era", "Civil War"],    ["Central State Hospital", "criticized as", "obsolete relic"],    ["Central State Hospital", "reflecting", "inhumane approaches to mental illness"],    ["V.A. facility", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places in 2012"]]
