Knight-Hennessy Scholars is an international graduate-level scholarship program for study at Stanford University. Established in 2016, the program prepares students to take leadership roles in finding creative solutions to complex global issues. Scholars receive full funding to pursue any graduate degree at Stanford and have additional opportunities for leadership training, mentorship, and experiential learning across multiple disciplines. <S> [["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "instance of", "Scholarship program"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "country", "International"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "level", "Graduate"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "study at", "Stanford University"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "established", "2016"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "prepares students for", "Leadership roles"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "focus on", "Finding creative solutions to complex global issues"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "funding", "Full"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "degree", "Graduate degree at Stanford"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "opportunities for", "Leadership training"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "opportunities for", "Mentorship"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "opportunities for", "Experiential learning"], ["Knight-Hennessy Scholars", "across", "Multiple disciplines"]]
Home BancShares, Inc., operating as Centennial Bank, is a bank holding company based in Conway, Arkansas. It is on the list of largest banks in the United States. The bank operates 165 branches in Arkansas, Alabama, Florida, and New York City. <S> [["Home BancShares, Inc.", "instance of", "Bank holding company"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "based in", "Conway, Arkansas"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "on list of", "largest banks in the United States"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "operates", "165 branches"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "operates in", "Arkansas"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "operates in", "Alabama"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "operates in", "Florida"], ["Home BancShares, Inc.", "operates in", "New York City"]]
The 1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships were contested June 1−4, 1988 at Hayward Field at the University of Oregon in Eugene, Oregon in order to determine the individual and team national champions of men's and women's collegiate Division I outdoor track and field events in the United States.These were the 66th annual men's championships and the seventh annual women's championships. This was the Ducks' sixth time hosting the event and the first since 1984.In a repeat of the previous year's result, UCLA and LSU topped the men's and women's team standings, respectively; it was the Bruins' eighth men's team title and the second for the Lady Tigers. LSU's title would ultimately be the second of a record eleven consecutive national championships between 1987 and 1997. <S> [    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "event date", "June 1-4, 1988"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "location", "Hayward Field at the University of Oregon"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "city", "Eugene, Oregon"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "purpose", "determine individual and team national champions of men's and women's collegiate Division I outdoor track and field events in the United States"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "men's championships", "66th annual"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "women's championships", "seventh annual"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "hosted by", "University of Oregon"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "men's team champions", "UCLA"],    ["1988 NCAA Division I Outdoor Track and Field Championships", "women's team champions", "LSU"],    ["UCLA", "men's team titles", "eighth"],    ["LSU", "women's team titles", "second"],    ["LSU", "consecutive national championships", "eleven between 1987 and 1997"]]
