The Independence 20, also called the Freedom Independence 20, is an American sailboat, that was designed by Gary Mull as a class for disabled sailors and first built in 1999. The design is out of production.The boat was initially built by Tillotson Pearson in the United States for Freedom Yachts and later built by Catalina Yachts.The Independence 20 shares the same hull as the Catalina Yachts-built Aero 20. <S> [["Independence 20", "instance of", "Sailboat"], ["Independence 20", "designer", "Gary Mull"], ["Independence 20", "class for", "Disabled sailors"], ["Independence 20", "first built", "1999"], ["Independence 20", "out of production", "True"], ["Independence 20", "initially built by", "Tillotson Pearson"], ["Independence 20", "built by", "Catalina Yachts"], ["Independence 20", "shares hull with", "Aero 20"], ["Independence 20", "also called", "Freedom Independence 20"], ["Independence 20", "country", "United States"], ["Independence 20", "built for", "Freedom Yachts"]]
The 1990–91 St. Francis Terriers men's basketball team represented St. Francis College during the 1990–91 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The team was coached by Rich Zvosec, who was in his third year at the helm of the St. Francis Terriers. The Terrier's home games were played at the Generoso Pope Athletic Complex. The team has been a member of the Northeast Conference since 1981.The Terriers finished their season at 15–14 overall and 8–8 in conference play. At the end of the regular season Rich Zvosec was named NEC Coach of the Year and Ron Arnold was named NEC Newcomer of the Year.Over 29 games, Lester James made 149 field-goals on 215 field-goal attempts, producing a 69.3 field-goal percentage that is 16th all-time in NCAA history. <S> [    ["1990-91 St. Francis Terriers men's basketball team", "represented", "St. Francis College"],    ["1990-91 St. Francis Terriers men's basketball team", "season", "1990-91 NCAA Division I men's basketball season"],    ["1990-91 St. Francis Terriers men's basketball team", "coached by", "Rich Zvosec"],    ["Rich Zvosec", "years at helm", "third"],    ["Terrier's home games", "played at", "Generoso Pope Athletic Complex"],    ["Terriers", "member of", "Northeast Conference"],    ["Terriers", "finished season", "15-14 overall and 8-8 in conference play"],    ["Rich Zvosec", "named", "NEC Coach of the Year"],    ["Ron Arnold", "named", "NEC Newcomer of the Year"],    ["Lester James", "made", "149 field-goals on 215 field-goal attempts"],    ["Lester James", "field-goal percentage", "69.3"],    ["Lester James", "field-goal percentage rank", "16th all-time in NCAA history"]]
Sam Sing Kung Temple ()(also known as the Three Saints Temple) is a Chinese temple in Sandakan, Sabah, Malaysia. Built in 1887, the temple is the third oldest temple in Sandakan, after Goddess of Mercy Temple and Tam Kung Temple. It is part of the Sandakan Heritage Trail. <S> [["Sam Sing Kung Temple", "instance of", "Chinese temple"], ["Sam Sing Kung Temple", "located in", "Sandakan, Sabah, Malaysia"], ["Sam Sing Kung Temple", "built in", "1887"], ["Sam Sing Kung Temple", "part of", "Sandakan Heritage Trail"], ["Sam Sing Kung Temple", "is the third oldest temple in Sandakan after", "Goddess of Mercy Temple and Tam Kung Temple"]]
