Emma di Resburgo (Emma of Roxburgh) is a melodramma "eroico" (a heroic, serious opera) in two acts by Giacomo Meyerbeer. It was the composer's sixth opera and the third that he wrote for an Italian theatre. The libretto in Italian by Gaetano Rossi is set in Scotland and has the same storyline as previous operas by Étienne Méhul "(Héléna", Paris, 1803, to a French text) and Simon Mayr ("Elena", Naples, 1814, with an Italian text). Meyerbeer's opera had its premiere at the Teatro San Benedetto Venice on 26 June 1819. <S> [    ["Emma di Resburgo", "instance of", "Melodramma eroico"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "composer", "Giacomo Meyerbeer"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "number of acts", "2"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "language", "Italian"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "setting", "Scotland"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "premiere date", "26 June 1819"],    ["Emma di Resburgo", "premiere location", "Teatro San Benedetto Venice"],    ["Giacomo Meyerbeer", "number of operas composed", "6"],    ["Giacomo Meyerbeer", "operas written for Italian theatre", "3"],    ["Giacomo Meyerbeer", "librettist", "Gaetano Rossi"],    ["Gaetano Rossi", "language", "Italian"],    ["Étienne Méhul", "opera", "Héléna"],    ["Étienne Méhul", "premiere location", "Paris"],    ["Étienne Méhul", "premiere date", "1803"],    ["Simon Mayr", "opera", "Elena"],    ["Simon Mayr", "premiere location", "Naples"],    ["Simon Mayr", "premiere date", "1814"]]
Philipp Pflieger (born 16 July 1987) is a German long distance runner who specialises in the marathon. He competed in the men's marathon event at the 2016 Summer Olympics where he finished in 55th place. In 2018, he competed in the men's marathon at the 2018 European Athletics Championships held in Berlin, Germany. He did not finish his race. <S> [["Philipp Pflieger", "instance of", "Long distance runner"], ["Philipp Pflieger", "nationality", "German"], ["Philipp Pflieger", "specializes in", "Marathon"], ["Philipp Pflieger", "competition", "2016 Summer Olympics, Men's marathon event, 55th place"], ["Philipp Pflieger", "competition", "2018 European Athletics Championships, Men's marathon, Did not finish"]]
Tewelde Estifanos (born 2 November 1981) is an Eritrean long distance runner who specialises in the marathon. He competed in the men's marathon event at the 2016 Summer Olympics where he finished in 60th place with a time of 2:19:12. <S> [["Tewelde Estifanos", "instance of", "Long distance runner"], ["Tewelde Estifanos", "nationality", "Eritrean"], ["Tewelde Estifanos", "specializes in", "Marathon"], ["Tewelde Estifanos", "competed in", "2016 Summer Olympics"], ["2016 Summer Olympics", "event", "Men's marathon"], ["2016 Summer Olympics", "finish position", "60th"], ["2016 Summer Olympics", "time", "2:19:12"]]
Evansville Journal News, also known as the Citizens Bank Building-Evansville Journal Building, is a historic commercial building located in downtown Evansville, Indiana. It was built in 1910, and is a two-story, Beaux-Arts style brick building with a limestone front. The building was originally built to house a newspaper.It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1982. <S> [["Evansville Journal News", "instance of", "Historic commercial building"], ["Evansville Journal News", "location", "Downtown Evansville, Indiana"], ["Evansville Journal News", "built in", "1910"], ["Evansville Journal News", "architectural style", "Beaux-Arts"], ["Evansville Journal News", "material", "Brick, Limestone"], ["Evansville Journal News", "original purpose", "Newspaper office"], ["Evansville Journal News", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places in 1982"]]
The 1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships were contested as part of the first annual NCAA swim meet to determine the team and individual national champions of men's collegiate swimming and diving in the United States. The championship was hosted by the United States Naval Academy at Scott Natatorium in Annapolis, Maryland.Only individual championships were officially contested during the first thirteen-NCAA sponsored swimming and diving championships. Unofficial team standings were kept but a team title was not officially awarded until 1937. Northwestern is acknowledged as this year's unofficial team champion, the first title for the Wildcats. <S> [["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "part of", "NCAA swim meet"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "location", "United States"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "hosted by", "United States Naval Academy"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "hosted at", "Scott Natatorium"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "hosted in", "Annapolis, Maryland"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "team champion", "Northwestern"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "individual champion", "Wildcats"], ["1924 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "team title awarded", "1937"]]
Buly Da Conceição Triste (born July 4, 1991) is a sprint canoeist from São Tomé and Príncipe. He competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in the men's C-1 1000 metres event; his time of 4:46.396 in the semifinals did not qualify him for the finals. He was the flag bearer for São Tomé and Príncipe at the Parade of Nations.He won a gold, a silver and a bronze medal at the 2019 African Games. <S> [["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "instance of", "Sprint canoeist"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "birth date", "July 4, 1991"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "country", "São Tomé and Príncipe"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "competition", "2016 Summer Olympics"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "event", "Men's C-1 1000 metres"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "time", "4:46.396"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "result", "Did not qualify for finals"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "flag bearer for", "São Tomé and Príncipe"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "medals won", "Gold, Silver, Bronze"], ["Buly Da Conceição Triste", "event", "2019 African Games"]]
is a 1989 shoot 'em up video game developed and published by Taito for the Taito Z System. In the game, the player flies an armoured car shooting enemy invaders to destroy a terrorist organisation. "Night Striker" combines gameplay elements of Sega's "Space Harrier" and "Out Run". Versions were released for the Sega Mega-CD in 1993, Sony PlayStation in 1995, and Sega Saturn (as "Night Striker S") in 1996. A version was released on the "Taito Memories II Gekan" compilation for the PlayStation 2 in 2007. "Night Striker" received mixed reviews, and the Mega-CD version in particular was heavily criticised, primarily due to poor graphics. The music was composed by Taito's Zuntata sound team, and has been released separately. The game was only released in Japan. <S> [["Night Striker", "instance of", "Video game"], ["Night Striker", "developed by", "Taito"], ["Night Striker", "published by", "Taito"], ["Night Striker", "platform", "Taito Z System"], ["Night Striker", "gameplay elements of", "Space Harrier"], ["Night Striker", "gameplay elements of", "Out Run"], ["Night Striker", "music composed by", "Zuntata sound team"], ["Night Striker", "released in", "Japan"], ["Night Striker", "received reviews", "mixed"], ["Night Striker", "criticised for", "poor graphics"], ["Versions of Night Striker", "released for", "Sega Mega-CD"], ["Versions of Night Striker", "released for", "Sony PlayStation"], ["Versions of Night Striker", "released for", "Sega Saturn"], ["Versions of Night Striker", "released for", "PlayStation 2"], ["Versions of Night Striker", "released on", "Taito Memories II Gekan compilation"]]
The Kings River Viaduct is a planned series of bridges and embankments carrying California High-Speed Rail over the Kings River in Fresno County and Kings County, California. The site is between the Fresno and Kings–Tulare stations, roughly east of Laton and north of Hanford. The structure is planned to be over long because three river channels must be crossed, two of which were created by floods in the 1860s.In the vicinity of the crossing, the Kings River consists of three widely separated river channels collectively known as the Kings River Complex. From north to south, these are Cole Slough, Dutch John Cut, and the Old Kings River, all of which flow in a westerly direction. Cole Slough and the Old River separate at the People's Weir, the largest weir in the Kings River system. The Old River was the main course of the river until two floods in 1861 and 1867, the first of which created Cole Slough and the second of which caused it to become the river's new main course. Since then the Old River has been dry except when river flows are exceptionally high. Dutch John Cut diverges from Cole Slough east of the bridge site, and joins the Old River to reform the main channel of the Kings River to the west of the bridge site. Cole Slough is then mostly diverted into several canals in the vicinity of Laton.Dirt excavation sites in the vicinity of the bridge will be reused as groundwater recharge basins once construction is complete. <S> [    ["Kings River Viaduct", "instance of", "Series of bridges and embankments"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Fresno County"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Kings County"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "California"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Laton"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Hanford"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Kings River"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Cole Slough"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Dutch John Cut"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Old Kings River"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "People's Weir"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "Kings River Complex"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "location", "California High-Speed Rail"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "length", "long"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "crosses", "Three river channels"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "created by", "Floods in the 1860s"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "diverges from", "Cole Slough"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "joins", "Old River"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "diverted into", "Canals"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "reused as", "Groundwater recharge basins"],    ["Kings River Viaduct", "operator", "California High-Speed Rail"]]
Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth Games was held on the Gold Coast, Australia from April 13 to 15. The rugby sevens competition was held at Robina Stadium. This is the sixth time that the men's competition was held, following rugby sevens's debut at the 1998 Games, with women's rugby sevens making its debut. A total of sixteen men's and eight women's teams are scheduled to compete (312 athletes, at 12 per team plus one traveling reserve) in each respective tournament. <S> [["Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth Games", "event", "Rugby sevens competition"], ["Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth Games", "location", "Gold Coast, Australia"], ["Rugby sevens at the 2018 Commonwealth Games", "date", "April 13 to 15"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "venue", "Robina Stadium"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "men's competition held", "sixth time"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "debut", "1998 Games"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "debut", "women's rugby sevens"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "teams", "16 men's and 8 women's"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "athletes", "312"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "players per team", "12"], ["Rugby sevens competition", "traveling reserve", "1"]]
Behold the Dreamers is the 2016 debut novel by Imbolo Mbue. The novel details the experiences of two New York City families during the 2008 financial crisis: an immigrant family from Cameroon, the Jonga family, and their wealthy employers, the Edwards family. <S> [["Behold the Dreamers", "instance of", "Novel"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "author", "Imbolo Mbue"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "publication year", "2016"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "setting", "New York City"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "theme", "2008 financial crisis"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "characters", "Jonga family"], ["Behold the Dreamers", "characters", "Edwards family"], ["Jonga family", "origin", "Cameroon"], ["Edwards family", "status", "wealthy employers"]]
Cristiano Lombardi (born 19 August 1995) is an Italian footballer who plays as a right winger for Serie B club Salernitana, on loan from Lazio. <S> [["Cristiano Lombardi", "date of birth", "19 August 1995"], ["Cristiano Lombardi", "nationality", "Italian"], ["Cristiano Lombardi", "occupation", "footballer"], ["Cristiano Lombardi", "position", "right winger"], ["Cristiano Lombardi", "plays for", "Salernitana"], ["Salernitana", "league", "Serie B"], ["Salernitana", "loaned from", "Lazio"]]
The 1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships were contested at the Malkin Athletic Center at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts as part of the 12th annual NCAA swim meet to determine the team and individual national champions of men's collegiate swimming and diving in the United States.Only individual championships were officially contested during the first thirteen-NCAA sponsored swimming and diving championships. Unofficial team standings were kept but a team title was not officially awarded until 1937.Michigan is acknowledged as this year's unofficial team champion, the sixth such title (and second consecutive) for the Wolverines. <S> [["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "location", "Malkin Athletic Center"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "held at", "Harvard University"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "city", "Cambridge"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "state", "Massachusetts"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "part of", "12th annual NCAA swim meet"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "determine", "team and individual national champions of men's collegiate swimming and diving"], ["1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships", "country", "United States"], ["Michigan", "team champion", "1935 NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships"], ["Michigan", "number of titles", "six"], ["Michigan", "consecutive titles", "second"]]
Wanaparthy district is a district in the Indian state of Telangana. It is located 143 km from the state capital Hyderabad. It is also an assembly Constituency in Telangana state. Wanaparthy is a famous historical site in Telangana and had served as capital of Wanaparthy Samsthanam. It was previously part of Mahabubnagar district. <S> [["Wanaparthy district", "instance of", "District"], ["Wanaparthy district", "located in", "Telangana"], ["Wanaparthy district", "distance from", "Hyderabad 143 km"], ["Wanaparthy district", "assembly constituency in", "Telangana state"], ["Wanaparthy district", "historical site in", "Telangana"], ["Wanaparthy district", "capital of", "Wanaparthy Samsthanam"], ["Wanaparthy district", "previously part of", "Mahabubnagar district"]]
