Heikki Hietanen (30 August 1914 – 27 May 2000) was a Finnish swimmer. He competed in two events at the 1936 Summer Olympics. <S> [["Heikki Hietanen", "instance of", "Swimmer"], ["Heikki Hietanen", "birth date", "30 August 1914"], ["Heikki Hietanen", "death date", "27 May 2000"], ["Heikki Hietanen", "country", "Finland"], ["Heikki Hietanen", "competition", "1936 Summer Olympics"], ["Heikki Hietanen", "number of events competed", "2"]]
Koinonia of West Georgia, commonly referred to simply as Koinonia, was a private, non-denominational Christian, accredited center for independent studies located on the Carrollton-Villa Rica border in the U.S. state of Georgia. It was founded in 1997 originally as a school for high school students, but over the years evolved into a K-12 format school. In contrast to most private schools — or public schools for that matter — Koinonia only had classes on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Thursdays, leaving Mondays and Fridays free. However, this does not mean that students coming out of Koinonia struggle with their schoolwork; on the contrary, some of them succeeded in different areas in which other students from "traditional" schools have struggled. <S> [["Koinonia of West Georgia", "instance of", "Educational institution"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "type", "Private school"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "location", "Carrollton-Villa Rica border"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "state", "Georgia"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "founded", "1997"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "format", "K-12 school"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "class schedule", "Tuesdays, Wednesdays, Thursdays"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "students", "successful"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "students", "struggle"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "subjects", "varied"], ["Koinonia of West Georgia", "different from", "traditional schools"]]
The Rebellion Festival, formerly Holidays in the Sun and the Wasted Festival is a British punk rock festival first held in 1996. The festival has attracted mainstream press coverage from such sources as The Guardian, The Independent, The Daily Telegraph and Kerrang.The first festival in 1996 was held at the Winter Gardens, Blackpool England. It is still held there now, although on some years the festival has been held in nearby Morecambe. Festivals have also been held under the Rebellion and earlier brand names in Australia, United States, Japan, Germany, Netherlands, Italy, Belgium, the Basque Country, Ireland and Austria.It is still a family-run, family-orientated event which celebrates Punk in all its forms, but also puts on bands from other alternative genres plus some Glam Rock artists and seminal bands from the 1960s and 1970s . There are up to seven music stages plus also an acoustic stage, a literary stage and a Punk Art gallery along with many workshops, and stalls for clothes, music and other products.Each year, over 300 acts perform at the festival over a four-day period, usually spread over the first weekend in August from Thursday to Sunday. The festival maintains a positive relationship with Blackpool Council and the people of Blackpool in general and has been commended for its involvement with local charities.Another punk festival, Nice 'N Sleazy in Morecambe, began life as an offshoot of Wasted in Morecambe, the 3B's (Breakfast, Beer, Bands) Festival, providing campsite accommodation with an unofficial stage. When Wasted reverted to Blackpool in 2006, the Morecambe campsite event continued as a separate festival.The Boomtown Rats' performance at the 2015 festival made national headlines after lead singer Bob Geldof derided all the other bands and the festival audience on account of their fashion preferences .2017 was the 21st anniversary of the festival which coincided with the 40th anniversary celebrations of Punk. The 2020 event was cancelled because of the Covid 19 pandemic and replaced with an online festival. <S> [["Rebellion Festival", "instance of", "Punk rock festival"],["Rebellion Festival", "first held", 1996],["Rebellion Festival", "location", "Winter Gardens, Blackpool England"],["Rebellion Festival", "additional locations", ["Morecambe", "Australia", "United States", "Japan", "Germany", "Netherlands", "Italy", "Belgium", "Basque Country", "Ireland", "Austria"]],["Rebellion Festival", "features", ["music stages", "acoustic stage", "literary stage", "Punk Art gallery", "workshops", "stalls"]],["Rebellion Festival", "number of acts", "over 300"],["Rebellion Festival", "duration", "four-day period"],["Rebellion Festival", "relationship with", ["Blackpool Council", "local charities"]],["Nice 'N Sleazy", "originated from", "Wasted in Morecambe"],["Nice 'N Sleazy", "features", "campsite accommodation"],["Nice 'N Sleazy", "separate festival from", "Wasted in Morecambe"],["Boomtown Rats", "performance at", "2015 festival"],["Boomtown Rats", "made headlines for", "Bob Geldof's comments"],["2020 event", "cancelled due to", "Covid 19 pandemic"],["2020 event", "replaced with", "online festival"]]
IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016) was a major professional wrestling event that was scripted and produced by the "lucha libre" wrestling company International Wrestling Revolution Group (IWRG; sometimes also referred to as "Grupo Internacional Revolución" in Spanish) that took place on August 3, 2016, in IWRG's home arena Arena Naucalpan in Naucalpan, State of Mexico, Mexico.In the main event of the show, a "Lucha de Apuestas" or "bet match", Dragon Fly defeated Demonio Infernal, forcing him to unmask and reveal his real name, José Antonio Rojas. In the semi-final match Black Terry and Judas el Traidor furthered their own storyline feud as Judas el Traidor defeated Black Terry, leading to IWRG's "Cabellera vs. Cabellera" show two weeks later. The show featured three additional matches. <S> [["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "instance of", "Professional wrestling event"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "scripted by", "International Wrestling Revolution Group"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "produced by", "International Wrestling Revolution Group"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "date", "August 3, 2016"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "location", "Arena Naucalpan"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "city", "Naucalpan"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "state", "State of Mexico"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "country", "Mexico"], ["Dragon Fly", "defeated", "Demonio Infernal"], ["Demonio Infernal", "real name", "José Antonio Rojas"], ["Black Terry", "feud with", "Judas el Traidor"], ["Judas el Traidor", "defeated", "Black Terry"], ["IWRG", "event", "Cabellera vs. Cabellera show"], ["IWRG Máscara vs. Máscara (August 2016)", "featured", "three additional matches"]]
Annamanum plagiatum is a species of beetle in the family Cerambycidae. It was described by Per Olof Christopher Aurivillius in 1913, originally under the genus "Orsidis". It is known from Borneo and Malaysia. <S> [["Annamanum plagiatum", "instance of", "Beetle"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "family", "Cerambycidae"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "described by", "Per Olof Christopher Aurivillius"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "described in", "1913"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "genus", "Orsidis"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "known from", "Borneo"], ["Annamanum plagiatum", "known from", "Malaysia"]]
Talgat Ilyasov (born 25 February 1981) is an Australian wrestler. He competed in the men's 74 kilogram freestyle wrestling competition at the 2016 Summer Olympics.Ilyasov holding the position of a President of Wrestling Australia. <S> [["Talgat Ilyasov", "instance of", "Wrestler"], ["Talgat Ilyasov", "country", "Australia"], ["Talgat Ilyasov", "born on", "25 February 1981"], ["Talgat Ilyasov", "competition", "2016 Summer Olympics"], ["Talgat Ilyasov", "weight class", "74 kilograms"], ["Talgat Ilyasov", "position", "President of Wrestling Australia"]]
Abdullah Öztürk (born October 1, 1989) is a Turkish para table tennis player of class 4 and Paralympian.Öztürk represented his country at the 2012 Summer Paralympics in London, United Kingdom.In 2014, he won the silver medal along with Ali Öztürk and Nesim Turan in the Team C5 event at the World Para Table Tennis Championships in Beijing, China.He took the gold medal with his teammates Ali Öztürk and Nesim Turan in the Team C4 event at the 2016 Lignano Master Open in Italy. He captured the gold medal in the individual C4 event at the 2016 Summer Paralympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. He won the bronze medal in the Team C4–5 event of the Paralympics along with his brother Ali Öztürk and teammate Nesim Turan.As of April 2019, Öztürk ranks second in the world list of his disability class. <S> [["Abdullah Öztürk", "instance of", "Para table tennis player"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "country", "Turkey"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "date of birth", "October 1, 1989"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "classification", "Class 4"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "Paralympian", "Yes"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "represent", "2012 Summer Paralympics"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "represent", "2016 Summer Paralympics"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "win", "Silver medal"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "win", "Gold medal"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "win", "Bronze medal"], ["Abdullah Öztürk", "rank", "Second in world list"], ["Ali Öztürk", "teammate", "Abdullah Öztürk"], ["Nesim Turan", "teammate", "Abdullah Öztürk"], ["Ali Öztürk", "teammate", "Abdullah Öztürk"], ["Nesim Turan", "teammate", "Abdullah Öztürk"], ["Ali Öztürk", "teammate", "Nesim Turan"], ["Ali Öztürk", "teammate", "Nesim Turan"], ["Ali Öztürk", "teammate", "Nesim Turan"]]
Vicenta Chávez Orozco (6 February 1867 - 30 July 1949), also known by her religious name María Vicenta de Santa Dorotea, was a Mexican Roman Catholic nun and the founder of the Servants of the Holy Spirit and the Poor. Orozco was admitted into a hospital in Guadalajara with pneumonia and there experienced a radical call to help others in the same hospital who were ill - she recovered and soon returned to fulfil this promise while later becoming a religious and establishing her own order in order to advance this mission.Orozco was beatified made a Servant of God on 13 April 1978 under Pope Paul VI and later named as Venerable under Pope John Paul II on 21 December 1991 who also beatified her on 9 November 1997. <S> [["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "date of birth", "6 February 1867"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "date of death", "30 July 1949"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "religious name", "María Vicenta de Santa Dorotea"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "nationality", "Mexican"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "occupation", "Roman Catholic nun"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "founder of", "Servants of the Holy Spirit and the Poor"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "admitted into", "hospital in Guadalajara"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "experience", "radical call to help others"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "recovered from", "pneumonia"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "established", "own order"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "beatified by", "Pope Paul VI"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "named as", "Venerable by Pope John Paul II"], ["Vicenta Chávez Orozco", "beatified by Pope John Paul II"]]
Cahuilla Creek is a tributary stream of Wilson Creek which is in turn a tributary of Temecula Creek, and the Santa Margarita River in Riverside County, California. Its mouth is at its confluence with Wilson Creek at an elevation of . Its source is at , at an elevation of 5,800 feet, on the west slope of Thomas Mountain 0.6 miles west-southwest of Tool Box Spring. It flows southwest through the Anza Valley and Cahuilla Valley in the Cahuilla Indian Reservation to Wilson Creek, 7 miles south-southwest of Cahuilla Mountain and 20 miles south-southeast of San Jacinto. <S> [    ["Cahuilla Creek", "tributary of", "Wilson Creek"],    ["Wilson Creek", "tributary of", "Temecula Creek"],    ["Wilson Creek", "tributary of", "Santa Margarita River"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "mouth at", "confluence with Wilson Creek"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "source at", "west slope of Thomas Mountain"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "flows through", "Anza Valley"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "flows through", "Cahuilla Valley"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "located in", "Riverside County, California"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "located in", "Cahuilla Indian Reservation"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "elevation at mouth", "unknown"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "elevation at source", "5,800 feet"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "distance from source to Tool Box Spring", "0.6 miles"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "distance from Cahuilla Mountain", "7 miles"],    ["Cahuilla Creek", "distance from San Jacinto", "20 miles"]]
Two of the Earthly Branches "( 两个时辰 )" is a workfor string quartet, composed by He Xuntian in 1983. <S> [["Two of the Earthly Branches", "instance of", "Musical composition"], ["Two of the Earthly Branches", "composed by", "He Xuntian"], ["Two of the Earthly Branches", "composed in", "1983"], ["Two of the Earthly Branches", "instrumentation", "String quartet"]]
Josef Schäffer (born July 2, 1891 in Moravia) was an Austrian track and field athlete who competed in the 1912 Summer Olympics. He competed in the decathlon, shot put, discus throw and two-handed discus throw. He finished tenth in the decathlon, throwing the second-furthest in the discus on his way to his score of 6568.585. In the shot put, he finished thirteenth. In the discus throw, he only managed to come twenty-ninth in the regular discus throw, but came sixteenth in the two-handed discus. <S> [["Josef Schäffer", "birth date", "July 2, 1891"], ["Josef Schäffer", "birth place", "Moravia"], ["Josef Schäffer", "nationality", "Austrian"], ["Josef Schäffer", "occupation", "track and field athlete"], ["Josef Schäffer", "competition", "1912 Summer Olympics"], ["Josef Schäffer", "events", "decathlon"], ["Josef Schäffer", "events", "shot put"], ["Josef Schäffer", "events", "discus throw"], ["Josef Schäffer", "events", "two-handed discus throw"], ["Josef Schäffer", "decathlon ranking", "tenth"], ["Josef Schäffer", "decathlon score", "6568.585"], ["Josef Schäffer", "discus throw ranking", "twenty-ninth"], ["Josef Schäffer", "discus throw type", "regular"], ["Josef Schäffer", "discus throw type", "two-handed"], ["Josef Schäffer", "shot put ranking", "thirteenth"], ["Josef Schäffer", "two-handed discus ranking", "sixteenth"]]
Ross Creek Aerodrome, , is located just east of Ross Creek, next to Shuswap Lake, British Columbia, Canada. <S> [["Ross Creek Aerodrome", "location", "Ross Creek"], ["Ross Creek Aerodrome", "location", "Shuswap Lake"], ["Ross Creek Aerodrome", "location", "British Columbia"], ["Ross Creek Aerodrome", "country", "Canada"]]
Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel, (1789 – 11 March 1865) was a British Army officer of the East India Company.Steel was the son of barrister David Steel and Mary Winde, daughter of Scudamore Winde, judge of the Supreme Court of Jamaica. Steel joined the East India Company's service as a cadet in 1805, and the following year was promoted to lieutenant in the Madras Army. He was slightly wounded in the Third Anglo-Maratha War of 1817–18. He was promoted to captain in 1821, and joined the 51st native infantry in 1824. He served on the quartermaster-general's staff at Nagpur and in the First Anglo-Burmese War in 1826. Steel was promoted to major in 1832, and from 1832 to 1845 served as secretary in the military department at Madras.In 1834, Steel took part in the capture of Coorg, and the following year was promoted to lieutenant colonel. He was appointed a Companion of the Order of the Bath in the 1838 Coronation Honours.In 1845, Steel was appointed military auditor-general and promoted to colonel of the Madras fusiliers in 1847. He commanded the Madras army during the Second Anglo-Burmese War in 1852–53. He was knighted as a Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath in December 1853. He was promoted to major general and given the command of the Pegu division and the Martaban provinces in 1854. Steel returned to England in 1856 and was promoted to lieutenant general in 1861.Steel married Elizabeth Margaret, the eldest daughter of Lieutenant Colonel William Read, in 1840. His eldest son, Col. Charles Steel, served in the Crimean War with the 12th Lancers and was present at the Siege of Sevastopol. He married Anna Caroline Wood, daughter of Rev. Sir John Page Wood, 2nd Baronet. Sir Scudamore died at his home at Hyde Park, London, in 1865. <S> [    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "instance of", "British Army officer"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "date of birth", "1789"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "date of death", "11 March 1865"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "father", "David Steel"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "mother", "Mary Winde"],    ["Mary Winde", "father", "Scudamore Winde"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "service", "East India Company"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "rank", "Lieutenant"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "wounded in", "Third Anglo-Maratha War"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "rank", "Captain"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "served in", "First Anglo-Burmese War"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "rank", "Major"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "appointed", "Companion of the Order of the Bath"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "appointed", "military auditor-general"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "rank", "Colonel"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "commanded", "Madras army"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "knighted as", "Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "rank", "Major General"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "commanded", "Pegu division and Martaban provinces"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "married", "Elizabeth Margaret"],    ["Elizabeth Margaret", "father", "Lieutenant Colonel William Read"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "son", "Col. Charles Steel"],    ["Col. Charles Steel", "served in", "Crimean War"],    ["Col. Charles Steel", "present at", "Siege of Sevastopol"],    ["Col. Charles Steel", "married", "Anna Caroline Wood"],    ["Anna Caroline Wood", "father", "Rev. Sir John Page Wood"],    ["Rev. Sir John Page Wood", "title", "2nd Baronet"],    ["Lieutenant General Sir Scudamore Winde Steel", "died at", "Hyde Park, London"]]
Palit Microsystems, Ltd. is a Taiwanese-based company, founded in 1988. It is known for exclusive manufacturing of graphic cards on the basis of NVIDIA & ATI graphic chipsets. Palit's factories are found in China, while the offices are in Taipei (Taiwan), a logistics center in Hong Kong, and branch office in Germany.Palit Microsystems runs two major brands, Palit, and Gainward, which target different global markets, and other brands like Daytona, Galaxy (GALAX), Vivkoo, Yuan, KFA2 and XpertVision. It also contract-manufactures graphics cards for other companies. In 2013 Palit Microsystems surpassed ASUSTek, becoming the biggest graphics card vendor by volume. Palit Microsystems' monthly maximum capacity reaches 1,200,000 units. As of 2011 Palit's production share was about at 20–25% of world market of graphics solutions. In the same time on the Russian market Palit had more than 40%, in Ukraine – about 30%.In 2005 Palit Microsystems acquired the Gainward brand, company and branch Gainward Europe GmbH for $1 million of Taiwan-based TNC Industrial. <S> [["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "country", "Taiwan"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "founded in", "1988"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "known for", "exclusive manufacturing of graphic cards on the basis of NVIDIA & ATI graphic chipsets"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "factories located in", "China"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "offices located in", "Taipei (Taiwan), Hong Kong, Germany"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "runs brands", "Palit, Gainward, Daytona, Galaxy (GALAX), Vivkoo, Yuan, KFA2, XpertVision"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "contract-manufactures graphics cards for other companies"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "surpassed ASUSTek in 2013 as biggest graphics card vendor by volume"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "monthly maximum capacity reaches", "1,200,000 units"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "production share in 2011 was about", "20-25% of world market of graphics solutions"], ["Palit Microsystems, Ltd.", "acquired Gainward brand in 2005 for $1 million"], ["Gainward Europe GmbH", "acquired by Palit Microsystems in 2005 for $1 million"], ["Gainward Europe GmbH", "owned by", "Taiwan-based TNC Industrial"]]
Noah Mascoll-Gomes (born 27 May 1999) is an Antigua and Barbuda competitive swimmer. He competed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, in the men's 200 metre freestyle. He finished 44th in the heats and did not advance to the semifinals. He was the flag bearer for Antigua and Barbuda in the closing ceremony. <S> [["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "instance of", "Competitive swimmer"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "birth date", "27 May 1999"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "country", "Antigua and Barbuda"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "competition", "2016 Summer Olympics"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "event", "Men's 200 metre freestyle"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "finish position", "44th"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "advancement", "Did not advance to semifinals"], ["Noah Mascoll-Gomes", "flag bearer", "Antigua and Barbuda"], ["2016 Summer Olympics", "location", "Rio de Janeiro"], ["Antigua and Barbuda", "flag bearer", "Noah Mascoll-Gomes"]]
