Oxford Hawks Hockey Club is a field hockey club that is based at Banbury Road North in Oxford. It was founded in 1938. Some fixtures are held at other venues including Gosford Hill School, St Edward's School, Oxford and Headington School, Oxford. The club runs seven men's and seven women's teams and also has a large junior section. Both first XI teams have progressed in recent years with the men's first XI playing in the Men's England Hockey League Division One South and the women's first XI playing in the England Hockey League Investec Conference West <S> [["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "instance of", "Field hockey club"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "location", "Banbury Road North, Oxford"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "founded", "1938"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "fixtures held at", "Gosford Hill School"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "fixtures held at", "St Edward's School, Oxford"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "fixtures held at", "Headington School, Oxford"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "runs", "7 men's teams"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "runs", "7 women's teams"], ["Oxford Hawks Hockey Club", "has", "large junior section"], ["Men's first XI team", "progressed to", "Men's England Hockey League Division One South"], ["Women's first XI team", "progressed to", "England Hockey League Investec Conference West"]]
The Waterford Bridge, formerly designated Bridge L0327 and now Bridge L3275, is a historic steel truss bridge over the Cannon River in Waterford Township, Minnesota, United States. It was constructed in 1909 and is one of the state's earliest surviving bridges to use rigid rather than pinned connections. Moreover, it is Minnesota's only known road bridge in which some of the rigid connections are fastened with bolts rather than rivets.The bridge was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2010 for having state-level significance in the theme of engineering. It was nominated for being a rare surviving example of Minnesota's once-common camelback through truss bridges, and for its early and uniquely transitional rigid connections. <S> [["Waterford Bridge", "instance of", "Steel truss bridge"], ["Waterford Bridge", "location", "Waterford Township, Minnesota, United States"], ["Waterford Bridge", "constructed in", "1909"], ["Waterford Bridge", "designated as", "Bridge L0327"], ["Waterford Bridge", "now designated as", "Bridge L3275"], ["Waterford Bridge", "significance", "Engineering"], ["Waterford Bridge", "listed on", "National Register of Historic Places"], ["Waterford Bridge", "reason for nomination", "Rare surviving example of camelback through truss bridges"], ["Waterford Bridge", "reason for nomination", "Early and uniquely transitional rigid connections"], ["Waterford Bridge", "connection type", "Rigid connections"], ["Waterford Bridge", "connection type", "Bolts"], ["Waterford Bridge", "connection type", "Rivets"]]
Below Her Mouth is a 2016 Canadian erotic romantic drama film directed by April Mullen and written by Stephanie Fabrizi. The film stars Natalie Krill as Jasmine and Erika Linder as Dallas, two women in Toronto who meet and begin a passionate love affair. The cast also includes Tommie-Amber Pirie, Mayko Nguyen, Elise Bauman, Melanie Leishman and Sebastian Pigott. <S> [["Below Her Mouth", "instance of", "Film"], ["Below Her Mouth", "country", "Canada"], ["Below Her Mouth", "genre", "Erotic romantic drama"], ["Below Her Mouth", "director", "April Mullen"], ["Below Her Mouth", "writer", "Stephanie Fabrizi"], ["Below Her Mouth", "cast", "Natalie Krill, Erika Linder, Tommie-Amber Pirie, Mayko Nguyen, Elise Bauman, Melanie Leishman, Sebastian Pigott"], ["Natalie Krill", "character", "Jasmine"], ["Erika Linder", "character", "Dallas"], ["Jasmine", "relationship", "Dallas"], ["Jasmine", "location", "Toronto"], ["Dallas", "location", "Toronto"]]
Truly Madly Guilty is a novel by Australian author Liane Moriarty. It tells the story of Sam and Clementine, an ordinary yet busy married couple trying to balance work and family life. After the couple is invited by Clementine's old friend Erika to a neighbor's barbecue party, a spiral of intrigue, lust, and betrayal is unleashed. The book was published in July 2016 by Flatiron Books.Just weeks after the novel's release, it was announced that Reese Witherspoon and Nicole Kidman had optioned for the novel's film rights. At the time, Witherspoon and Kidman had already begun producing a television miniseries adaptation of Moriarty's previous novel, "Big Little Lies". <S> [["Truly Madly Guilty", "instance of", "Novel"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "author", "Liane Moriarty"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "main characters", "Sam and Clementine"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "setting", "neighbor's barbecue party"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "themes", "intrigue, lust, betrayal"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "publication date", "July 2016"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "publisher", "Flatiron Books"], ["Truly Madly Guilty", "film adaptation", "Reese Witherspoon, Nicole Kidman"], ["Reese Witherspoon, Nicole Kidman", "previous project", "television miniseries adaptation of Big Little Lies"]]
The Asia Spelling Cup is the largest annual spelling bee in Southeast Asia, and is organised by Qooco, a mobile language learning solutions provider. The first Asia Spelling Cup took place in Singapore in 2013, the next event took place in Bali, Indonesia in 2014, and the next in Bangkok, Thailand in 2015. The 2016 Asia Spelling Cup took place in Bangkok, Thailand, at the Conrad Hotel on November 12, 2016, and the 2017 event took place in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on November 12, 2017.The Asia Spelling Cup draws on primary and secondary school students in various countries in Asia, including Malaysia, Thailand, China and Indonesia. The 2013 event included Singaporean students. <S> [["Asia Spelling Cup", "instance of", "Spelling bee"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "largest in", "Southeast Asia"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "organised by", "Qooco"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "first event location", "Singapore"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "next event location", "Bali, Indonesia"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "next event location", "Bangkok, Thailand"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "2016 event location", "Bangkok, Thailand"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "2017 event location", "Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "draws on students from", "Malaysia"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "draws on students from", "Thailand"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "draws on students from", "China"], ["Asia Spelling Cup", "draws on students from", "Indonesia"], ["2013 event", "included students from", "Singapore"]]
The 2016 Sun Belt Conference football season was the 16th season in which the Sun Belt Conference operated a football league, and was part of the 2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season. The season began on September 1 with Appalachian State facing Tennessee. This was the third season for the Sun Belt since realignment that took effect in 2014, which added the tenth and eleventh members — Idaho and New Mexico State. Both teams were previously independents before joining the conference. The Sun Belt Conference is a "Group of Five" conference under the College Football Playoff format along with the American Athletic Conference, Conference USA, the Mid-American Conference, and the Mountain West Conference.In this season, the Sun Belt football conference included 11 members: Appalachian State, Arkansas State, Georgia Southern, Georgia State, Idaho, Louisiana–Lafayette, Louisiana–Monroe, New Mexico State, South Alabama, Texas State, and Troy. The conference championship was determined by win-loss record within the conference.Arkansas State entered the season as defending Sun Belt champions, as they went undefeated in 2015 conference play. The Red Wolves went on to lose to Louisiana Tech in the New Orleans Bowl 28–47. <S> [    ["2016 Sun Belt Conference football season", "instance of", "Football season"],    ["2016 Sun Belt Conference football season", "part of", "2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season"],    ["2016 Sun Belt Conference football season", "start date", "September 1"],    ["2016 Sun Belt Conference football season", "teams", ["Appalachian State", "Arkansas State", "Georgia Southern", "Georgia State", "Idaho", "Louisiana–Lafayette", "Louisiana–Monroe", "New Mexico State", "South Alabama", "Texas State", "Troy"]],    ["2016 Sun Belt Conference football season", "conference championship determined by", "win-loss record within the conference"],    ["Arkansas State", "defending champion", "Sun Belt champions"],    ["Arkansas State", "lost to", "Louisiana Tech in the New Orleans Bowl 28–47"],    ["Sun Belt Conference", "type", "Group of Five conference"],    ["Sun Belt Conference", "teams", ["Appalachian State", "Arkansas State", "Georgia Southern", "Georgia State", "Idaho", "Louisiana–Lafayette", "Louisiana–Monroe", "New Mexico State", "South Alabama", "Texas State", "Troy"]],    ["Sun Belt Conference", "realignment in", "2014"],    ["Sun Belt Conference", "added members", ["Idaho", "New Mexico State"]],    ["Idaho", "previous status", "independent"],    ["New Mexico State", "previous status", "independent"]]
