Grevillea eryngioides, commonly called the curly grevillea, is a shrub of the genus "Grevillea" native to an in the eastern Wheatbelt and western Goldfields-Esperance regions of Western Australia.The suckering glaucous shrub typically grows to a height of and has non-glaucous branchlets. It has simple dissected leaves with a blade that is in length and wide. It blooms from September to January and produces a terminal inflorescence with yellow or purple flowers, followed by a globose glaucous viscid fruit that is long. <S> [["Grevillea eryngioides", "common name", "Curly grevillea"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "genus", "Grevillea"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "native to", "Eastern Wheatbelt"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "native to", "Western Goldfields-Esperance regions"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "height", "unknown"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "branchlets", "non-glaucous"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "leaf blade length", "unknown"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "leaf blade width", "unknown"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "blooms from", "September"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "blooms until", "January"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "inflorescence color", "yellow"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "inflorescence color", "purple"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "fruit color", "glaucous"], ["Grevillea eryngioides", "fruit length", "unknown"]]
