Sonai (Pron:/'sə(ʊ)'nʌɪ/) is a town in the Cachar district in the Indian state of Assam. It is also the name of a circle and block in the town. The River Sonai flows through the town of Sonai joining with Barak River near Dungripar Village of Sonai. The Chandragiri Park and an Archeological site, a temple of Kachari Kingdom at Shivtilla (Changutilla) near Madhab Chandra Das College (MCD College) is a famous place to visit. <S> [["Sonai", "instance of", "Town"], ["Sonai", "located in", "Cachar district"], ["Sonai", "located in", "Assam"], ["Sonai", "has circle", "Sonai"], ["Sonai", "has block", "Sonai"], ["Sonai", "River", "Sonai"], ["Sonai", "joins with", "Barak River"], ["Sonai", "near", "Dungripar Village"], ["Sonai", "has", "Chandragiri Park"], ["Sonai", "has", "Archeological site"], ["Archeological site", "temple of", "Kachari Kingdom"], ["temple of Kachari Kingdom", "located near", "Shivtilla"], ["Shivtilla", "also known as", "Changutilla"], ["Changutilla", "located near", "Madhab Chandra Das College"], ["Madhab Chandra Das College", "also known as", "MCD College"], ["MCD College", "famous place to visit"]]
Louis Perceau (22 September 1883 – 20 April 1942) was a 20th-century French polygraph. He used several pseudonyms including "Helpey bibliographe poitevin", "Dr. Ludovico Hernandez", "Alexandre de Vérineau", "Un vieux journaliste", "Radeville et Deschamps", "marquis Boniface de Richequeue", sometimes jointly with Fernand Fleuret. <S> [["Louis Perceau", "instance of", "French polygraph"], ["Louis Perceau", "date of birth", "22 September 1883"], ["Louis Perceau", "date of death", "20 April 1942"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "Helpey bibliographe poitevin"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "Dr. Ludovico Hernandez"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "Alexandre de Vérineau"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "Un vieux journaliste"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "Radeville et Deschamps"], ["Louis Perceau", "pseudonyms", "marquis Boniface de Richequeue"], ["Louis Perceau", "collaborator", "Fernand Fleuret"]]
The AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup, previously the AFC U-20 Futsal Championship, is the premier youth futsal competition of the Asian Football Confederation nations. It was first held in 2017 and played biennially. From 2021, the tournament will be rebranded from the "AFC U-20 Futsal Championship" to the "AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup". <S> [["AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup", "instance of", "Youth futsal competition"], ["AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup", "organization", "Asian Football Confederation"], ["AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup", "first held", 2017], ["AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup", "frequency", "biennial"], ["AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup", "rebranded to", "AFC U-20 Futsal Asian Cup"]]
