Arthur Ormston (born 3 June 1900 in Alnwick) was an English association footballer, who played for eight different clubs in the Football League during the interwar period.After brief spells with Radcliffe Welfare United and South Shields, Ormston made his Football League debut with Chesterfield during the 1921–22 season. He went on to play for Durham City, Coventry City, Barrow, Wigan Borough, Oldham Athletic, Bradford City, Bristol Rovers and Oldham again, all in quick succession. After this he dropped out of the League and made further appearances for Blyth Spartans, Stalybridge Celtic and Macclesfield. <S> [    ["Arthur Ormston", "birth date", "3 June 1900"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "place of birth", "Alnwick"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "nationality", "English"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "occupation", "association footballer"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Chesterfield"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Durham City"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Coventry City"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Barrow"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Wigan Borough"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Oldham Athletic"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Bradford City"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Bristol Rovers"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Blyth Spartans"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Stalybridge Celtic"],    ["Arthur Ormston", "played for", "Macclesfield"]]
is a Japanese idol anime television series produced by Seven Arcs Pictures and Happy Elements. It is a "hybrid anime", where the first half of the show is a typical animation and the second half is a live-action segment featuring the anime's voice actresses.Katsuya Kikuchi directed the anime with scripts written by Hiroshi Oonogi, and I've Sound produced the music. Idol Memories debuted on October 3, 2016 on Tokyo MX with further airings on AT-X. <S> [["Idol Memories", "instance of", "Japanese idol anime television series"], ["Idol Memories", "produced by", "Seven Arcs Pictures"], ["Idol Memories", "produced by", "Happy Elements"], ["Idol Memories", "type", "hybrid anime"], ["Idol Memories", "director", "Katsuya Kikuchi"], ["Idol Memories", "scripts written by", "Hiroshi Oonogi"], ["Idol Memories", "music produced by", "I've Sound"], ["Idol Memories", "debuted on", "October 3, 2016"], ["Idol Memories", "aired on", "Tokyo MX"], ["Idol Memories", "further airings on", "AT-X"]]
The 2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy was a senior international figure skating competition held in September 2016 at the Eissportzentrum Oberstdorf. It was part of the 2016–17 ISU Challenger Series. Medals were awarded in the disciplines of men's singles, ladies' singles, pair skating, and ice dance. <S> [["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "instance of", "Senior international figure skating competition"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "held at", "Eissportzentrum Oberstdorf"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "part of", "2016-17 ISU Challenger Series"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "awarded medals in", "Men's singles"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "awarded medals in", "Ladies' singles"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "awarded medals in", "Pair skating"], ["2016 CS Nebelhorn Trophy", "awarded medals in", "Ice dance"]]
Castle Rock Mountain () is in the Beartooth Mountains in the U.S. state of Montana. The peak is one of the tallest in the Beatooth Mountains, the tenth-tallest in Montana and is in the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness, on the border of Custer and Gallatin national forests. The nearest taller mountain to Castle Rock Mountain is Castle Rock Spire, east. Castle Rock Mountain is flanked by the Sundance Glacier to the north and the Castle Rock Glacier to the south. <S> [["Castle Rock Mountain", "located in", "Beartooth Mountains"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "located in", "Montana"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "tallest in", "Beartooth Mountains"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "tenth-tallest in", "Montana"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "located in", "Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "located on border of", "Custer National Forest"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "located on border of", "Gallatin National Forest"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "nearest taller mountain", "Castle Rock Spire"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "flanked by", "Sundance Glacier"], ["Castle Rock Mountain", "flanked by", "Castle Rock Glacier"]]
Okada Manila () is a casino resort and hotel complex located on the Entertainment City gaming strip in Parañaque, Metro Manila, Philippines.In 2007, with a total construction cost of about 250 billion Yen and spending 7 years, Japanese billionaire Kazuo Okada established and managed Okada Manila. <S> [["Okada Manila", "instance of", "Casino resort"], ["Okada Manila", "instance of", "Hotel complex"], ["Okada Manila", "located in", "Entertainment City gaming strip"], ["Okada Manila", "located in", "Parañaque"], ["Okada Manila", "located in", "Metro Manila"], ["Okada Manila", "country", "Philippines"], ["Okada Manila", "established by", "Kazuo Okada"], ["Okada Manila", "construction cost", "250 billion Yen"], ["Okada Manila", "construction duration", "7 years"]]
Daulowal is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Bhulath, away from district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per the constitution of India and Panchayati raj (India). <S> [["Daulowal", "instance of", "Village"], ["Daulowal", "located in", "Bhulath Tehsil"], ["Daulowal", "located in", "Kapurthala district"], ["Daulowal", "located in", "Punjab State, India"], ["Daulowal", "distance from", "Bhulath"], ["Daulowal", "distance from", "Kapurthala"], ["Daulowal", "administered by", "Sarpanch"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Elected representative"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Village representative"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Constitution of India"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Panchayati raj (India)"]]
Hotel Monterey is a 1973 American silent documentary film directed by Chantal Akerman. It is Akerman's first feature film.In 2013, an article in the "Village Voice" stated that "Hotel Monterey", along with two other Akerman films, "La Chambre" and "News from Home" are a "not-to-be-missed event" as part of MoMa's “To Save and Project” film series. <S> [["Hotel Monterey", "instance of", "Film"], ["Hotel Monterey", "year", "1973"], ["Hotel Monterey", "country", "United States"], ["Hotel Monterey", "director", "Chantal Akerman"], ["Chantal Akerman", "first feature film", "Hotel Monterey"], ["Hotel Monterey", "part of", "MoMa's To Save and Project film series"], ["MoMa's To Save and Project film series", "event", "not-to-be-missed"], ["MoMa's To Save and Project film series", "films", "Hotel Monterey, La Chambre, News from Home"], ["Hotel Monterey", "article in", "Village Voice"]]
Raipur Rajputan is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Bhulath, away from district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative of village as per the constitution of India and Panchayati raj (India). <S> [["Raipur Rajputan", "instance of", "Village"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "located in", "Bhulath Tehsil"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "located in", "Kapurthala district"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "located in", "Punjab State"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "distance from", "Bhulath"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "distance from", "Kapurthala"], ["Raipur Rajputan", "administered by", "Sarpanch"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Elected representative"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Village representative"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Constitution of India"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Panchayati raj (India)"]]
Nadala is a village in Bholath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Bhulath, away from district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Municipal Councillor who is an elected representative of village as per the constitution of India and Municipality (India). <S> [["Nadala", "instance of", "Village"], ["Nadala", "located in", "Bholath Tehsil"], ["Nadala", "located in", "Kapurthala district"], ["Nadala", "located in", "Punjab State"], ["Nadala", "distance from", "Bhulath"], ["Nadala", "distance from", "Kapurthala"], ["Nadala", "administered by", "Municipal Councillor"], ["Municipal Councillor", "elected representative of", "Village"], ["Municipal Councillor", "elected representative of", "Constitution of India"], ["Municipal Councillor", "elected representative of", "Municipality (India)"]]
Aero Engine Corporation of China (AECC) is a Chinese state-owned aerospace manufacturer focused on the design and development of aeroengine and related technology. The company was established on August 28, 2016. At launch, AECC was to be capitalised with US$7.5 billion with AVIC and COMAC both shareholders, China's two main state aerospace companies. The corporation consists of 46 affiliate companies, including 22 engine companies, several institutes, 3 aeroengine-repairing factories and some other small companies, with the majority of the affiliate companies having been split from Aviation Industry Corporation of China. The main institutes under AECC are Beijing Institute of Aerial Materials, Shenyang Engine Design and Research Institute, China Gas Turbine Research Institute, China Aero Power Machine Research Institute, Guizhou Aero-Engine Research Institute, and Chine Aero Power Control System Institute.The main subsidiaries of AECC are Harbin Dong'an Engine Manufacturing Company, Shenyang Liming Engine Manufacturing Company, Chengdu Engine Manufacturing Company, Xi'an Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company, Liyang Engine Manufacturing Company, and Shanghai Commercial Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company. <S> [["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "instance of", "Aerospace manufacturer"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "focus", "Design and development of aeroengine and related technology"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "established on", "August 28, 2016"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "capitalised with", "US$7.5 billion"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "shareholders", "AVIC and COMAC"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "consists of", "46 affiliate companies"], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "main institutes"], ["Beijing Institute of Aerial Materials", "Shenyang Engine Design and Research Institute", "China Gas Turbine Research Institute", "China Aero Power Machine Research Institute", "Guizhou Aero-Engine Research Institute", "China Aero Power Control System Institute"]], ["Aero Engine Corporation of China", "main subsidiaries", ["Harbin Dong'an Engine Manufacturing Company", "Shenyang Liming Engine Manufacturing Company", "Chengdu Engine Manufacturing Company", "Xi'an Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company", "Liyang Engine Manufacturing Company", "Shanghai Commercial Aero-Engine Manufacturing Company"]]
ABC Country is a digital radio station, available on mobile devices, DAB+ digital radio, digital TV and online. A small number of self-help retransmissions, mainly in WA and Qld also carry the station's programme stream. It is owned and operated by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation. <S> [["ABC Country", "instance of", "Digital radio station"], ["ABC Country", "available on", "Mobile devices"], ["ABC Country", "available on", "DAB+ digital radio"], ["ABC Country", "available on", "Digital TV"], ["ABC Country", "available on", "Online"], ["ABC Country", "owner", "Australian Broadcasting Corporation"], ["ABC Country", "operator", "Australian Broadcasting Corporation"], ["ABC Country", "retransmissions in", "WA"], ["ABC Country", "retransmissions in", "Qld"], ["ABC Country", "programme stream", "Carried by self-help retransmissions"]]
The Cadell Fault is a north-south trending intra-plate geological fault in the Riverina area of New South Wales and Victoria within Australia. It straddles the Murray River and in quite recent prehistoric times has impacted its course, as well as the courses of the Edward River, Wakool River, Goulburn River and Campaspe River. The Cadell Fault is notable due to this impact and has been described as one of the most significant examples of seismic activity changing the course of rivers. The fault is visible as a continuous earthen ridge along the Cobb Highway between Deniliquin and Echuca, and extending further south into Victoria. The fault is likely named after Francis Cadell, an early pioneer of the Murray River and river trader. <S> [["Cadell Fault", "instance of", "Geological fault"], ["Cadell Fault", "location", "Riverina area"], ["Cadell Fault", "location", "New South Wales"], ["Cadell Fault", "location", "Victoria"], ["Cadell Fault", "location", "Australia"], ["Cadell Fault", "impacts", "Murray River"], ["Cadell Fault", "impacts", "Edward River"], ["Cadell Fault", "impacts", "Wakool River"], ["Cadell Fault", "impacts", "Goulburn River"], ["Cadell Fault", "impacts", "Campaspe River"], ["Cadell Fault", "notable for", "impact on river courses"], ["Cadell Fault", "visible as", "earthen ridge"], ["Cadell Fault", "location", "Cobb Highway"], ["Cadell Fault", "extends into", "Victoria"], ["Cadell Fault", "named after", "Francis Cadell"], ["Francis Cadell", "occupation", "pioneer"], ["Francis Cadell", "association", "Murray River"], ["Francis Cadell", "association", "river trader"]]
The Trumbull Correctional Institution is a medium-security prison for men located in Leavittsburg, Trumbull County, Ohio and operated by the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction. The facility first opened in 1992 and has a population of 1,529 state inmates, with mixed minimum, medium, and close (maximum) security levels. <S> [["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "instance of", "Medium-security prison"], ["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "location", "Leavittsburg, Trumbull County, Ohio"], ["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "operator", "Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction"], ["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "opened", "1992"], ["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "population", "1,529 state inmates"], ["Trumbull Correctional Institution", "security levels", "mixed minimum, medium, and close (maximum)"]]
The Ashi River is a right tributary of the Songhua in eastern Manchuria, in Harbin's Acheng District in the People's Republic of China. <S> [["Ashi River", "tributary of", "Songhua River"], ["Ashi River", "location", "Manchuria"], ["Ashi River", "district", "Acheng District"], ["Acheng District", "city", "Harbin"], ["Acheng District", "country", "People's Republic of China"]]
Krishnananda Agamavagisha (Devanagari; कृष्णानन्द आगमवागीश, Bengali language: কৃষ্ণানন্দ আগমবাগীশ) (a.k.a. Mahamahopadhyaya Krishnananda Bhattacharya) was a noted Kulin Bengali Brahmin of Nabadwip, Nadia district origin and a renowned Pandita (Scholar) and Sadhaka of Tantra tradition who lived around 1575 CE. He is the author of the "Tantrasara".He (being the introducer of Navya Tantric-scripture, "Tantrasara") considered to be one among the four pillars of Shreehatta origin scholars in Nabadwip worked for Sanatana Philosophy, alongside Raghunatha (introducer of Navya Nyaya), Raghunandana (introducer of Navya Smriti), and Vishvambhara : Chaitanya (introducer of Navya Vaishnava). <S> [    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "origin", "Nabadwip, Nadia district"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "profession", "Pandita"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "tradition", "Tantra"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "author of", "Tantrasara"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "considered as", "pillar of Shreehatta origin scholars"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "worked with", "Raghunatha"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "worked with", "Raghunandana"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "worked with", "Vishvambhara : Chaitanya"],    ["Krishnananda Agamavagisha", "introducer of", "Navya Tantric-scripture"],    ["Raghunatha", "introducer of", "Navya Nyaya"],    ["Raghunandana", "introducer of", "Navya Smriti"],    ["Vishvambhara : Chaitanya", "introducer of", "Navya Vaishnava"]]
Marugalpatty is a village in Theni District, in the southern state of Tamil Nadu, India. It is located western 18 km from Periyakulam and south 15 km from Andipatti. <S> [["Marugalpatty", "instance of", "Village"], ["Marugalpatty", "located in", "Theni District"], ["Marugalpatty", "located in", "Tamil Nadu"], ["Marugalpatty", "country", "India"], ["Marugalpatty", "distance from", "Periyakulam", "18 km"], ["Marugalpatty", "distance from", "Andipatti", "15 km"]]
Grand Casino Portorož is located in Portorož and is the oldest casino in Slovenia. It is owned and operated by Casino Portorož d.d. The casino was renovated in 2012. <S> [["Grand Casino Portorož", "location", "Portorož"], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "instance of", "Casino"], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "country", "Slovenia"], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "owner", "Casino Portorož d.d."], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "operator", "Casino Portorož d.d."], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "age", "oldest"], ["Grand Casino Portorož", "renovation year", 2012]]
Saeed Ghani (; born 8 November 1972) is a Pakistani politician who is the current Provincial Minister of Sindh for Labour, Education and Literacy and Human Resources. He has been a member of the Provincial Assembly of Sindh since August 2018. Previously, he was a member of Provincial Assembly of Sindh from July 2017 to May 2018 and a Member of the Senate of Pakistan <S> [["Saeed Ghani", "instance of", "Pakistani politician"], ["Saeed Ghani", "position", "Provincial Minister of Sindh for Labour, Education and Literacy and Human Resources"], ["Saeed Ghani", "member of", "Provincial Assembly of Sindh"], ["Saeed Ghani", "member of", "Senate of Pakistan"], ["Saeed Ghani", "birth date", "8 November 1972"]]
Museum Masuuni Brunou is a museum about the industrial history of Juankoski, Finland . The museum is situated in the old blast furnace building right beside the rapids (now dammed and diverted to produce hydro electricity) and is in the centre of the old foundry milieu.The Juankoski Heritage Society was founded in 1990 to safeguard the cultural and historical heritage of the area. The Museum was opened by the society in 1991 and has displays relating to products of the foundry, local history and the lives of local inhabitants.The museum's name 'Blast furnace Brunou' comes from building's original use and from the name of one of the founders of the foundry, Brynolf Brunou.The main entry hall contains displays about the development from peasant to iron worker as well as the development of the factory from an ironworks to a cardboard mill. The second floor contains products from the foundry.In other floors there is changing displays with different themes. The museum contains mainly products of the ironworks from the 1900s.The museum is open in the summer from June to August. <S> [["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "instance of", "Museum"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "located in", "Juankoski, Finland"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "situated in", "old blast furnace building"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "founded by", "Juankoski Heritage Society"],["Juankoski Heritage Society", "founded in", "1990"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "opened by", "Juankoski Heritage Society"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "contains displays about", "products of the foundry, local history, lives of local inhabitants"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "name", "Blast furnace Brunou"],["Blast furnace Brunou", "origin", "building's original use, name of one of the founders of the foundry, Brynolf Brunou"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "contains displays about", "development from peasant to iron worker, development of the factory from ironworks to cardboard mill"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "contains products from", "foundry"],["Museum Masuuni Brunou", "open", "summer from June to August"]]
Florentine Junction, also known as Pillinger’s Creek, Risby’s Junction, Florentine Rail Yard and Florentine Depot, is the terminus of the Derwent Valley Railway, a 3’ 6” narrow gauge railway that operates from New Norfolk in Tasmania, Australia. The station opened in 1936 but closed in the mid twentieth century when the railway beyond Kallista was closed. <S> [["Florentine Junction", "also known as", "Pillinger’s Creek"], ["Florentine Junction", "also known as", "Risby’s Junction"], ["Florentine Junction", "also known as", "Florentine Rail Yard"], ["Florentine Junction", "also known as", "Florentine Depot"], ["Florentine Junction", "terminus of", "Derwent Valley Railway"], ["Derwent Valley Railway", "gauge", "3’ 6”"], ["Derwent Valley Railway", "operates from", "New Norfolk"], ["New Norfolk", "country", "Australia"], ["Florentine Junction", "opened in", "1936"], ["Florentine Junction", "closed in", "mid twentieth century"], ["Kallista", "closed", "railway beyond"]]
Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal (born 5 March 1982) is an Indian sprinter who specialises in the 400 metres event. He participated in the 4 × 400 metres relay event at the 2016 Summer Olympics.In July 2016, Muhammed was part of the relay team that broke the national 4 × 400 metres relay at Bangalore and qualified for the Olympics. The quartet of Muhammed, Mohammad Anas, Ayyasamy Dharun and Arokia Rajiv clocked 3:00:91, rewriting the national record of 3:02.17 set by themselves four weeks earlier in Turkey. The performance also helped the relay team jump to 13th place in the world rankings. <S> [    ["Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal", "instance of", "Sprinter"],    ["Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal", "nationality", "Indian"],    ["Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal", "specializes in", "400 metres event"],    ["Kunhu Muhammed Puthanpurakkal", "participated in", "2016 Summer Olympics"],    ["Muhammed", "part of relay team", "national 4 × 400 metres relay"],    ["Muhammed", "part of relay team", "relay team that broke national record"],    ["Muhammed", "part of relay team", "relay team that qualified for Olympics"],    ["Muhammed", "part of quartet with", "Mohammad Anas"],    ["Muhammed", "part of quartet with", "Ayyasamy Dharun"],    ["Muhammed", "part of quartet with", "Arokia Rajiv"],    ["Muhammed", "clocked", "3:00:91"],    ["Muhammed", "rewrote national record of", "3:02.17"],    ["Muhammed", "set national record in", "Turkey"],    ["Muhammed", "helped relay team jump to", "13th place in world rankings"]]
Make Votes Matter is a political pressure group based in the United Kingdom which campaigns for replacing the first-past-the-post voting system with one of proportional representation for elections to the British House of Commons. <S> [["Make Votes Matter", "instance of", "Political pressure group"], ["Make Votes Matter", "country", "United Kingdom"], ["Make Votes Matter", "campaigns for", "Replacing first-past-the-post voting system with proportional representation"], ["Replacing first-past-the-post voting system with proportional representation", "for", "Elections to British House of Commons"]]
Johnny Laws (born January 12, 1943) is an American Chicago blues guitarist, singer and songwriter. A regular performer for over half a century in Chicago's South Side clubs, Laws has released two albums, including "Burnin' in My Soul", of which "Blues & Rhythm" magazine in November 1999 noted, "It's a real shame that Johnny Laws has been unjustly ignored in the past... This is an enjoyable CD... Full marks to those folks at Electro-Fi."His version of McKinley Mitchell's "End of the Rainbow" demonstrates his versatility and vocal range.In an April 1999 editorial leader, the "Toronto Star" remarked that "South Side Chicago fave Johnny Laws... [is] winning plaudits for his seductive, soul-drenched blues." <S> [["Johnny Laws", "occupation", "Guitarist"], ["Johnny Laws", "occupation", "Singer"], ["Johnny Laws", "occupation", "Songwriter"], ["Johnny Laws", "birth date", "January 12, 1943"], ["Johnny Laws", "nationality", "American"], ["Johnny Laws", "location", "Chicago"], ["Johnny Laws", "genre", "Blues"], ["Johnny Laws", "album", "Burnin' in My Soul"], ["Johnny Laws", "publication", "Blues & Rhythm magazine"], ["Johnny Laws", "song", "End of the Rainbow"], ["Johnny Laws", "publication", "Toronto Star"], ["Johnny Laws", "praise", "Seductive blues"], ["Johnny Laws", "praise", "Soul-drenched blues"]]
The Giraldilla International is the name of an international badminton tournament, which is organized as an open championship of Cuba. The competition is held annually since 2000 and is now a young supraregional Badminton Championship. The organizer was the Cuban Badminton Association ( "Federación Cubana de Badminton") in cooperation with the Badminton Pan Am continental federation.At 2013, the tournament was classified as "Future Series" by the Badminton World Federation (BWF), since the fifteenth event in March 2014 Giraldilla classified as "International Series" level, which held on to win the tournament before $1,700 now $2,500 points for the world ranking will be credited.The tournament is named after the unofficial symbol of the city of Havana, "La Giraldilla" is a bronze weathervane in female figure on the oldest fortress of the city, the Castillo de la Real Fuerza. Until XIII, Giraldilla 2012 which was held in Pinar del Río, Havana is the host city of the tournament.The XVI edition held in March 2015 at Havana. Registration of participants is carried out in each case solely on the WBF. On the players who reach at least the semi-finals, a staggered by ranking prize pool of currently $5,000 will be paid. <S> [["Giraldilla International", "instance of", "Badminton tournament"], ["Giraldilla International", "organized by", "Cuban Badminton Association"], ["Giraldilla International", "held annually since", "2000"], ["Giraldilla International", "classification", "International Series"], ["Giraldilla International", "named after", "La Giraldilla"], ["La Giraldilla", "symbol of", "city of Havana"], ["La Giraldilla", "located on", "Castillo de la Real Fuerza"], ["Havana", "host city of", "Giraldilla International"], ["Giraldilla International", "held in", "March 2015"], ["Giraldilla International", "prize pool", "$5,000"], ["Giraldilla International", "registration", "WBF"], ["Giraldilla International", "cooperation with", "Badminton Pan Am continental federation"]]
Ask the StoryBots is an American live action/animated children's television series based on the characters from the StoryBots educational website and videos. It premiered exclusively on Netflix on August 12, 2016. Originally created and produced by JibJab Bros. Studios, the StoryBots media franchise was fully acquired by Netflix in May 2019.In its first season, the series was nominated for an Annie Awards, was a finalist for a Peabody Award, was nominated in the International category at the British Academy Children's Awards and received six nominations for the Daytime Emmy Awards, including Outstanding Preschool Children's Animated Program. It won the 2017 Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Interactive Media - Enhancement to a Daytime Program or Series. Its second season, which premiered on Netflix on August 24, 2018, received the Annie Award for Best Animated Television Production for Preschool Children and won two Daytime Emmy Awards for writing and directing."Ask the StoryBots" also inspired a holiday special, "A StoryBots Christmas", also on Netflix, which won two Daytime Emmy Awards. Starting in its second season, "Ask the StoryBots" has been translated into 22 languages and is available for streaming on Netflix in 190 countries.A third season premiered on August 2, 2019. A trailer for the new episodes was launched on YouTube ahead of the season's premiere. <S> [["Ask the StoryBots", "instance of", "Television series"],["Ask the StoryBots", "based on", "StoryBots educational website and videos"],["Ask the StoryBots", "premiere date", "August 12, 2016"],["Ask the StoryBots", "created by", "JibJab Bros. Studios"],["StoryBots media franchise", "fully acquired by", "Netflix"],["Ask the StoryBots", "nominated for", "Annie Awards"],["Ask the StoryBots", "finalist for", "Peabody Award"],["Ask the StoryBots", "nominated in", "International category at British Academy Children's Awards"],["Ask the StoryBots", "received nominations for", "Daytime Emmy Awards"],["Ask the StoryBots", "won", "2017 Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Interactive Media - Enhancement to a Daytime Program or Series"],["Second season of Ask the StoryBots", "premiere date", "August 24, 2018"],["Second season of Ask the StoryBots", "won", "Annie Award for Best Animated Television Production for Preschool Children"],["Second season of Ask the StoryBots", "won", "two Daytime Emmy Awards for writing and directing"],["A StoryBots Christmas", "holiday special of", "Ask the StoryBots"],["A StoryBots Christmas", "won", "two Daytime Emmy Awards"],["Ask the StoryBots", "translated into", "22 languages"],["Ask the StoryBots", "available for streaming on Netflix in", "190 countries"],["Third season of Ask the StoryBots", "premiere date", "August 2, 2019"],["Trailer for new episodes of Ask the StoryBots", "launched on", "YouTube"]]
Henry Stuart Carter or H. Stuart Carter (September 5, 1910 –September 17, 1985) was a Virginia lawyer, who served part-time for a dozen years representing Bristol, Virginia and Washington County in the Virginia House of Delegates. A member of the Byrd Organization, Carter participated in its Massive Resistance to racial integration. <S> [["Henry Stuart Carter", "profession", "Lawyer"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "birth date", "September 5, 1910"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "death date", "September 17, 1985"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "location", "Virginia"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "political affiliation", "Byrd Organization"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "role", "Representative for Bristol, Virginia and Washington County in Virginia House of Delegates"], ["Henry Stuart Carter", "involvement", "Massive Resistance to racial integration"]]
