Metlan Khairabad is a village in Bhulath Tehsil in Kapurthala district of Punjab State, India. It is located from Bhulath, away from district headquarter Kapurthala. The village is administrated by a Sarpanch who is an elected representative. <S> [["Metlan Khairabad", "instance of", "Village"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "located in", "Bhulath Tehsil"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "located in", "Kapurthala district"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "located in", "Punjab State, India"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "distance from", "Bhulath"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "distance from", "Kapurthala"], ["Metlan Khairabad", "administered by", "Sarpanch"], ["Sarpanch", "role", "Elected representative"]]
The Chantry Island Lighthouse, officially known as Chantry Island Lightstation Tower, is a lightstation on Chantry Island, off the coast of Southampton, Ontario in Lake Huron. It was constructed in the years 1855 through to 1859, by John Brown of Thorold, Ontario, under the authority of the Province of Canada and is recognized as one of the six Imperial Towers. Virtually identical, they were completed in 1858-1859 on Lake Huron and Georgian Bay and are among the few lighthouses on the Great Lakes made of cut limestone and granite (not brick, metal, wood or concrete).This lighthouse was planned in about 1850 because underwater shoals of massive granite boulders made navigation in the area dangerous. There are many accounts from the 1800s on of disasters and lost lives in this area of Lake Huron. The first beacon on the island (1857) was provided by a temporary fixed light which was replaced by the tower. The actual lighthouse was first lit on 1 April 1859. Valuable in its day, it still emits a bright beam, but now, buoys and modern navigational tools are more important for safe navigation.The tower and the keeper's dwelling have been extensively restored. The dwelling is listed on the Canadian Register of Historic Places while the Lightstation Tower is listed on the National Historic Sites of Canada. However, because the island is a bird sanctuary, only one company has a license to offer tours of the property and only on a limited basis. All other access to the island is prohibited. <S> [["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "instance of", "Lightstation"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "located in", "Chantry Island"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "located off the coast of", "Southampton, Ontario"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "located in", "Lake Huron"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "constructed by", "John Brown"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "constructed in", "1855-1859"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "recognized as", "Imperial Tower"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "made of", "cut limestone and granite"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "first lit on", "1 April 1859"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "listed on", "National Historic Sites of Canada"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "restricted access due to", "bird sanctuary"], ["Chantry Island Lighthouse", "restored by", "unknown company"]]
Emirates Flight 521 was a scheduled international passenger flight from Thiruvananthapuram, India, to Dubai, United Arab Emirates, operated by Emirates using a Boeing 777-300. On 3 August 2016, the aircraft carrying 282 passengers and 18 crew crashed while landing at Dubai International Airport.All 300 people on board survived the accident; 32 were injured, 4 were seriously injured. An airport firefighter died during the rescue operation and another 7 were injured. The accident is the only hull loss of an Emirates aircraft. <S> [["Emirates Flight 521", "instance of", "Scheduled international passenger flight"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "origin", "Thiruvananthapuram, India"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "destination", "Dubai, United Arab Emirates"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "operator", "Emirates"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "aircraft", "Boeing 777-300"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "incident date", "3 August 2016"], ["Emirates Flight 521", "passengers", 282], ["Emirates Flight 521", "crew", 18], ["Emirates Flight 521", "survivors", 300], ["Emirates Flight 521", "injured", 32], ["Emirates Flight 521", "seriously injured", 4], ["Emirates Flight 521", "airport firefighter died", 1], ["Emirates Flight 521", "rescue operation injuries", 7], ["Emirates Flight 521", "hull loss", "Emirates aircraft"]]
Jean-Joseph Rive (19 May 1730 – 20 October 1791) was an 18th-century French bibliographer, librarian and revolutionary leader. <S> [["Jean-Joseph Rive", "occupation", "Bibliographer"], ["Jean-Joseph Rive", "occupation", "Librarian"], ["Jean-Joseph Rive", "occupation", "Revolutionary leader"], ["Jean-Joseph Rive", "birth date", "19 May 1730"], ["Jean-Joseph Rive", "death date", "20 October 1791"], ["Jean-Joseph Rive", "nationality", "French"]]
Bonnie Burton (born July 12, 1972) is a San Francisco-based author, journalist, comedian, actress, and show host. She is best known for arts & crafts books like "The Star Wars Craft Book," and appearances on web series including "Geek DIY" on Stan Lee's "World of Heroes" YouTube channel, "Ask Bonnie," Wil Wheaton's "TableTop," and Felicia Day's "Vaginal Fantasy Book Club." She is the former Senior Editor and Social Media Strategist at StarWars.com for Lucasfilm and was staff writer for "Star Wars Insider" magazine for 10 years. She works as a freelance writer with a specialty in writing about topics for young child and teen audiences. <S> [["Bonnie Burton", "profession", "Author"], ["Bonnie Burton", "profession", "Journalist"], ["Bonnie Burton", "profession", "Comedian"], ["Bonnie Burton", "profession", "Actress"], ["Bonnie Burton", "profession", "Show host"], ["Bonnie Burton", "birth date", "July 12, 1972"], ["Bonnie Burton", "location", "San Francisco"], ["Bonnie Burton", "known for", "The Star Wars Craft Book"], ["Bonnie Burton", "appearance on", "Geek DIY"], ["Bonnie Burton", "appearance on", "Ask Bonnie"], ["Bonnie Burton", "appearance on", "TableTop"], ["Bonnie Burton", "appearance on", "Vaginal Fantasy Book Club"], ["Bonnie Burton", "former position", "Senior Editor at StarWars.com"], ["Bonnie Burton", "former position", "Social Media Strategist at Lucasfilm"], ["Bonnie Burton", "former position", "Staff writer at Star Wars Insider magazine"], ["Bonnie Burton", "specialty", "Writing for young child and teen audiences"]]
God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single) is a 2012 single by Pete Seeger featuring Lorre Wyatt & Friends, produced and arranged by Richard Barone and Matthew Billy, and released by Billy Barone Productions. Originally recorded in 2010 aboard the Hudson River Sloop Clearwater, the song was written immediately after that year's massive BP Oil Spill in the Gulf of Mexico. The spill is referenced in the lyrics. It was Seeger's final single release.The recording session was filmed live aboard the Sloop, while sailing up and down the Hudson River. The music video, directed by Damien Drake, can be viewed on YouTube: It is one of the few, in not only music video sanctioned and planned with Seeger and filmed especially to accompany one of his songs. The single is available for download on iTunes, Amazon.com, and all digital retailers.The song and video were released on Election Day, November 6, 2012. <S> [["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "instance of", "Single"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "artist", "Pete Seeger"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "featuring", "Lorre Wyatt & Friends"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "producer", "Richard Barone"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "arranger", "Matthew Billy"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "released by", "Billy Barone Productions"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "recorded in", "2010"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "location", "Hudson River Sloop Clearwater"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "written after", "BP Oil Spill in the Gulf of Mexico"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "final release by", "Pete Seeger"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "filmed aboard", "Hudson River Sloop"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "director of music video", "Damien Drake"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "available for download on", "iTunes, Amazon.com, and all digital retailers"], ["God's Counting on Me, God's Counting on You (Single)", "release date", "November 6, 2012"]]
The 30th Filmfare Awards were held on 25 September 1983."Prem Rog" led the ceremony with 12 nominations, followed by "Nikaah" with 11 nominations, and "Bazaar" and "Shakti" with 7 nominations each."Prem Rog" and "Shakti" won 4 awards each, thus becoming the most-awarded films at the ceremony – with the former winning Best Director for Raj Kapoor and Best Actress for Padmini Kolhapure, and the latter winning Best Film and Best Actor for Dilip Kumar.Dilip Kumar won Best Actor for a record 8th time for his performance in "Shakti." <S> [["30th Filmfare Awards", "date", "25 September 1983"], ["30th Filmfare Awards", "most awarded films", "Prem Rog"], ["30th Filmfare Awards", "most awarded films", "Shakti"], ["Prem Rog", "nominations", 12], ["Nikaah", "nominations", 11], ["Bazaar", "nominations", 7], ["Shakti", "nominations", 7], ["Prem Rog", "awards won", 4], ["Shakti", "awards won", 4], ["Prem Rog", "Best Director", "Raj Kapoor"], ["Prem Rog", "Best Actress", "Padmini Kolhapure"], ["Shakti", "Best Film", "Yes"], ["Shakti", "Best Actor", "Dilip Kumar"], ["Dilip Kumar", "Best Actor wins", 8]]
Rachel Berger is an Australian comedian, actress, and writer. Berger was born in Israel to Polish Jewish parents and emigrated to Melbourne at the age of five.She is a "performer who delivers rapid-fire lines with assertive and acerbic virtuosity," who has made her name as a stand-up comedian, staging "confronting and politically incorrect" productions including "Perfect", "Clenched Buttocks", "Loose Cannon", "The She Comic", "Comedy Siren", and "Berger Republic".In 2008, Berger wrote and performed "Hold the Pickle". A major departure from her previous work, "Hold the Pickle" is a monologue that traces her parents' flight from Nazi-occupied Poland to Israel during the Second World War, to running a delicatessen in Acland Street, St Kilda, a Melbourne suburb.In 2008, "Hold the Pickle" was nominated for three Green Room Awards: Best Female Performer in an Independent Theatre Production, New Writing for the Australian Stage, and Lighting Design.In 2010, Berger was cast as Cora in the Australian Production of "Calendar Girls", which toured for four months.Berger provided the UK voice of Calimero in the 2013 reboot of the same name.Berger is the author of "Whaddya Mean You're Allergic to Rubber?" (Penguin Books, 2001) and regularly co-hosts "The Conversation Hour" with Jon Faine on Radio 774 ABC in Melbourne. <S> [    ["Rachel Berger", "instance of", "Comedian"],    ["Rachel Berger", "instance of", "Actress"],    ["Rachel Berger", "instance of", "Writer"],    ["Rachel Berger", "birth place", "Israel"],    ["Rachel Berger", "ethnicity", "Polish Jewish"],    ["Rachel Berger", "emigrated to", "Melbourne"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Perfect"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Clenched Buttocks"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Loose Cannon"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "The She Comic"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Comedy Siren"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Berger Republic"],    ["Rachel Berger", "notable works", "Hold the Pickle"],    ["Hold the Pickle", "year", 2008],    ["Hold the Pickle", "nominated for", "Best Female Performer in an Independent Theatre Production"],    ["Hold the Pickle", "nominated for", "New Writing for the Australian Stage"],    ["Hold the Pickle", "nominated for", "Lighting Design"],    ["Rachel Berger", "cast as", "Cora"],    ["Cora", "in", "Australian Production of Calendar Girls"],    ["Calendar Girls", "toured for", "four months"],    ["Rachel Berger", "provided voice for", "Calimero"],    ["Calimero", "rebooted in", 2013],    ["Rachel Berger", "author of", "Whaddya Mean You're Allergic to Rubber?"],    ["Whaddya Mean You're Allergic to Rubber?", "publisher", "Penguin Books"],    ["Rachel Berger", "co-hosts", "The Conversation Hour"],    ["The Conversation Hour", "with", "Jon Faine"],    ["The Conversation Hour", "on", "Radio 774 ABC"],    ["Radio 774 ABC", "location", "Melbourne"]]
Puthanathani is a city in Malappuram district in the state of Kerala, India. The town lies on the National Highway 66 (India), between Kottakkal and Valanchery. Roads to Vailathur (and hence Tirur) and Thirunavaya also can be seen in Puthanathani. <S> [["Puthanathani", "instance of", "City"], ["Puthanathani", "located in", "Malappuram district"], ["Malappuram district", "located in", "Kerala, India"], ["Puthanathani", "located on", "National Highway 66 (India)"], ["National Highway 66 (India)", "connects", "Kottakkal"], ["National Highway 66 (India)", "connects", "Valanchery"], ["Puthanathani", "roads to", "Vailathur"], ["Vailathur", "connects to", "Tirur"], ["Puthanathani", "roads to", "Thirunavaya"]]
Safaripark Beekse Bergen is the largest wildlife zoo of the Benelux region and provides a home to approximately 1,250 animals from over 150 species, varying from small mammals to large birds. It is located between the cities of Tilburg and Hilvarenbeek in the south of the Netherlands. The visitors can for instance watch zebras and giraffes on the spacious savannahs. Safaripark Beekse Bergen offers the possibility to explore the park on numerous safaris: walksafari, carsafari, bussafari and boatsafari.The park is owned by the company Libéma Exploitatie BV, which is one of the largest leisure-related companies in the Netherlands.What makes the park so special is that visitors can explore the park with their own car, without a fence in between the visitor and the animals. While driving through the park people can for instance encounter leopards and zebras or get their car 'washed' by a giraffe. In this way the visitor can imagine that they are really taking a safari in Africa. Visitors can also choose to follow the same route per bus. In this way they will get to know more information about the animals, since they will be joined by a Ranger.Besides these two ways of exploring the park, the visitor can also choose to take a boat, that plies between two piers in the park. The visitors can also watch the animals by foot on the approximately 5 kilometres of roads throughout the park.All of the above-mentioned safari possibilities can be combined. All the safaris start at the front of the park and come together at a parking side at the backside of the park, close to the Kongorestaurant.Another feature of the park for which it is very well known is its bird show. In this show full of humour and interesting facts all sorts of birds are shown to the audience.All animals receive a strict diet, as a result of which feeding the animals is prohibited. <S> [    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "instance of", "Wildlife zoo"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "located in", "Netherlands"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "size", "largest in Benelux region"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "home to", "1,250 animals"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "home to", "over 150 species"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "owned by", "Libéma Exploitatie BV"],    ["Libéma Exploitatie BV", "type", "leisure-related company"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "unique feature", "visitors can explore with own car"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari options", "walksafari"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari options", "carsafari"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari options", "bussafari"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari options", "boatsafari"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari routes start at", "front of the park"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "safari routes end at", "parking side at the back of the park"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "special feature", "bird show"],    ["Safaripark Beekse Bergen", "feeding animals", "prohibited"]]
Dimitar Kapinkovski (; born 27 May 1975) is a retired Macedonian football player and current coach, which was recently managed FK Pelister as interim coach. <S> [["Dimitar Kapinkovski", "instance of", "Football player"], ["Dimitar Kapinkovski", "instance of", "Coach"], ["Dimitar Kapinkovski", "country of citizenship", "Macedonia"], ["Dimitar Kapinkovski", "date of birth", "27 May 1975"], ["Dimitar Kapinkovski", "managed", "FK Pelister"], ["FK Pelister", "type", "Football club"], ["FK Pelister", "position", "Interim coach"]]
The Cheltenham Badlands are located in Caledon, Ontario on the south east side of Olde Base Line Road, between Creditview and Chinguacousy Roads. The site occupies an area of approximately 0.4 square kilometers and features exposed and highly eroded Queenston Shale. The Cheltenham Badlands are a significant educational site due to the readily visible geologic processes and the red color and the unique topography of the exposed shale makes this a popular tourist site. The site is a Provincial Earth Sciences Area of Natural and Scientific Interest (ANSI) since it is considered as one of the best examples of "badlands topography" in Ontario. <S> [["Cheltenham Badlands", "location", "Caledon, Ontario"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "area", "0.4 square kilometers"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "features", "exposed Queenston Shale"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "educational site", "yes"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "tourist site", "yes"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "designation", "Provincial Earth Sciences Area of Natural and Scientific Interest (ANSI)"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "geologic processes", "readily visible"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "topography", "unique"], ["Queenston Shale", "location", "Cheltenham Badlands"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "example of", "badlands topography"], ["Cheltenham Badlands", "color", "red"]]
The Saurashtra people, or Saurashtrians, are an Indo-Aryan ethno-linguistic Hindu community of South India who speak the Saurashtra language, an Indo-Aryan language, and predominantly reside in the Indian states of Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Andhra Pradesh and Karnataka.Saurashtrians trace their ancestry to the historical region of Saurashtra in Western India. Their migration to Southern India owes to the forays and desecration of the Somnath temple triggered by the frequent Muslim invasions, most notably by Mahmud Ghazni. They were a prominent industrious and prosperous mercantile community of merchants and weavers in southern India until the 20th century.Saurashtrians are Brahmins, and are also referred to as Saurashtra Brahmins. Further, like all traditional orthodox Brahmins, they are classified based on their gotra, or patrilineal descent. The majority of the people are Vaishnavas, though there is a significant proportion of Shaivas as well. They are prominently known by their unique family names and also use the titles Sharma, Rao, Iyer, Iyengar and Achary as their surnames but belong to linguistic minorities. <S> [["Saurashtra people", "ethnicity", "Indo-Aryan"],["Saurashtra people", "religion", "Hindu"],["Saurashtra people", "language", "Saurashtra language"],["Saurashtra people", "reside in", "Tamil Nadu"],["Saurashtra people", "reside in", "Kerala"],["Saurashtra people", "reside in", "Andhra Pradesh"],["Saurashtra people", "reside in", "Karnataka"],["Saurashtra people", "ancestry", "Saurashtra region"],["Saurashtra people", "migration reason", "Muslim invasions"],["Saurashtra people", "occupation", "merchants"],["Saurashtra people", "occupation", "weavers"],["Saurashtra people", "religion", "Vaishnavas"],["Saurashtra people", "religion", "Shaivas"],["Saurashtra people", "Brahmins", "Saurashtra Brahmins"],["Saurashtra people", "classification", "gotra"],["Saurashtra people", "family names", "unique"],["Saurashtra people", "surnames", "Sharma"],["Saurashtra people", "surnames", "Rao"],["Saurashtra people", "surnames", "Iyer"],["Saurashtra people", "surnames", "Iyengar"],["Saurashtra people", "surnames", "Achary"],["Saurashtra people", "linguistic minorities", "yes"]]
Team Differdange–Geba () is a continental cycling team, based in Luxembourg. The team participates in UCI Continental Circuits races. <S> [["Team Differdange-Geba", "instance of", "Cycling team"], ["Team Differdange-Geba", "country", "Luxembourg"], ["Team Differdange-Geba", "participates in", "UCI Continental Circuits races"]]
Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra (born 20 January 1974) is the current Crown Prince (Tengku Mahkota) of the Malaysian state of Kelantan. He was proclaimed as the Crown Prince of Kelantan on 18 October 2010 upon the accession of his elder brother, Sultan Muhammad V as the 29th Sultan of Kelantan.He is the second of four children of the late Sultan of Kelantan, Sultan Ismail Petra and Raja Perempuan Tengku Anis. His two younger siblings are Tengku Muhammad Fakhry Petra and Tengku Amalin Aishah Putri. His eldest brother is the Sultan of Kelantan, Sultan Muhammad V, the fifteenth Yang di-Pertuan Agong of Malaysia. <S> [["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "instance of", "Crown Prince"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "birth date", "20 January 1974"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "state", "Kelantan"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "siblings", "Tengku Muhammad Fakhry Petra"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "siblings", "Tengku Amalin Aishah Putri"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "parents", "Sultan Ismail Petra"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "parents", "Raja Perempuan Tengku Anis"], ["Tengku Muhammad Fa-iz Petra ibni Almarhum Sultan Ismail Petra", "elder brother", "Sultan Muhammad V"], ["Sultan Muhammad V", "position", "Sultan of Kelantan"], ["Sultan Muhammad V", "position", "Yang di-Pertuan Agong of Malaysia"]]
Michael R. Fuljenz (born 1954) is a numismatist, author, and businessman. He is currently the president of Universal Coin & Bullion, a precious metals trading company located in Beaumont, Texas. <S> [["Michael R. Fuljenz", "profession", "Numismatist"], ["Michael R. Fuljenz", "profession", "Author"], ["Michael R. Fuljenz", "profession", "Businessman"], ["Michael R. Fuljenz", "birth year", "1954"], ["Michael R. Fuljenz", "current position", "President of Universal Coin & Bullion"], ["Universal Coin & Bullion", "industry", "Precious metals trading"], ["Universal Coin & Bullion", "location", "Beaumont, Texas"]]
The Virtuous Scoundrel (), is a French comedy drama film from 1953, directed and written by Sacha Guitry, and starring Michel Simon and Louis de Funès. <S> [["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "instance of", "French comedy drama film"], ["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "director", "Sacha Guitry"], ["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "writer", "Sacha Guitry"], ["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "starring", "Michel Simon"], ["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "starring", "Louis de Funès"], ["The Virtuous Scoundrel", "year", 1953]]
Jaroslav Benda (27 April 1882 - January 12, 1970 in Prague) was Czech painter, graphic artist, author, designer of postage stamps and posters, monumental decorations. His contributions significantly affected the development of Czech book graphics.He graduated from the School of Applied Arts in Prague. From 1907-1912 he was an editor of the magazine "Světozor". He was advisor to publishers, Jan Laichtr and Jan Štenc for the proposed modification of individual books. From 1920 he was Professor of Applied Arts at the School of Applied Arts. In the years 1926-1928 he was the rector. His students included Zdeněk Seydl, Jaroslav Šváb, Antonín Strnadel, Jiří Trnka and Antonín Homolka. <S> [["Jaroslav Benda", "occupation", "Painter"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "occupation", "Graphic artist"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "occupation", "Author"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "occupation", "Designer"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "occupation", "Professor"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "birth date", "27 April 1882"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "death date", "12 January 1970"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "place of birth", "Prague"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "education", "School of Applied Arts in Prague"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "editor of", "Světozor"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "advisor to", "Jan Laichtr"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "advisor to", "Jan Štenc"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "students", "Zdeněk Seydl"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "students", "Jaroslav Šváb"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "students", "Antonín Strnadel"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "students", "Jiří Trnka"], ["Jaroslav Benda", "students", "Antonín Homolka"]]
The Perfect Circle (Bosnian: Savršeni krug) is a 1997 Bosnian film by Ademir Kenović set in Sarajevo during the siege of 1992-1996. It was written by Kenović with Pjer Žalica and Abdulah Sidran. The title derives from the ability of "Hamza" (played by Mustafa Nadarević) to draw perfect circles on paper. <S> [["The Perfect Circle", "instance of", "Film"], ["The Perfect Circle", "language", "Bosnian"], ["The Perfect Circle", "title", "Savršeni krug"], ["The Perfect Circle", "year", "1997"], ["The Perfect Circle", "director", "Ademir Kenović"], ["The Perfect Circle", "setting", "Sarajevo"], ["The Perfect Circle", "event", "Siege of 1992-1996"], ["The Perfect Circle", "writer", "Ademir Kenović"], ["The Perfect Circle", "writer", "Pjer Žalica"], ["The Perfect Circle", "writer", "Abdulah Sidran"], ["The Perfect Circle", "character", "Hamza"], ["Hamza", "actor", "Mustafa Nadarević"], ["Hamza", "ability", "draw perfect circles on paper"]]
The Egypt national rugby union team represents Egypt in rugby union. The national team was put together after the separation of the Arabian Gulf national rugby union team.In September 2011, the under 20 Egyptian rugby national team traveled to Lebanon to play two matches against the Lebanon's national team. Egypt won both matches with scores of 51-5 and 14 10.The captain of the team is Ahmed Elmohamady. <S> [["Egypt national rugby union team", "represents", "Egypt"], ["Egypt national rugby union team", "sport", "rugby union"], ["Egypt national rugby union team", "captain", "Ahmed Elmohamady"], ["Egypt national rugby union team", "formed after", "separation of Arabian Gulf national rugby union team"], ["under 20 Egyptian rugby national team", "travelled to", "Lebanon"], ["under 20 Egyptian rugby national team", "played matches against", "Lebanon's national team"], ["Egypt", "won", "both matches against Lebanon's national team with scores of 51-5 and 14-10"]]
James Leroy Wright Sr. (May 6, 1938 – March 21, 2020) was an American professional basketball player. He played two seasons in the American Basketball Association (ABA) in 1967–68 and 1968–69, winning the ABA Finals in 1968 as a member of the Pittsburgh Pipers. <S> [["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "instance of", "Professional basketball player"], ["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "country", "United States"], ["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "played in", "American Basketball Association"], ["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "seasons played", "2"], ["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "ABA Finals winner", "1968"], ["James Leroy Wright Sr.", "team member", "Pittsburgh Pipers"]]
